ms-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=July 24, 2019}}</ref>\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=[https://www.census.gov/prod/www/abs/decennial/ U.S. Decennial Census]\n}}\n\nAs of the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]],<ref name =\"FactFinder\">{{cite web|title=American FactFinder|url=http://factfinder2.census.gov/faces/nav/jsf/pages/index.xhtml|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]}}</ref> there were 26,658 people, 9,071 households, and 6,355 families residing in the city. The [[population density]] was 3,136.2 people per square mile (1,210.9/km\u00b2). There were 9,656 housing units at an average density of 1,136.0 per square mile (436.9/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the city was 74.7% [[White American|White]], 4.4% [[Asian American|Asian]], 2.8% [[African American]], 0.9% [[Native Americans in the United States|American Indian]], 14.2% from some other race, and 2.9% from two or more races. [[Hispanic and Latino Americans|Hispanics and Latinos]] of any race comprised 48.6% of the population.<ref name=Census2010/>\n\nThere were 9,071 households of which 43.1% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 49.6% were married couples living together, 6.5% had a male householder with no wife present, 13.9% had a female householder with no husband present, and 29.9% were non-families. 24.0% of all households were made up of individuals, and 19.3% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.88, and the average family size was 3.45.<ref name=Census2010/>\n\nThe median age was 29.9 years. 31.2% of residents were under the age of 18; 11.6% were between ages 18 and 24; 26.0% were between 25 and 44; 22.2% were between 45 and 64; and 9.0% were 65 years of age or older. The gender makeup of the population was 49.8% male and 50.2% female.<ref name=Census2010/>\n\nThe median income for a household in the city was $47,975, and the median income for a family was $54,621. Males had a median income of $33,873 versus $27,304 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $20,066. About 7.1% of families and 12.5% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 18.5% of those under age 18 and 6.0% of those age 65 or over.<ref name=Census2010/>\n\n===Ethnic groups===\nIn 2017, Albert Kyaw, a translator of the [[Garden City Public Schools]], stated that Garden City was the most ethnically diverse community in the state of Kansas. That year, according to Frank Morris of [[National Public Radio]], \"some say\" the residents may speak up to 40 different languages; at least 27 were spoken.<ref name=MorrisGardenCity>{{cite web|author=Morris, Frank|url=https://www.npr.org/2017/02/19/516016940/a-thriving-rural-towns-winning-formula-faces-new-threats-under-trump-administrat|title=A Thriving Rural Town's Winning Formula Faces New Threats Under Trump Administration|publisher=[[National Public Radio]]|date=2017-02-19|accessdate=2017-02-25}}</ref>\n\nHispanics and Latinos, including immigrants, came to Garden City beginning in the 1980s due to the establishment of meatpacking plants and partially due to plant management deliberately recruiting them. Many educational institutions for adults were teaching Hispanic immigrants after they had asked for amnesty for having illegally immigrated.<ref name=BensonKansas>Benson, Janet E. ([[Kansas State University]]). \"[https://migration.ucdavis.edu/cf/more.php?id=157 Garden City: Meatpacking and Immigration to the High Plains -- Dr. Janet E. Benson].\" [[University of California, Davis]]. Retrieved on February 25, 2017.</ref>\n\nAfter the [[Fall of Saigon]] in 1975 immigrants from southeast Asia began coming to Garden City. Garden City Catholics sponsored an initial group of Vietnamese immigrants that year. More Vietnamese came in the 1980s during a wave of immigration, and [[Lao American|Lao]] people also came with them. Dr. Janet E. Benson of [[Kansas State University]] stated that perhaps about half had originated from [[Wichita, Kansas|Wichita]] since they had lost work during industry layoffs there. The second group of Vietnamese were less educated than the first, and they were more likely to be Buddhist as opposed to being Christian. In their home country they had originally done agricultural and/or fishing work. By the late 1980s many Mexican immigrants replaced Vietnamese immigrants who had moved away from Garden City and stopped doing meatpacking work since they had made sufficient money.<ref name=BensonKansas/>\n\n==Economy==\n[[File:Garden City, KS, grain elevator IMG 5871.JPG|thumb|Garden City [[Cooperative]] [[grain elevator]] (2010)]]\nThe economy of Garden City is driven largely by agriculture. There are several feedlots and [[grain elevator]]s located in and around the city. Additionally, an ethanol plant, Bonanza Bioenergy was built in 2007 by Conestoga Energy Partners which uses 19.6 million bushels of grain.<ref name=\"ethanol\">{{cite web| title =Kansas Ethanol| url =http://www.ksgrains.com/ethanol/kseth.html| format =English| accessdate =2010-05-29| url-status =dead| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20090501134504/http://www.ksgrains.com/ethanol/kseth.html| archivedate =2009-05-01}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2012, 73.9% of the population over the age of 16 was in the labor force. 0.0% was in the armed forces, and 73.9% was in the civilian labor force with 71.5% being employed and 2.4% unemployed. The composition, by occupation, of the employed civilian labor force was: 23.8% in production, transportation, and material moving; 23.5% in management, business, science, and arts; 21.9% in sales and office occupations; 19.2% in service occupations; and 11.5% in natural resources, construction, and maintenance. The industries employing the largest percentages of the working civilian labor force were educational services, health care, and social assistance (20.4%); manufacturing (19.3%); and retail trade (15.0%).<ref name=Census2010/>\n\nThe cost of living in Garden City is relatively low; compared to a U.S. average of 100, the cost of living index for the city is 81.6.<ref name=CityData>{{cite web | title = Garden City, Kansas | publisher = City-Data.com | url = http://www.city-data.com/city/Garden-City-Kansas.html | accessdate = 2014-01-14}}</ref> As of 2012, the median home value in the city was $103,400, the median selected monthly owner cost was $1,159 for housing units with a mortgage and $455 for those without, and the median gross rent was $665.<ref name=Census2010/>\n\n===Top employers===\n[[Image:Finney County, Kansas courthouse from E 1.JPG|thumb|Finney County Courthouse (2015)]]\nAccording to Garden City's 2012 Comprehensive Annual Financial Report,<ref>[http://www.garden-city.org/DocumentCenter/View/969 City of Garden City CAFR] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151218185955/http://www.garden-city.org/DocumentCenter/View/969 |date=2015-12-18 }}</ref> the top employers in the city are:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n! #\n! Employer\n! # of employees\n|-\n| 1\n| [[Tyson Foods]]\n| 2,200\n|-\n|2\n| Unified School District 457\n| 1,200\n|-\n|3\n| Cheyenne Drilling \n| 638\n|-\n|4\n| St. Catherine Hospital \n| 635\n|-\n|5\n| [[Garden City Community College]]\n| 385\n|-\n|6\n| [[Walmart]] \n| 372\n|-\n|7\n| [[Finney County, Kansas|Finney County]]\n| 330\n|-\n|8\n| City of Garden City\n| 303\n|-\n|9\n| [[Beef Products]]\n| 245\n|-\n|10\n| Sunflower Electric Power Corporation\n| 225\n|}\n\n==Government==\n[[File:City Hall, Garden City, KS IMG 5946.JPG|thumb|Garden City Administrative Center (2010)]]\nGarden City is a [[Kansas#Important cities and towns|city of the first class]] with a [[council-manager government|commission-manager]] form of government.<ref name=LKM>{{cite web|title=Garden City |work=Directory of Kansas Public Officials |publisher=The League of Kansas Municipalities |url=http://www.lkm.org/directory/cities.php?ID=163 |accessdate=2014-01-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140815063157/http://www.lkm.org/directory/cities.php?ID=163 |archivedate=2014-08-15 }}</ref> The [[city commission]] consists of five commissioners elected [[plurality-at-large voting|at-large]]. It meets on the first and third Tuesday of each month. The commission sets goals and policy for the city, approves the city budget, and directs the [[city manager]]. Annually, the commission selects one member to serve as [[Mayor#United States|mayor]] who then presides over commission meetings.<ref>{{cite web | title = City Commission | publisher = City of Garden City, Kansas | url = http://www.garden-city.org/index.aspx?nid=195 | accessdate = 2014-01-22 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140831032201/http://www.garden-city.org/index.aspx?nid=195 | archivedate = 2014-08-31 }}</ref> The city manager implements policies set by the commission and administers the city's operations, departments, and employees.<ref>{{cite web | title = City Manager | publisher = City of Garden City, Kansas | url = http://www.garden-city.org/index.aspx?nid=85 | accessdate = 2014-01-22 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140830135148/http://www.garden-city.org/index.aspx?nid=85 | archivedate = 2014-08-30 }}</ref>\n\nAs the [[county seat]], Garden City is the administrative center of Finney County. The [[county courthouse]] is downtown, and all departments of the county government base their operations in the city.<ref>{{cite web | title = Departments | publisher = Finney County, Kansas | url = http://www.finneycounty.org/index.aspx?NID=8 | accessdate = 2014-01-22}}</ref>\n\nGarden City lies within [[Kansas's 1st congressional district|Kansas's 1st U.S. Congressional District]]. For the purposes of representation in the [[Kansas Legislature]], the city is located in the 39th district of the [[Kansas Senate]] and the 122nd and 123rd districts of the [[Kansas House of Representatives]].<ref name=LKM/>\n\n==Education==\n[[Garden City Public Schools]] operates the public schools. [[Garden City High School (Kansas)|Garden City High School]] is the local and only high school in Garden City.\n\n[[Garden City Community College]] (GCCC) is a fully accredited community college. GCCC is a member of the [[Kansas Jayhawk Community College Conference]] (KJCCC), one of the conferences in the [[National Junior College Athletic Association]] (NJCAA).\n\n==Infrastructure==\n===Transportation===\n[[File:Garden City (Amtrak station) in 2008.jpg|right|thumb|[[Garden City (Amtrak station)|Amtrak]] station in Garden City (2008)]]\n[[U.S. Route 50 in Kansas|U.S. Route 50]] and [[U.S. Route 400 in Kansas|U.S. Route 400]], both east-west highways, meet [[U.S. Route 83 in Kansas|U.S. Route 83]], a north-south highway, in the southeast part of the city. A U.S. 50 [[business route]] continues west from the intersection into the city. U.S. 50, U.S. 400, and U.S. 83 run [[concurrency (road)|concurrently]] around the city's eastern and northern fringe. Northwest of the city, U.S. 50 and U.S. 400 continue west while U.S. 83 turns north. South of the city, a U.S. 83 business route splits off from the main highway and enters the city as Main Street. Downtown, it intersects the U.S. 50 business route, and the two run concurrently north out of the city, terminating northwest of the city at the junction of U.S. 50 and U.S. 83. Garden City is also the western terminus of [[K-156 (Kansas highway)|K-156]] which enters the city from the northeast.  Garden City was located on the [[National Old Trails Road]], also known as the Ocean-to-Ocean Highway, that was established in 1912.\n\nFinney County Transit operates CityLink, a [[public transport bus service]] with four routes in the city, as well as a [[minibus]] [[paratransit]] service.<ref>{{cite web | title = Transportation | publisher = Senior Center of Finney County | url = http://www.seniorcenterfc.com/transportation.html | accessdate = 2010-09-16}}</ref>  Bus service is provided daily eastward towards [[Wichita, Kansas]] by BeeLine Express (subcontractor of [[Greyhound Lines]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.beeline-express.com/|title=Beeline Express|first=beeline-express|last=info@beeline-express.com|date=|website=www.beeline-express.com|accessdate=22 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.greyhound.com/|title=Home|author=|date=|website=www.greyhound.com|accessdate=22 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190906232014/https://www.greyhound.com/|archive-date=6 September 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n[[Garden City Regional Airport]] is located approximately {{convert|8|mi|km}} southeast of the city. Used primarily for [[general aviation]], it is connected to the [[American Airlines]] network via [[American Eagle Airlines|American Eagle]] regional service to [[Dallas/Fort Worth International Airport]] under the [[Essential Air Service]] program.\n\nThree rail lines serve Garden City: the [[La Junta Subdivision]] of the [[BNSF Railway]], which runs southeast-northwest, and the two lines of the [[Garden City Western Railway]], of which the city is the southern and eastern terminus.<ref>{{cite web | title = Kansas Operating Division | publisher = [[BNSF Railway]] | date = 2009-01-01 | url = http://www.bnsf.com/customers/pdf/maps/div_ks.pdf | accessdate = 2010-09-16 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110325001559/http://www.bnsf.com/customers/pdf/maps/div_ks.pdf | archivedate = 2011-03-25 }}</ref> [[Amtrak]] uses the La Junta Subdivision to provide passenger rail service; [[Garden City (Amtrak station)|Garden City]] is a stop on the ''[[Southwest Chief]]'' line.\n\n===Health care===\nGarden City is served by St. Catherine Hospital. The Southwest Kansas Surgery Center, Heart Center, Cancer Center and Maternal Child Center provide additional employment, as do several other health-related businesses.\n\n==Media==\n[[File:Garden City Telegram newspaper IMG 5948.JPG|thumb|right|The ''[[Garden City Telegram]]'' newspaper office (2010)]]\n{{Main|Media in Garden City, Kansas}}\nThe ''[[Garden City Telegram]]'' is the local newspaper, published six days a week.<ref>{{cite web | title = Garden City Telegram | publisher = Mondo Times | url = http://www.mondotimes.com/1/world/us/16/912/2369 | accessdate = 2011-10-30}}</ref>\n\nAlong with [[Dodge City, Kansas|Dodge City]], Garden City is a center of broadcast media for southwestern Kansas.<ref name=Radio>{{cite web | title = Radio Stations in Garden City, Kansas | publisher = Radio-Locator | url = http://www.radio-locator.com/cgi-bin/locate?select=city&city=Garden+City&state=KS&x=0&y=0 | accessdate = 2011-10-30}}</ref><ref name=Rabbit>{{cite web | title = Stations for Garden City, Kansas | publisher = RabbitEars.Info | url = http://www.rabbitears.info/market.php?request=print_market&mktid=86 | accessdate = 2011-10-30}}</ref> Two [[AM broadcasting|AM]] radio stations and seven [[FM broadcasting|FM]] radio stations, including one of the two flagship stations of [[High Plains Public Radio]], broadcast from the city.<ref name=Radio/><ref>{{cite web | title = Visit HPPR's Studios | publisher = [[High Plains Public Radio]] | url = http://www.hppr.org/hpprstudios.html | accessdate = 2011-10-30 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20111126093012/http://www.hppr.org/hpprstudios.html | archivedate = 2011-11-26 }}</ref>\n\nGarden City is in the [[Media in Wichita, Kansas#Television|Wichita-Hutchinson, Kansas television market]], and four television stations are [[City of license|licensed]] to and/or broadcast from the city.<ref>{{cite web | title = TV Market Maps | publisher = EchoStar Knowledge Base | url = http://dishuser.org/TVMarkets/ | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080820131351/http://www.dishuser.org/TVMarkets/ | url-status = dead | archive-date = 2008-08-20 | accessdate = 2011-10-30 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = TVQ TV Database Query | publisher = [[Federal Communications Commission]] | url = http://www.fcc.gov/fcc-bin/audio/tvq.html | accessdate = 2011-10-30 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090508022231/http://www.fcc.gov/fcc-bin/audio/tvq.html | archivedate = 2009-05-08 }}</ref> These stations include [[NBC]], [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]], and [[Fox Broadcasting Company|FOX]] [[network affiliate]]s, all of which are satellite stations of their respective affiliates in Wichita.<ref name=Rabbit/><ref>{{cite web|title=KSAS Coverage Map |publisher=[[KSAS-TV]] |url=http://www.foxkansas.com/sites/ksas/content/about_us/contact_us/coverage-map-2009.pdf |accessdate=2011-10-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929073749/http://www.foxkansas.com/sites/ksas/content/about_us/contact_us/coverage-map-2009.pdf |archivedate=2011-09-29 }}</ref> The fourth station, [[KGCE-LD]], is a sister station of [[KDGL-LD]] in [[Sublette, Kansas]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kdgltv.com/coverage.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-07-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130811103347/http://www.kdgltv.com/coverage.htm |archivedate=2013-08-11 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcc.gov/encyclopedia/tv-query-broadcast-station-search|title=TV Query Broadcast Station Search|author=|date=10 December 2015|website=fcc.gov|accessdate=22 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Culture==\n===Arts and music===\nGarden City Arts is a non-profit organization dedicated to enriching lives and encouraging creativity through the arts. Its gallery offers 10 to 12 exhibits per year along with internships and educational programming<ref>{{cite web|title=Garden City Arts|url=https://www.facebook.com/GardenCityArts}}</ref>\n\nIn recent years an annual music festival called the Hillside Sessions<ref>{{cite web|title=Hilliside Sessions|url=http://gctelegram.com/search/Hillside-Session-06-02-14|publisher=Garden City Telegram|accessdate=3 June 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140606234433/http://gctelegram.com/search/Hillside-Session-06-02-14|archive-date=6 June 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> has taken place at an historic structure which over the decades has been a barn, an industrial atelier and a dance hall.\n\n===Points of interest===\n[[File:Swimmers in Garden City, KS IMG 5879.JPG|thumb|Swimmers at \"The Big Pool\" on a 100-degree afternoon (2010)]]\n\nInitially named by its developers \"The Big Dipper\", Garden City's \"The Big Pool\" is larger than a 100-yard football field, holds 2.2 million gallons of water and is large enough to accommodate water-skiing. Originally hand-dug in 1922, a bathhouse was added by the [[Works Progress Administration]] during the [[Great Depression]], and local farmers used horse-drawn soil-scrapers to later enlarge the pool. The pool hosts 50-meter Olympic swimming lanes, three water slides, and a children's pool with zero-entry depth. The pool employs a minimum of 14 lifeguards, two slide assistants, three admission clerks, two concession workers and a pool manager on duty each day. Advertised for years as \"The World's Largest, Free, Outdoor, Municipal, Concrete Swimming Pool\", the pool has been known to count up to 2,000 patrons during the summer months. In order to finance improvements made in recent years, an admission fee is now charged.\n\nLocated inside {{convert|110|acre|km2|adj=on}} Finnup Park, the pool is co-located with Finney County Historical Museum and Lee Richardson Zoo, the largest zoological facility in western Kansas, housing more than 300 animals representing 110 species. Walking tours are free to the public; there is a charge for driving into the zoo.\n\nA few miles from Finnup Park, the Big Pool and Lee Richardson Zoo is the Buffalo Game Preserve, with one of the largest herds of bison in the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roadsideamerica.com/tip/21491|title=Garden City, KS - World's Largest Outdoor Municipal Concrete Swimming Pool|author=|date=|website=RoadsideAmerica.com|accessdate=22 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Windsor Hotel (Garden City KS) from NE 1.JPG|thumb|Windsor Hotel (2015)]]\n\nThe [[Windsor Hotel (Garden City, Kansas)|Windsor Hotel]], built downtown in 1887 by John A. Stevens, was known as the \"Waldorf of the Prairies\" because of its lavish quarters. Among its early guests were [[Eddie Foy, Sr.|Eddie Foy]], [[Lillian Russell]], [[Jay Gould]] and [[Buffalo Bill Cody]], who stayed in the presidential suite of the third floor. The Windsor, which closed in 1977, is owned by the Finney County Preservation Alliance. The hotel is four stories high, or about {{convert|50|ft|m|abbr=on}}. tall.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gardencitychamber.net/convention-tourism-bureau/attractions/#windsor|title=Windsor Hotel|publisher=gardencitychamber.net|accessdate=September 3, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100911003341/http://www.gardencitychamber.net/convention-tourism-bureau/attractions/#windsor|archive-date=September 11, 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> The Finney County Preservation Alliance is working with New Communities LLC of Denver, Colorado to renovate the hotel into a 65-room boutique hotel with restaurant and bar on the ground floor.<ref>{{cite news|title=Windsor Hotel, Garden City|url=http://www.kansassampler.org/8wonders/architectureresults.php?id=53|accessdate=4 June 2014|publisher=Kansas Sampler Foundation}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Developers propose new plan for Windsor Hotel|url=http://www.gctelegram.com/news/Windsor-development-10-17-12|accessdate=4 June 2014|publisher=Garden City Telegram|date=17 October 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140606214100/http://www.gctelegram.com/news/Windsor-development-10-17-12|archivedate=6 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n===In popular culture and the arts===\nGarden City is depicted in [[Truman Capote]]'s ''[[In Cold Blood (book)|In Cold Blood]]''.\n\nBillie Jo Spears' 1969 ''Billboard'' country hit song \"Mr. Walker, It's All Over\" is about a young woman from Garden City who moves to New York City to become a big-city secretary and quickly becomes disenchanted.\n\n===Sports===\nGarden City is home to the [[Garden City Wind]] baseball team, which plays in the [[Pecos League]].\n\nGarden City is also home to the [[Garden City High School (Kansas)|Garden City High School]] Buffaloes. The school offers football, basketball, soccer, wrestling, track and field, baseball, softball, tennis, and swimming. Garden City is a part of the 6A level of sports in the state of Kansas. The Buffaloes have had success in wrestling, winning state titles in 2013, 2014, 2015, and 2016. The school has had success in football as well, winning the state championship in 1999.\n\n==Notable people==\n{{main|List of people from Garden City, Kansas}}\n{{See also|Garden_City_Community_College#Notable_alumni|l1=List of Garden City Community College people}}\n<!-- Note:\n\u00b7 Only people who already have a Wikipedia article may appear here. This establishes notability.\n\u00b7 The biographical article must mention how they are associated with Garden City, whether born, raised, or residing.\n\u00b7 The fact of their association should have a reliable source cited.\n\u00b7 Alphabetical by last name, please.\n\u00b7 All others will be deleted without further explanation.\n-->\nNotable individuals who were born in and/or have lived in Garden City include novelist [[Sanora Babb]],<ref>{{cite web | title = Biography: Sanora Babb | publisher = [[University of Texas at Austin]] | url = http://www.hrc.utexas.edu/exhibitions/web/babb/bio/ | accessdate = 2011-10-31}}</ref> jazz pianist [[Frank Mantooth]],<ref>{{cite news | title = Frank Mantooth, 56; Albums Earned 11 Grammy Nominations | newspaper = [[Los Angeles Times]] | date = 2004-02-02 | url = http://articles.latimes.com/2004/feb/02/local/me-passings2.3 | accessdate = 2011-10-31}}</ref> former [[Governor of Colorado]] [[Roy Romer]],<ref>{{cite web | title = Biography of Governor Roy Romer | publisher = Colorado State Archives | date = 1997-05-05 | url = http://www.colorado.gov/dpa/doit/archives/romer/govbio.htm | accessdate = 2011-10-31}}</ref> professional football players [[Thurman \"Fum\" McGraw]] and [[Hal Patterson]] and successful professional boxers [[Victor Ortiz]], Antonio Orozco,and [[Brandon Rios]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Thurman McGraw | website = [[National Football League]] | url = http://www.nfl.com/player/thurmanmcgraw/2520768/profile | accessdate = 2011-10-31}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Hall Patterson |publisher=[[Canadian Football League]] |url=https://www.cfl.ca/page/retroweek_player_hal-patterson |accessdate=2011-10-31 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120712102222/http://www.cfl.ca/page/retroweek_player_hal-patterson |archivedate=2012-07-12 }}</ref>\nJoe Exotic\n\n==Sister cities==\n{{SisterCities|Garden City|two}}\n* {{flagdeco|Costa Rica}} [[Ciudad Quesada]], Costa Rica\n* {{flagdeco|Italy}} [[Oristano]], [[Sardinia]], Italy\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery widths=\"160px\" heights=\"120px\" perrow=\"4\">\nFile:Downtown Garden City, KS IMG_5935.JPG|Downtown Garden City\nFile:Finney County, KS, Public Library IMG_5873.JPG|The Finney County [[Public Library]] in Garden City\nFile:Mark Twain statue, Garden City, KS IMG_5875.JPG|A statue of [[Mark Twain]] at Finney County Library\nFile:Former State Theater, Garden City, KS IMG_5936.JPG|Defunct State Theatre in downtown Garden City\nFile:Community Congregational Church, Garden City, KS IMG_5878.JPG|Community [[Congregational church|Congregational Church]] in Garden City\nFile:St. Thomas' Episcopal Church, Garden City, KS IMG_5872.JPG|St. Thomas' [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopal Church]] in Garden City\nFile:Pleasant Valley School, Garden City, KS IMG_5928.JPG|The former Pleasant Valley School has been relocated to Finnup Park in Garden City.\nFile:Garden City, KS, Western Railway Co. train IMG_5912.JPG|The Garden City Western Railway Company train on display in Finnup Park \n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Kansas}}\n* [[National Register of Historic Places listings in Finney County, Kansas]]\n* [[Santa Fe Trail]]\n* [[National Old Trails Road]]\n\n==References==\n{{PD-old-text|title=Conquest of Southwest Kansas|year=1931|author=Leola Howard Blanchard}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?uid=4556442065221187955&hl=en&q=%22Conquest+of+Southwest+Kansas%22|title=\"Conquest of Southwest Kansas\" - this user's library - Google Books|author=|date=|website=books.google.com|accessdate=22 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://collections.stanford.edu/copyrightrenewals/bin/search/simple/process?query=%22Conquest+of+Southwest+Kansas%22|title=Copyright Renewals|first1=\u00a9 Stanford|last1=University|last2=Stanford|first3=California 94305 Copyright|last3=Complaints|date=|website=Spotlight at Stanford|accessdate=22 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://comminfo.rutgers.edu/~lesk/copyrenew.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-05-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100304224301/http://comminfo.rutgers.edu/~lesk/copyrenew.html |archivedate=2010-03-04 }}</ref>\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Kansas books}}\n{{See also|Finney County, Kansas#Further reading|l1=List of books about Finney County, Kansas}}\n{{See also|Santa Fe Trail#Further reading|l1=List of books about Santa Fe Trail}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Garden City, Kansas}}\n{{wikivoyage|Garden City (Kansas)}}\n;City\n* [http://www.garden-city.org/ City of Garden City]\n* [https://www.lkm.org/members/?id=41260709 Garden City - Directory of Public Officials]\n* [https://www.visitgck.com Finney County Convention and Visitors Bureau]\n;Schools\n* [http://www.gckschools.com/ USD 457], local school district\n;History\n* [http://www.gardencity.net/info/history/ History of Garden City]\n* {{YouTube|ddgECx25NHs|Duane West - No Experience Doesn't Stop Playwright - A play about Buffalo Jones}}, from ''Hatteberg's People'' on [[KAKE]] TV news\n;Maps\n* [http://www.ksdot.org/Assets/wwwksdotorg/bureaus/burTransPlan/maps/city-pdf/garden%20city.PDF Garden City Map], KDOT\n\n{{Finney County, Kansas}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Kansas]]\n[[Category:County seats in Kansas]]\n[[Category:Cities in Finney County, Kansas]]\n[[Category:Micropolitan areas of Kansas]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1878]]\n[[Category:Populated places on the Arkansas River]]\n[[Category:1878 establishments in Kansas]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|name                     = Garden City, Kansas\n|settlement_type          = [[City]] and [[county seat]]\n\n<!-- Images -->\n|image_skyline            = Garden City, KS, welcome sign IMG_5933.JPG\n|image_caption            =\n|image_flag               =\n|image_seal               =\n\n<!-- Maps -->\n|image_map                = Finney_County_Kansas_Incorporated_and_Unincorporated_areas_Garden_City_Highlighted.svg\n|map_caption              = Location within [[Finney County, Kansas|Finney County]] and [[Kansas]]\n|image_map1               = Map of Finney Co, Ks, USA.png\n|map_caption1             = [[Kansas Department of Transportation|KDOT]] map of [[Finney County, Kansas|Finney County]] ([[:File:Kansas official transportation map legend.png|legend]])\n\n<!-- Location -->\n|coordinates_footnotes    =\n|coordinates              = {{coord|37|58|31|N|100|51|51|W|region:US-KS|display=inline,title}}\n|subdivision_type         = Country\n|subdivision_name         = United States\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = [[Kansas]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Kansas|County]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Finney County, Kansas|Finney]]\n|subdivision_type3        = [[List of townships in Kansas|Township]]\n|subdivision_name3        =\n\n<!-- Established -->\n|established_title        = Founded\n|established_date         = 1878\n|es