4||2||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||38||16\n|-\n|[[2018\u201319 Liga I|2018\u201319]]\n|18||13||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||2||0||1||0||22||13\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!49!!25!!6!!4!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!4!!0!!1!!0!!60!!29\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[New York City FC]] \n|[[2019 Major League Soccer season|2018\u201319]]\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[Major League Soccer]]\n|30||12||2||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||32||13\n|-\n|[[2020 Major League Soccer season|2019\u201320]]\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[Major League Soccer]]\n|2||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||2||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||4||1\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!32!!12!!2!!1!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!2!!1!!0!!0!!36!!14\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career total\n!170!!45!!12!!5!!2!!1!!6!!1!!1!!0!!191!!52\n|}\n\n===International===\n{{updated|18 November 2019}}<ref name=EU>{{cite web|url=https://eu-football.info/_player.php?id=30216|title=Alexandru Mitri\u021b\u0103|publisher=European Football|accessdate=24 March 2018}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!National team!!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Romania national football team|Romania]]\n|-\n|2018||6||0\n|-\n|2019||5||2\n|-\n!colspan=2|Total||11||2\n|}\n\n===International goals===\n{{Updated|15 October 2019}} (Romania score listed first, score column indicates score after each Mitri\u021b\u0103 goal)<ref name=EU/>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" \n|+ International goals by date, venue, cap, opponent, score, result and competition\n|-\n!scope=col|No.\n!scope=col data-sort-type=date|Date\n!scope=col|Venue\n!scope=col|Cap\n!scope=col|Opponent\n!scope=col|Score\n!scope=col|Result\n!scope=col|Competition\n|-\n!scope=row|1\n| 12 October 2019 || [[T\u00f3rsv\u00f8llur]], [[T\u00f3rshavn]], Faroe Islands || align=\"center\" | 8 || {{fb|FRO}} || align=center | '''2'''\u20130 || align=center | 3\u20130 || rowspan=\"2\" | [[UEFA Euro 2020 qualifying Group F|UEFA Euro 2020 qualification]]\n|-\n!scope=row|2\n| 15 October 2019 || [[Arena Na\u021bional\u0103]], [[Bucharest]], Romania || align=\"center\" | 9 || {{fb|NOR}} || align=center | '''1'''\u20130 || align=center | 1\u20131\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n\n===Club===\n'''Universitatea Craiova'''\n*[[Cupa Rom\u00e2niei]]: [[2017\u201318 Cupa Rom\u00e2niei|2017\u201318]]<ref name=\"Cupa_Romaniei_2018\"/>\n*[[Supercupa Rom\u00e2niei]]: Runner-up [[2018 Supercupa Rom\u00e2niei|2018]]<ref name=\"Supercupa_Romaniei_2018\"/>\n\n===Individual===\n*[[Liga I]] Team of the Season: [[2017\u201318 Liga I|2017\u201318]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{RomanianSoccer|2521/alexandru-ionut-mitrita}}\n*{{NFT player|70852}}\n*{{UEFA player|250042529}}\n\n{{New York City FC squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mitrita, Alexandru}}\n[[Category:1995 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Craiova]]\n[[Category:Romanian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Association football wingers]]\n[[Category:Liga I players]]\n[[Category:Liga II players]]\n[[Category:CS Turnu Severin players]]\n[[Category:FC Viitorul Constan\u021ba players]]\n[[Category:CS Universitatea Craiova players]]\n[[Category:Serie A players]]\n[[Category:Serie B players]]\n[[Category:Delfino Pescara 1936 players]]\n[[Category:Major League Soccer players]]\n[[Category:New York City FC players]]\n[[Category:Designated Players (MLS)]]\n[[Category:Romania youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Romania under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Romania international footballers]]\n[[Category:Romanian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Italy]]\n[[Category:Romanian expatriate sportspeople in Italy]]\n[[Category:Expatriate soccer players in the United States]]\n[[Category:Romanian expatriate sportspeople in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "8Dodo8", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNew York City", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexandru_Mitri%C8%9B%C4%83"}
{"title_page": "Davydov soliton", "text_new": "[[Image:Davydov-soliton.gif|right|thumb|476px|Quantum dynamics of a Davydov soliton with <math>\\chi = 35</math> pN generated by an initial Gaussian step distribution of amide I energy over 3 peptide groups at the N-end of a single \u03b1-helix spine composed of 40 peptide groups (extending along the ''x''-axis) during a period of 125 picoseconds. Quantum probabilities <math>|a_n|^2</math> of amide I excitation are plotted in blue along the ''z''-axis. Phonon lattice displacement differences <math>b_n-b_{n-1}</math> (measured in picometers) are plotted in red along the ''y''-axis. The soliton is formed by self-trapping of the amide I energy by the induced lattice distortion.<ref name=\"Georgiev2019a\">{{cite journal\n | last1 = Georgiev\n | first1 = Danko D.\n | last2 = Glazebrook\n | first2 = James F.\n | title = On the quantum dynamics of Davydov solitons in protein \u03b1-helices\n | journal = Physica A: Statistical Mechanics and Its Applications\n | volume = 517\n | pages = 257\u2013269\n | year = 2019\n | doi = 10.1016/j.physa.2018.11.026\n | mr = 3880179\n | arxiv = 1811.05886\n}}</ref><ref name=\"Georgiev2019b\">{{cite journal\n | last1 = Georgiev\n | first1 = Danko D.\n | last2 = Glazebrook\n | first2 = James F.\n | title = Quantum tunneling of Davydov solitons through massive barriers\n | journal = Chaos, Solitons and Fractals\n | volume = 123\n | pages = 275\u2013293\n | year = 2019\n | doi = 10.1016/j.chaos.2019.04.013\n | mr = 3941070\n | arxiv = 1904.09822\n}}</ref>]]\n\n'''Davydov soliton''' is a quantum [[quasiparticle]] representing an excitation propagating along the [[protein]] [[\u03b1-helix]] self-trapped [[amide|amide I]].  It is a solution of the Davydov [[Hamiltonian (quantum mechanics)|Hamiltonian]]. It is named for the Soviet and Ukrainian physicist [[Alexander Davydov]]. The Davydov model describes the interaction of the amide I [[vibration]]s with the [[hydrogen bond]]s that stabilize the [[\u03b1-helix]] of [[protein]]s. The elementary excitations within the \u03b1-helix are given by the [[phonon]]s which correspond to the deformational oscillations of the lattice, and the [[exciton]]s which describe the internal [[amide|amide I]] excitations of the [[peptide group]]s. Referring to the atomic structure of an \u03b1-helix region of protein the mechanism that creates the Davydov soliton ([[polaron]], [[exciton]]) can be described as follows: [[vibration]]al [[energy]] of the [[carbonyl|C=O]] [[stretching]] (or [[amide|amide I]]) [[oscillator]]s that is localized on the \u03b1-helix acts through a phonon coupling effect to distort the structure of the \u03b1-helix, while the helical distortion reacts again through phonon coupling to trap the amide I oscillation energy and prevent its dispersion. This effect is called ''self-localization'' or ''self-trapping''.<ref name=\"Davydov1973\">{{cite journal\n | last1 = Davydov\n | first1 = Alexander S.\n | title = The theory of contraction of proteins under their excitation\n | journal = Journal of Theoretical Biology\n | volume = 38\n | pages = 559\u2013569\n | year = 1973\n | doi = 10.1016/0022-5193(73)90256-7\n | pmid = 4266326\n | issue = 3\n}}</ref><ref name=\"Davydov1977\">\n{{cite journal\n | last1 = Davydov\n | first1 = Alexander S.\n | title = Solitons and energy transfer along protein molecules\n | journal = Journal of Theoretical Biology\n | volume = 66\n | pages = 379\u2013387\n | year = 1977\n | doi = 10.1016/0022-5193(77)90178-3\n | pmid = 886872\n | issue = 2\n}}</ref><ref name=\"Davydov1979\">{{cite journal\n | last1 = Davydov\n | first1 = Alexander S.\n | title = Solitons, bioenergetics, and the mechanism of muscle contraction\n | journal = International Journal of Quantum Chemistry\n | volume = 16\n | issue = 1\n | pages = 5\u201317\n | year = 1979\n | doi = 10.1002/qua.560160104\n}}</ref> [[Soliton]]s in which the [[energy]] is distributed in a fashion preserving the [[helix|helical]] [[symmetry]] are dynamically unstable, and such [[symmetric]]al solitons once formed decay rapidly when they propagate. On the other hand, an [[symmetry|asymmetric]] soliton which [[Spontaneous symmetry breaking|spontaneously breaks the local translational and helical symmetries]] possesses the lowest energy and is a robust localized entity.<ref name=\"Brizhik2004\">\n{{cite journal\n | last1 = Brizhik\n | first1 = Larissa\n | last2 = Eremko\n | first2 = Alexander\n | last3 = Piette\n | first3 = Bernard\n | last4 = Zakrzewski\n | first4 = Wojtek\n | title = Solitons in \u03b1-helical proteins\n | journal = Physical Review E\n | volume = 70\n | issue = 3 Pt 1\n | pages = 031914\n | year = 2004\n | bibcode = 2004PhRvE..70a1914K \n | pmid = 15524556\n | doi = 10.1103/PhysRevE.70.011914\n | arxiv=cond-mat/0402644}}</ref>\n\n==Davydov Hamiltonian==\n\nDavydov [[Hamiltonian (quantum mechanics)|Hamiltonian]] is formally similar to the [[Polaron#Polaron theory|Fr\u00f6hlich-Holstein Hamiltonian]] for the interaction of electrons with a polarizable lattice. Thus the [[Hamiltonian (quantum mechanics)|Hamiltonian]] of the [[energy operator]] <math>\\hat{H}</math> is\n\n:<math>\n\\hat{H}=\\hat{H}_{\\text{qp}}+\\hat{H}_{\\text{ph}}+\\hat{H}_{\\text{int}}</math>\n\nwhere <math>\\hat{H}_{\\text{qp}}</math> is the [[quasiparticle]] ([[exciton]]) [[Hamiltonian (quantum mechanics)|Hamiltonian]], which describes the motion of the amide I excitations between adjacent sites; <math>\\hat{H}_{\\text{ph}}</math> is the [[phonon]] [[Hamiltonian (quantum mechanics)|Hamiltonian]], which describes\nthe [[vibration]]s of the [[lattice model (physics)|lattice]]; and <math>\\hat{H}_{\\text{int}}</math> is the [[interaction]] [[Hamiltonian (quantum mechanics)|Hamiltonian]], which describes the interaction of the amide I excitation with the lattice.<ref name=\"Davydov1973\"/><ref name=\"Davydov1977\"/><ref name=\"Davydov1979\"/>\n\nThe [[quasiparticle]] ([[exciton]]) [[Hamiltonian (quantum mechanics)|Hamiltonian]] <math>\\hat{H}_{\\text{qp}}</math> is:\n\n:<math>\\hat{H}_{\\text{qp}}=</math> <math>\\sum_{n,\\alpha}E_{0}\\hat{A}_{n,\\alpha}^{\\dagger}\\hat{A}_{n,\\alpha}</math> <math>-J\\sum_{n,\\alpha}\\left(\\hat{A}_{n,\\alpha}^{\\dagger}\\hat{A}_{n+1,\\alpha}+\\hat{A}_{n,\\alpha}^{\\dagger}\\hat{A}_{n-1,\\alpha}\\right)</math> <math>+L\\sum_{n,\\alpha}\\left(\\hat{A}_{n,\\alpha}^{\\dagger}\\hat{A}_{n,\\alpha+1}+\\hat{A}_{n,\\alpha}^{\\dagger}\\hat{A}_{n,\\alpha-1}\\right)</math>\n\nwhere the index <math>n=1,2,\\cdots,N</math> counts the peptide groups along the \u03b1-helix spine, the index <math>\\alpha=1,2,3</math> counts each \u03b1-helix spine, <math>E_{0}=32.8</math> [[Zepto-|z]][[Joule|J]] is the energy of the amide I\nvibration (CO stretching), <math>J=0.155</math> [[Zepto-|z]][[Joule|J]] is the [[dipole]]-[[dipole]] coupling energy between a particular amide I bond and those ahead and behind along the same spine, <math>L=0.246</math> [[Zepto-|z]][[Joule|J]] is the\ndipole-dipole coupling energy between a particular amide I bond and those on adjacent spines in the same unit cell of the [[protein]] [[\u03b1-helix]], <math>\\hat{A}_{n,\\alpha}^{\\dagger}</math> and <math>\\hat{A}_{n,\\alpha}</math> are respectively\nthe [[boson]] [[creation and annihilation operator]] for a quasiparticle at the [[peptide group]] <math>(n,\\alpha)</math>.<ref name=\"Hyman1981\">\n{{cite journal\n | last1 = Hyman\n | first1 = James M.\n | last2 = McLaughlin\n | first2 = David W.\n | last3 = Scott\n | first3 = Alwyn C.\n | year = 1981\n | title = On Davydov's alpha-helix solitons\n | journal=Physica D: Nonlinear Phenomena\n | volume=3 \n | issue=1  \n | pages = 23\u201344\n | bibcode =1981PhyD....3...23H \n | doi= 10.1016/0167-2789(81)90117-2\n}}</ref><ref name=\"Scott1992\">\n{{cite journal\n | last1 = Scott\n | first1 = Alwyn C.\n | title = Davydov's soliton\n | journal = Physics Reports\n | volume = 217\n | issue = 1\n | pages = 1\u201367\n | year = 1992\n | doi = 10.1016/0370-1573(92)90093-F\n|bibcode = 1992PhR...217....1S }}</ref><ref name=\"Takeno1997\">\n{{cite journal\n | last1 = Cruzeiro-Hansson\n | first1 = Leonor\n | last2 = Takeno\n | first2 = Shozo\n | year = 1997\n | title = Davydov model: the quantum, mixed quantum-classical, and full classical systems\n | journal=[[Physical Review E]]\n | volume=56 | issue=1  | pages = 894\u2013906\n | bibcode = 1997PhRvE..56..894C\n | doi= 10.1103/PhysRevE.56.894\n}}</ref>\n\nThe [[phonon]] [[Hamiltonian (quantum mechanics)|Hamiltonian]] <math>\\hat{H}_{\\text{ph}}</math> is\n\n:<math>\n\\hat{H}_{\\text{ph}}=\\frac{1}{2}\\sum_{n,\\alpha}\\left[w(\\hat{u}_{n+1,\\alpha}-\\hat{u}_{n,\\alpha})^{2}+\\frac{\\hat{p}_{n,\\alpha}^{2}}{M_{n,\\alpha}}\\right]</math>\n\nwhere <math>\\hat{u}_{n,\\alpha}</math> is the [[displacement operator]] from the equilibrium position of the [[peptide group]] <math>(n,\\alpha)</math>, <math>\\hat{p}_{n,\\alpha}</math> is the [[momentum operator]] of the peptide group <math>(n,\\alpha)</math>, <math>M_{n,\\alpha}</math> is the [[mass]] of the peptide group <math>(n,\\alpha)</math>, and <math>w=13-19.5</math> [[Newton_(unit)|N]]/[[Metre|m]] is an [[Elasticity (physics)|effective elasticity coefficient]] of the lattice (the [[spring constant]] of a [[hydrogen bond]]).<ref name=\"Scott1992\"/>\n\nFinally, the [[interaction]] [[Hamiltonian (quantum mechanics)|Hamiltonian]] <math>\\hat{H}_{\\text{int}}</math> is\n\n:<math>\n\\hat{H}_{\\text{int}}=\\chi\\sum_{n,\\alpha}\\left[(\\hat{u}_{n+1,\\alpha}-\\hat{u}_{n,\\alpha})\\hat{A}_{n,\\alpha}^{\\dagger}\\hat{A}_{n,\\alpha}\\right]</math>\n\nwhere <math>\\chi=35-62</math> [[Pico-|p]][[Newton_(unit)|N]] is an anharmonic parameter arising from the coupling between the [[quasiparticle]] (exciton) and the lattice displacements (phonon) and parameterizes the strength of the [[exciton]]-[[phonon]] [[interaction]].<ref name=\"Scott1992\"/> The value of this parameter for [[\u03b1-helix]] has been determined via comparison of the theoretically calculated absorption line shapes with the experimentally measured ones.\n\n==Davydov soliton properties==\n\nThere are three possible fundamental approaches for deriving equations of motion from Davydov Hamiltonian:\n* ''[[Quantum mechanics|quantum approach]]'', in which both the amide I vibration ([[exciton]]s) and the lattice site motion ([[phonon]]s) are treated quantum mechanically;<ref name=\"Kerr1987\">{{cite journal\n | last1 = Kerr\n | first1 = William C.\n | last2 = Lomdahl\n | first2 = Peter S.\n | title = Quantum-mechanical derivation of the equations of motion for Davydov solitons\n | journal = Physical Review B\n | volume = 35\n | issue = 7\n | pages = 3629\u20133632\n | year = 1987\n | doi = 10.1103/PhysRevB.35.3629\n | pmid = 9941870\n| hdl = 10339/15922\n }}</ref>\n* ''mixed quantum-classical approach'', in which the amide I vibration is treated quantum mechanically but the lattice is classical;<ref name=\"Takeno1997\"/>\n* ''[[classical physics|classical approach]]'', in which both the amide I and the lattice motions are treated classically.<ref name=\"Skrinjar1988\">{{cite journal\n | last1 =  \u0160krinjar\n | first1 =  M. J.\n | last2 = Kapor\n | first2 = D. V.\n | last3 = Stojanovi\u0107\n | first3 = S. D.\n | title = Classical and quantum approach to Davydov's soliton theory\n | journal = Physical Review A\n | volume = 38\n | issue = 12\n | pages = 6402\u20136408\n | year = 1988\n | doi = 10.1103/PhysRevA.38.6402\n | pmid = 9900400\n}}</ref>\n\nThe mathematical techniques that are used to analyze the Davydov soliton are similar to some that have been developed in polaron theory.<ref name=\"Sun2010\">{{cite journal\n | last1 = Sun\n | first1 = Jin\n | last2 = Luo\n | first2 = Bin\n | last3 = Zhao\n | first3 = Yang\n | title = Dynamics of a one-dimensional Holstein polaron with the Davydov ans\u00e4tze\n | journal = Physical Review B\n | volume = 82\n | issue = 1\n | pages = 014305\n | year = 2010\n | doi = 10.1103/PhysRevB.82.014305\n| arxiv = 1001.3198\n }}</ref> In this context, the Davydov soliton corresponds to a [[polaron]] that is:\n* ''large'' so the continuum limit approximation is justified,<ref name=\"Scott1992\"/>\n* ''acoustic'' because the self-localization arises from interactions with acoustic modes of the lattice,<ref name=\"Scott1992\"/>\n* ''weakly coupled'' because the anharmonic energy is small compared with the phonon bandwidth.<ref name=\"Scott1992\"/>\n\nThe Davydov soliton is a ''quantum quasiparticle'' and it obeys [[Heisenberg's uncertainty principle]]. Thus any model that does not impose translational invariance is flawed by construction.<ref name=\"Scott1992\"/> Supposing that the Davydov soliton is localized to 5 turns of the [[\u03b1-helix]] results in significant uncertainty in the [[velocity]] of the [[soliton]] <math>\\Delta v=133</math> m/s, a fact that is obscured if one models the Davydov soliton as a classical object.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{particles}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davydov Soliton}}\n[[Category:Biological matter]]\n[[Category:Biophysics]]\n[[Category:Quantum biology]]\n[[Category:Quantum mechanics]]\n", "text_old": "[[Image:Davydov-soliton.gif|right|thumb|500px|Quantum dynamics of a Davydov soliton with <math>\\chi = 35</math> pN generated by an initial Gaussian step distribution of amide I energy over 3 peptide groups at the N-end of a single \u03b1-helix spine composed of 40 peptide groups (extending along the ''x''-axis) during a period of 125 picoseconds. Quantum probabilities <math>|a_n|^2</math> of amide I excitation are plotted in blue along the ''z''-axis. Phonon lattice displacement differences <math>b_n-b_{n-1}</math> (measured in picometers) are plotted in red along the ''y''-axis. The soliton is formed by self-trapping of the amide I energy by the induced lattice distortion.<ref name=\"Georgiev2019a\">{{cite journal\n | last1 = Georgiev\n | first1 = Danko D.\n | last2 = Glazebrook\n | first2 = James F.\n | title = On the quantum dynamics of Davydov solitons in protein \u03b1-helices\n | journal = Physica A: Statistical Mechanics and Its Applications\n | volume = 517\n | pages = 257\u2013269\n | year = 2019\n | doi = 10.1016/j.physa.2018.11.026\n | mr = 3880179\n | arxiv = 1811.05886\n}}</ref><ref name=\"Georgiev2019b\">{{cite journal\n | last1 = Georgiev\n | first1 = Danko D.\n | last2 = Glazebrook\n | first2 = James F.\n | title = Quantum tunneling of Davydov solitons through massive barriers\n | journal = Chaos, Solitons and Fractals\n | volume = 123\n | pages = 275\u2013293\n | year = 2019\n | doi = 10.1016/j.chaos.2019.04.013\n | mr = 3941070\n | arxiv = 1904.09822\n}}</ref>]]\n\n'''Davydov soliton''' is a quantum [[quasiparticle]] representing an excitation propagating along the [[protein]] [[\u03b1-helix]] self-trapped [[amide|amide I]].  It is a solution of the Davydov [[Hamiltonian (quantum mechanics)|Hamiltonian]]. It is named for the Soviet and Ukrainian physicist [[Alexander Davydov]]. The Davydov model describes the interaction of the amide I [[vibration]]s with the [[hydrogen bond]]s that stabilize the [[\u03b1-helix]] of [[protein]]s. The elementary excitations within the \u03b1-helix are given by the [[phonon]]s which correspond to the deformational oscillations of the lattice, and the [[exciton]]s which describe the internal [[amide|amide I]] excitations of the [[peptide group]]s. Referring to the atomic structure of an \u03b1-helix region of protein the mechanism that creates the Davydov soliton ([[polaron]], [[exciton]]) can be described as follows: [[vibration]]al [[energy]] of the [[carbonyl|C=O]] [[stretching]] (or [[amide|amide I]]) [[oscillator]]s that is localized on the \u03b1-helix acts through a phonon coupling effect to distort the structure of the \u03b1-helix, while the helical distortion reacts again through phonon coupling to trap the amide I oscillation energy and prevent its dispersion. This effect is called ''self-localization'' or ''self-trapping''.<ref name=\"Davydov1973\">{{cite journal\n | last1 = Davydov\n | first1 = Alexander S.\n | title = The theory of contraction of proteins under their excitation\n | journal = Journal of Theoretical Biology\n | volume = 38\n | pages = 559\u2013569\n | year = 1973\n | doi = 10.1016/0022-5193(73)90256-7\n | pmid = 4266326\n | issue = 3\n}}</ref><ref name=\"Davydov1977\">\n{{cite journal\n | last1 = Davydov\n | first1 = Alexander S.\n | title = Solitons and energy transfer along protein molecules\n | journal = Journal of Theoretical Biology\n | volume = 66\n | pages = 379\u2013387\n | year = 1977\n | doi = 10.1016/0022-5193(77)90178-3\n | pmid = 886872\n | issue = 2\n}}</ref><ref name=\"Davydov1979\">{{cite journal\n | last1 = Davydov\n | first1 = Alexander S.\n | title = Solitons, bioenergetics, and the mechanism of muscle contraction\n | journal = International Journal of Quantum Chemistry\n | volume = 16\n | issue = 1\n | pages = 5\u201317\n | year = 1979\n | doi = 10.1002/qua.560160104\n}}</ref> [[Soliton]]s in which the [[energy]] is distributed in a fashion preserving the [[helix|helical]] [[symmetry]] are dynamically unstable, and such [[symmetric]]al solitons once formed decay rapidly when they propagate. On the other hand, an [[symmetry|asymmetric]] soliton which [[Spontaneous symmetry breaking|spontaneously breaks the local translational and helical symmetries]] possesses the lowest energy and is a robust localized entity.<ref name=\"Brizhik2004\">\n{{cite journal\n | last1 = Brizhik\n | first1 = Larissa\n | last2 = Eremko\n | first2 = Alexander\n | last3 = Piette\n | first3 = Bernard\n | last4 = Zakrzewski\n | first4 = Wojtek\n | title = Solitons in \u03b1-helical proteins\n | journal = Physical Review E\n | volume = 70\n | issue = 3 Pt 1\n | pages = 031914\n | year = 2004\n | bibcode = 2004PhRvE..70a1914K \n | pmid = 15524556\n | doi = 10.1103/PhysRevE.70.011914\n | arxiv=cond-mat/0402644}}</ref>\n\n==Davydov Hamiltonian==\n\nDavydov [[Hamiltonian (quantum mechanics)|Hamiltonian]] is formally similar to the [[Polaron#Polaron theory|Fr\u00f6hlich-Holstein Hamiltonian]] for the interaction of electrons with a polarizable lattice. Thus the [[Hamiltonian (quantum mechanics)|Hamiltonian]] of the [[energy operator]] <math>\\hat{H}</math> is\n\n:<math>\n\\hat{H}=\\hat{H}_{\\text{qp}}+\\hat{H}_{\\text{ph}}+\\hat{H}_{\\text{int}}</math>\n\nwhere <math>\\hat{H}_{\\text{qp}}</math> is the [[quasiparticle]] ([[exciton]]) [[Hamiltonian (quantum mechanics)|Hamiltonian]], which describes the motion of the amide I excitations between adjacent sites; <math>\\hat{H}_{\\text{ph}}</math> is the [[phonon]] [[Hamiltonian (quantum mechanics)|Hamiltonian]], which describes\nthe [[vibration]]s of the [[lattice model (physics)|lattice]]; and <math>\\hat{H}_{\\text{int}}</math> is the [[interaction]] [[Hamiltonian (quantum mechanics)|Hamiltonian]], which describes the interaction of the amide I excitation with the lattice.<ref name=\"Davydov1973\"/><ref name=\"Davydov1977\"/><ref name=\"Davydov1979\"/>\n\nThe [[quasiparticle]] ([[exciton]]) [[Hamiltonian (quantum mechanics)|Hamiltonian]] <math>\\hat{H}_{\\text{qp}}</math> is:\n\n:<math>\\hat{H}_{\\text{qp}}=</math> <math>\\sum_{n,\\alpha}E_{0}\\hat{A}_{n,\\alpha}^{\\dagger}\\hat{A}_{n,\\alpha}</math> <math>-J\\sum_{n,\\alpha}\\left(\\hat{A}_{n,\\alpha}^{\\dagger}\\hat{A}_{n+1,\\alpha}+\\hat{A}_{n,\\alpha}^{\\dagger}\\hat{A}_{n-1,\\alpha}\\right)</math> <math>+L\\sum_{n,\\alpha}\\left(\\hat{A}_{n,\\alpha}^{\\dagger}\\hat{A}_{n,\\alpha+1}+\\hat{A}_{n,\\alpha}^{\\dagger}\\hat{A}_{n,\\alpha-1}\\right)</math>\n\nwhere the index <math>n=1,2,\\cdots,N</math> counts the peptide groups along the \u03b1-helix spine, the index <math>\\alpha=1,2,3</math> counts each \u03b1-helix spine, <math>E_{0}=32.8</math> [[Zepto-|z]][[Joule|J]] is the energy of the amide I\nvibration (CO stretching), <math>J=0.155</math> [[Zepto-|z]][[Joule|J]] is the [[dipole]]-[[dipole]] coupling energy between a particular amide I bond and those ahead and behind along the same spine, <math>L=0.246</math> [[Zepto-|z]][[Joule|J]] is the\ndipole-dipole coupling energy between a particular amide I bond and those on adjacent spines in the same unit cell of the [[protein]] [[\u03b1-helix]], <math>\\hat{A}_{n,\\alpha}^{\\dagger}</math> and <math>\\hat{A}_{n,\\alpha}</math> are respectively\nthe [[boson]] [[creation and annihilation operator]] for a quasiparticle at the [[peptide group]] <math>(n,\\alpha)</math>.<ref name=\"Hyman1981\">\n{{cite journal\n | last1 = Hyman\n | first1 = James M.\n | last2 = McLaughlin\n | first2 = David W.\n | last3 = Scott\n | first3 = Alwyn C.\n | year = 1981\n | title = On Davydov's alpha-helix solitons\n | journal=Physica D: Nonlinear Phenomena\n | volume=3 \n | issue=1  \n | pages = 23\u201344\n | bibcode =1981PhyD....3...23H \n | doi= 10.1016/0167-2789(81)90117-2\n}}</ref><ref name=\"Scott1992\">\n{{cite journal\n | last1 = Scott\n | first1 = Alwyn C.\n | title = Davydov's soliton\n | journal = Physics Reports\n | volume = 217\n | issue = 1\n | pages = 1\u201367\n | year = 1992\n | doi = 10.1016/0370-1573(92)90093-F\n|bibcode = 1992PhR...217....1S }}</ref><ref name=\"Takeno1997\">\n{{cite journal\n | last1 = Cruzeiro-Hansson\n | first1 = Leonor\n | last2 = Takeno\n | first2 = Shozo\n | year = 1997\n | title = Davydov model: the quantum, mixed quantum-classical, and full classical systems\n | journal=[[Physical Review E]]\n | volume=56 | issue=1  | pages = 894\u2013906\n | bibcode = 1997PhRvE..56..894C\n | doi= 10.1103/PhysRevE.56.894\n}}</ref>\n\nThe [[phonon]] [[Hamiltonian (quantum mechanics)|Hamiltonian]] <math>\\hat{H}_{\\text{ph}}</math> is\n\n:<math>\n\\hat{H}_{\\text{ph}}=\\frac{1}{2}\\sum_{n,\\alpha}\\left[w(\\hat{u}_{n+1,\\alpha}-\\hat{u}_{n,\\alpha})^{2}+\\frac{\\hat{p}_{n,\\alpha}^{2}}{M_{n,\\alpha}}\\right]</math>\n\nwhere <math>\\hat{u}_{n,\\alpha}</math> is the [[displacement operator]] from the equilibrium position of the [[peptide group]] <math>(n,\\alpha)</math>, <math>\\hat{p}_{n,\\alpha}</math> is the [[momentum operator]] of the peptide group <math>(n,\\alpha)</math>, <math>M_{n,\\alpha}</math> is the [[mass]] of the peptide group <math>(n,\\alpha)</math>, and <math>w=13-19.5</math> [[Newton_(unit)|N]]/[[Metre|m]] is an [[Elasticity (physics)|effective elasticity coefficient]] of the lattice (the [[spring constant]] of a [[hydrogen bond]]).<ref name=\"Scott1992\"/>\n\nFinally, the [[interaction]] [[Hamiltonian (quantum mechanics)|Hamiltonian]] <math>\\hat{H}_{\\text{int}}</math> is\n\n:<math>\n\\hat{H}_{\\text{int}}=\\chi\\sum_{n,\\alpha}\\left[(\\hat{u}_{n+1,\\alpha}-\\hat{u}_{n,\\alpha})\\hat{A}_{n,\\alpha}^{\\dagger}\\hat{A}_{n,\\alpha}\\right]</math>\n\nwhere <math>\\chi=35-62</math> [[Pico-|p]][[Newton_(unit)|N]] is an anharmonic parameter arising from the coupling between the [[quasiparticle]] (exciton) and the lattice displacements (phonon) and parameterizes the strength of the [[exciton]]-[[phonon]] [[interaction]].<ref name=\"Scott1992\"/> The value of this parameter for [[\u03b1-helix]] has been determined via comparison of the theoretically calculated absorption line shapes with the experimentally measured ones.\n\n==Davydov soliton properties==\n\nThere are three possible fundamental approaches for deriving equations of motion from Davydov Hamiltonian:\n* ''[[Quantum mechanics|quantum approach]]'', in which both the amide I vibration ([[exciton]]s) and the lattice site motion ([[phonon]]s) are treated quantum mechanically;<ref name=\"Kerr1987\">{{cite journal\n | last1 = Kerr\n | first1 = William C.\n | last2 = Lomdahl\n | first2 = Peter S.\n | title = Quantum-mechanical derivation of the equations of motion for Davydov solitons\n | journal = Physical Review B\n | volume = 35\n | issue = 7\n | pages = 3629\u20133632\n | year = 1987\n | doi = 10.1103/PhysRevB.35.3629\n | pmid = 9941870\n| hdl = 10339/15922\n }}</ref>\n* ''mixed quantum-classical approach'', in which the amide I vibration is treated quantum mechanically but the lattice is classical;<ref name=\"Takeno1997\"/>\n* ''[[classical physics|classical approach]]'', in which both the amide I and the lattice motions are treated classically.<ref name=\"Skrinjar1988\">{{cite journal\n | last1 =  \u0160krinjar\n | first1 =  M. J.\n | last2 = Kapor\n | first2 = D. V.\n | last3 = Stojanovi\u0107\n | first3 = S. D.\n | title = Classical and quantum approach to Davydov's soliton theory\n | journal = Physical Review A\n | volume = 38\n | issue = 12\n | pages = 6402\u20136408\n | year = 1988\n | doi = 10.1103/PhysRevA.38.6402\n | pmid = 9900400\n}}</ref>\n\nThe mathematical techniques that are used to analyze the Davydov soliton are similar to some that have been developed in polaron theory.<ref name=\"Sun2010\">{{cite journal\n | last1 = Sun\n | first1 = Jin\n | last2 = Luo\n | first2 = Bin\n | last3 = Zhao\n | first3 = Yang\n | title = Dynamics of a one-dimensional Holstein polaron with the Davydov ans\u00e4tze\n | journal = Physical Review B\n | volume = 82\n | issue = 1\n | pages = 014305\n | year = 2010\n | doi = 10.1103/PhysRevB.82.014305\n| arxiv = 1001.3198\n }}</ref> In this context, the Davydov soliton corresponds to a [[polaron]] that is:\n* ''large'' so the continuum limit approximation is justified,<ref name=\"Scott1992\"/>\n* ''acoustic'' because the self-localization arises from interactions with acoustic modes of the lattice,<ref name=\"Scott1992\"/>\n* ''weakly coupled'' because the anharmonic energy is small compared with the phonon bandwidth.<ref name=\"Scott1992\"/>\n\nThe Davydov soliton is a ''quantum quasiparticle'' and it obeys [[Heisenberg's uncertainty principle]]. Thus any model that does not impose translational invariance is flawed by construction.<ref name=\"Scott1992\"/> Supposing that the Davydov soliton is localized to 5 turns of the [[\u03b1-helix]] results in significant uncertainty in the [[velocity]] of the [[soliton]] <math>\\Delta v=133</math> m/s, a fact that is obscured if one models the Davydov soliton as a classical object.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{particles}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davydov Soliton}}\n[[Category:Biological matter]]\n[[Category:Biophysics]]\n[[Category:Quantum biology]]\n[[Category:Quantum mechanics]]\n", "name_user": "B\u00fcrgerentscheid", "label": "safe", "comment": "image size fixed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Davydov_soliton"}
{"title_page": "Hacettepe University", "text_new": "{{short description|Major state university in Ankara, Turkey}}\n{{Infobox university\n|name = Hacettepe University\n|native_name = Hacettepe \u00dcniversitesi\n|motto = To the leading edge... Toward being the best...\n|image_name = Hacettepe University (emblem).png\n|image_size = 122px\n|established = 1967\n|type = [[Public University]]\n|rector = Haluk \u00d6zen\n|staff = 3638\n|students = 49582\n|city = [[Ankara]]\n|country = [[Turkey]]\n|affiliations = [[European University Association|EUA]]\n|campus = [[Urban area|Urban]] ({{convert|210,238 |m2|acre|0}}) <br>[[Suburban]] ({{convert|5,877,628| m2|acre|0}}) \n|mascot = Stag \n|logo = Hacettepe_University_logo.svg\n|logo_size = 250px\n|website = [http://www.hacettepe.edu.tr/ www.hacettepe.edu.tr]}}\n\n'''Hacettepe University''' is a major state [[university]] in [[Ankara]], [[Turkey]]. Based on academic performance, it ranks 1st among Turkish universities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tr.urapcenter.org/2018/2018_t9.php |title=URAP- University Rankings in Turkey}}</ref> \n\nThe University has two main campuses.  The first campus is located in the old town of Ankara and hosts the Medical Centre, and the second one, Beytepe Campus is {{convert|13|km|mi|abbr=on|0}} from the city centre.  The Beytepe Campus covers {{convert|6000000|m2|ha acre|abbr=on|0}} of green land and woodland, and hosts the faculties of Economic and Administrative Sciences, Law, Education, Engineering, Fine Arts, Letters, and Science. In addition to these two main campuses, the School of Social Work is located at Ke\u00e7i\u00f6ren, and the Turkish State Conservatory in Ankara, affiliated with the University as of 1982, is located at the Be\u015fevler Campus.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hacettepe.edu.tr/english/hakkinda/geneltanitim|title=Hacettepe University|website=www.hacettepe.edu.tr|access-date=2017-10-04}}</ref>.\n\n==General information==\n\n===History===\n[[Image:Museum of Anatolian Civilizations027.jpg|right|thumb|200px|The [[Hittites|Hittite]] stag, which served as the inspiration for the Hacettepe University emblem]]\nThe history of Hacettepe University can be traced back to the establishment of the Institute of Child Health on July 8, 1958, and the inauguration of the Hacettepe Children's Hospital founded by Prof. Dr. [[Ihsan Dogramaci|\u0130hsan Do\u011framac\u0131]]. In 1961 the School of Health Sciences and its divisions of Nursing, Medical Technology, Physical Therapy and Rehabilitation and Nutrition were opened, all centered on the Institute of Child Health.\n\nOn June 15, 1963, Hacettepe University, Faculty of Medicine was established and a general teaching hospital was built. Three months later Hacettepe University School of Dentistry was established.\n\nIn the summer of 1964, a School of Basic Sciences was opened, offering courses in the natural sciences, social sciences and the humanities. At the time, all Hacettepe teaching institutions were affiliated to Ankara University and grouped under the title \"Hacettepe Science Center\".\n\nHacettepe University was chartered through Act No. 892 of the Turkish Parliament on July 8, 1967. Hacettepe Institutes of Higher Education formed the core of Hacettepe University, and the Faculties of Medicine, Science and Engineering, and Social and Administrative sciences were established.\n\nIn 1969 Hacettepe School of Pharmacy and Health Administration were established. In 1971 with a reorganization, the former schools were given faculty status and thus they became the Faculty of Dentistry, Faculty of Engineering, Faculty of Pharmacy and Faculty of Science. In 1973 the School of Technology was established. In I982 the former faculties were reorganized as the Faculty of Letters, Faculty of Education, Faculty of Fine Arts, Faculty of Economic and Administrative Sciences and the State Conservatory was affiliated to Hacettepe University. In 1984 the School of Health services and in 1989 the School of Sport Sciences and Technology were established. Recently in 1998 the two Polatli; Vocational Schools and Kaman Vocational School have been established.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hacettepe.edu.tr/english/hakkinda/tarihce|title=Hacettepe University|website=www.hacettepe.edu.tr|access-date=2017-10-04}}</ref>\n\n===Official Seal===\nThe emblem of the University was designed in 1967 by Dr. Y\u00fccel Tanyeri, then a second year medical student, in the likeness of a stag \u2013 the symbol of a [[Hittite mythology|Hittite]] deity discovered at the royal tombs in [[Alacah\u00f6y\u00fck]]. Inspired by this archeological symbol common to the [[Central Anatolia|region]], the Stag was chosen as the symbol of the University, and was abstracted to represent a lowercase \"h\" \u2013 the first letter of the university's name.[https://web.archive.org/web/20070810010732/http://www.hacettepe.edu.tr/ortak/universite/oyku.php]\n\n==Rankings==\nIn 2018 US News Global University Rankings, Hacettepe University ranked 1st in Turkey and 208th globally, in clinical medicine <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/education/best-global-universities/search?region=asia&subject=clinical-medicine&page=3|title=US News - University Clinical Medicine Ranking by Academic Performance }}</ref> . In 2010, University Ranking by Academic Performance (URAP) ranked Hacettepe University 399th in the world and best university in Turkey.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.urapcenter.org |title=URAP - University Ranking by Academic Performance }}</ref>\nIn QS 2010 University ranking it is ranked 285 in the field of life sciences and medicine. In SCImagoir 2010 ranking it is ranked 354th worldwide, 114th in Western Europe, 1st in Turkey and 122nd worldwide in the field of Health Sciences. Locally Hacettepe University Faculty of Medicine is ranked the best in the country. Based on the minimum scores required to enroll in medical school, Hacettepe University holds the top spot among state schools for longer than a decade.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ogrencibulteni.com/2011-2012-tip-fakultesi-taban-puanlari.html |title=OSYM- Medical School Rankings by Minimum Scores |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120709025431/http://www.ogrencibulteni.com/2011-2012-tip-fakultesi-taban-puanlari.html |archivedate=2012-07-09 }}</ref> \n{{Clear}}\n\n==Campuses==\n\n=== Main Campus \u2013 Medical Center ===\n[[Image:Merkez1.jpg|right|thumb|200px|The Medical School on Main Campus, with old Ankara in the background.]]\nMain campus is located in S\u0131hhiye, Ankara. In this campus, the following are located: Faculties of Dentistry, Faculty of Medicine and Pharmacy, Institutes of Child Health, Health Sciences, Neurological Sciences, Oncology, Public Health and Population Studies, and Schools of Health Administration, HeaIth Technology, Home Economics, Nursing, Physical Therapy and Rehabilitation and Health Services, Teaching Hospitals (the Adult Hospital, Ihsan Dogramaci Children's Hospital and the Oncology Hospital), a biomedical library, biomedical research units, student dormitories, sports and recreation centers and clubs.\n\n===Beytepe Campus===\n\nThis campus is located in Beytepe. The faculties of Economic and Administrative Sciences, Education, Engineering, Fine Arts, Letters and Natural Sciences, Institutes of History of Modern Turkey, Natural Sciences, Nuclear Sciences and Social Sciences and Schools of Foreign Languages, and the Vocational School of Technology, School of Sport Sciences and Technology, and administrative offices, library, student dormitories, sports and recreation centers are located in this campus.\n\nHacettepe University currently has thirteen faculties, eight vocational schools, one conservatory, thirteen institutes and forty one research centres. \nHacettepe University is a state university supported mainly by state funds allocated by the Turkish Parliament. Over 150 different undergraduate degree programs are offered and there are also over 200 different degree programs for postgraduate studies. The University has about 49582 students enrolled for undergraduate studies and academic staff of 3.279.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nBeytepe Campus also has a large artificial forest, where different sportive activities such as trekking, mountain-biking, running can be done and it is ideal for other recreational activities.\n\n===Other campuses===\n\n*Be\u015fevler Campus: (Located at the City Center) Houses the Turkish State Conservatory\n*Bala Campus: (Located in Bala, {{convert|67| km|mi|abbr=off|0}} south of Ankara) Houses Bala Vocational School\n*Polatl\u0131 Campus:  (Located in Polatl\u0131, a district {{convert|55| km|mi|abbr=off|0}} west of Ankara) Houses the Technical Sciences Vocational School, Health Services Vocational School\n\n==Academic units==\n\n=== Faculties & schools ===\n\n====Faculties====\n* '''[https://web.archive.org/web/20110625112836/http://www.iletisim.hacettepe.edu.tr/tr/ Faculty of Communication]'''\n* '''[https://web.archive.org/web/20110919100525/http://www.dis.hacettepe.edu.tr/indexweb.php Faculty of Dentistry]'''\n* '''[http://www.iibf.hacettepe.edu.tr/ Faculty of Economics and Administrative Sciences]'''\n**Economics\n**Business Administration\n**Family and Consumer Sciences\n**Health Administration\n**International Relations\n**Political Sciences and Public Administration\n**Public Finance\n**Social Work\n* '''[http://www.egitim.hacettepe.edu.tr/ Faculty of Education]'''\n**Computer Education and Instructional Technologies\n**'''Department of Educational Sciences'''\n***Curriculum and Instruction\n***Educational Administration\n***Supervision, Planning and Economics\n***Psychological Counselling and Guidance\n***Testing and Evaluation in Education\n**'''Department of Foreign Languages Teaching'''\n***English Language Teaching\n***French Language Teaching\n***German Language Teaching\n**'''Department of Primary Education'''\n***Elementary Teaching\n***Mathematics Teaching\n***Pre-School Teaching\n***Science Teaching\n**'''Department of Science and Mathematics for Secondary Education'''\n***Biology Education\n***Chemistry Education\n***Mathematics Education\n***Physics Education\n* '''[http://www.muhfak.hacettepe.edu.tr/ Faculty of Engineering]'''\n**Chemical Engineering\n**[http://cs.hacettepe.edu.tr/ Computer Engineering],\n**[http://ee.hacettepe.edu.tr/ Electrical & Electronics Engineering],\n**Environmental Engineering\n**[http://www.food.hacettepe.edu.tr/ Food Engineering]\n**Geological Engineering\n**[http://geomatik.hacettepe.edu.tr/ Geomatics Engineering],\n**Hydrogeological Engineering\n**[http://www.ie.hacettepe.edu.tr/ Industrial Engineering],\n**Mining Engineering\n**Nuclear Engineering\n**Physics Engineering\n**Mechanical Engineering (Automotive Engineering)\n* '''[http://www.gsf.hacettepe.edu.tr/ Faculty of Fine Arts]''' :\n**Ceramics\n**Graphic Arts\n**Interior Architecture And Environmental Design\n**Painting\n**Sculpture\n* '''[http://www.sbf.hacettepe.edu.tr/ Faculty of Health Sciences]'''\n**Child Development\n**Nursing\n**Nutrition and Dietetics\n**Occupational Therapy\n**Physiotherapy Rehabilitation\n* '''[http://www.hukukfakultesi.hacettepe.edu.tr/ Faculty of Law]'''\n* '''[http://www.edebiyat.hacettepe.edu.tr/ Faculty of Letters]'''\n**American Culture and Literature,\n**Archaeology,\n**English Language and Literature,\n**French Language and Literature,\n**German Language and Literature,\n**History,\n**History of Art,\n**Information Management,\n**Linguistics,\n**Philosophy,\n**Psychology,\n**Sociology,\n**'''Translation and Interpreting'''\n***English Translation and Interpreting\n***French Translation and Interpreting\n***German Translation and Interpreting\n**'''Turkish Language and Literature'''\n***Turkish Folklore\n\nThe Faculty Of Letters was established as Faculty of Science and Humanities in 1967, inaugurated between 1968-1969 and divided into Faculty of Literature and Faculty of Economics and Administrative Sciences on July 20, 1982. The Faculty of Letters has the highest student population of the University and has 15 academic units. It is located at Beytepe Campus, Ankara. This faculty has been publishing ''Edebiyat Fak\u00fcltesi Dergisi'' since 1983. The journal is published biannually. It contains news and innovations of humanities along with essays by Turkish and international authors.\n\n* '''[http://www.tip.hacettepe.edu.tr/ Faculty of Medicine]'''\n**Medicine (Turkish Medium)\n**Medicine (English Medium)\n* '''[https://web.archive.org/web/20110625113257/http://www.kastamonutip.hacettepe.edu.tr/ Faculty of Medicine at Kastamonu]'''\n* '''[http://www.eczacilik.hacettepe.edu.tr/ Faculty of Pharmacy]'''\n* '''[http://www.fenfakultesi.hacettepe.edu.tr/tr/ Faculty of Science]'''\n**Actuarial Sciences\n**Biology\n**Chemistry\n**Mathematics\n**Statistics\n\n==== Schools ====\n* '''School of Foreign Languages'''\n**Basic English Division\n**English Preparatory Division\n**German Preparatory Division\n**French Preparatory Division\n* '''School of Sports Science and Technology'''\n\n===Institutes===\n* Atat\u00fcrk Institute for Modern Turkish History\n* Institute of Child Health\n* Institute of Population Studies\n* Institute of Pure & Applied Sciences\n* Institute of Social Sciences\n* Institute of Health Sciences\n* Institute of Fine Arts\n* Institute of Public Health\n* Institute of Neurological Sciences\n* Institute of Nuclear Sciences\n* Institute of Oncology\n* Institute of Turkology Research\n* Environmental Research and Application Center (ERAC)\n\n===Vocational schools===\n*Bala Vocational School\n*Hacettepe Vocational School\n*Health Services Vocational School\n*Polatl\u0131 Health Services Vocational School\n*Polatl\u0131 Technical Science Vocational School\n*Social Sciences Vocational School\n\n==Notable people==\n\n===Alumni===\n*[[Bilge Yildiz|Bilge Y\u0131ld\u0131z]] - Associate Professor of Nuclear Science and Engineering, [[MIT]]<ref>[http://web.mit.edu/nse/people/faculty/yildiz.html Nuclear Science and Engineering, Massachusetts Institute of Technology<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n*Prof.Dr.Erkan [[:tr:Erkan \u0130bi\u015f|\u0130bi\u015f]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.erkanibis.com/wp/|title=Rector of Ankara University|last=Prof.Dr|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416162117/http://www.erkanibis.com/wp/|archivedate=2016-04-16}}</ref>-Rector of Ankara University<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/profdrerkanibis|title=Erkan \u0130bi\u015f (@profdrErkanibis) {{!}} Twitter|website=twitter.com|access-date=2016-04-16}}</ref>\n* [[Erdal Be\u015fik\u00e7io\u011flu]] - actor\n* [[U\u011fur Erdener]] - physician specialized in ophthalmology and professor\n* [[:tr:\u00c7a\u011fr\u0131 Erhan|\u00c7a\u011fr\u0131 Erhan]] - Rector of \u0130stanbul Kemerburgaz University\n* [[Erdal \u0130nci]] - new media artist\n* [[Tekin Bing\u00f6l]] - politician and doctor\n* Esen K. Akpek - Bendann Professor of Ophthalmology, Johns Hopkins University School of Medicine\n* [[:tr:Canan Da\u011fdeviren|Canan Da\u011fdeviren]] - Assistant Professor at MIT Media Lab\n* [[Esra Bilgi\u00e7| Esra Bilgi\u00e7 T\u00f6re]] - Actress\n\n==See also== \n* [[List of universities in Ankara]] \n* [[List of universities in Turkey]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n\n{{Universities and colleges in Ankara}}\n{{Universities in Turkey}}\n\n{{coord|39|52|02|N|32|44|04|E|region:TR-06_type:edu_source:kolossus-dewiki|display=title}}\n\n...\n\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Ankara]]\n[[Category:Hacettepe University|*]]\n[[Category:1967 establishments in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1967]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Major state university in Ankara, Turkey}}\n{{Infobox university\n|name = Hacettepe University\n|native_name = Hacettepe \u00dcniversitesi\n|motto = To the leading edge... Toward being the best...\n|image_name = Hacettepe University (emblem).png\n|image_size = 122px\n|established = 1967\n|type = [[Public University]]\n|rector = Haluk \u00d6zen\n|staff = 3638\n|students = 49582\n|city = [[Ankara]]\n|country = [[Turkey]]\n|affiliations = [[European University Association|EUA]]\n|campus = [[Urban area|Urban]] ({{convert|210,238 |m2|acre|0}}) <br>[[Suburban]] ({{convert|5,877,628| m2|acre|0}}) \n|mascot = Stag \n|logo = Hacettepe_University_logo.svg\n|logo_size = 250px\n|website = [http://www.hacettepe.edu.tr/ www.hacettepe.edu.tr]}}\n\n'''Hacettepe University''' is a major state [[university]] in [[Ankara]], [[Turkey]]. Based on academic performance, it ranks 1st among Turkish universities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tr.urapcenter.org/2018/2018_t9.php |title=URAP- University Rankings in Turkey}}</ref> \n\nThe University has two main campuses.  The first campus is located in the old town of Ankara and hosts the Medical Centre, and the second one, Beytepe Campus is {{convert|13|km|mi|abbr=on|0}} from the city centre.  The Beytepe Campus covers {{convert|6000000|m2|ha acre|abbr=on|0}} of green land and woodland, and hosts the faculties of Economic and Administrative Sciences, Law, Education, Engineering, Fine Arts, Letters, and Science. In addition to these two main campuses, the School of Social Work is located at Ke\u00e7i\u00f6ren, and the Turkish State Conservatory in Ankara, affiliated with the University as of 1982, is located at the Be\u015fevler Campus.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hacettepe.edu.tr/english/hakkinda/geneltanitim|title=Hacettepe University|website=www.hacettepe.edu.tr|access-date=2017-10-04}}</ref>.\n\n==General information==\n\n===History===\n[[Image:Museum of Anatolian Civilizations027.jpg|right|thumb|200px|The [[Hittites|Hittite]] stag, which served as the inspiration for the Hacettepe University emblem]]\nThe history of Hacettepe University can be traced back to the establishment of the Institute of Child Health on July 8, 1958, and the inauguration of the Hacettepe Children's Hospital founded by Prof. Dr. [[Ihsan Dogramaci|\u0130hsan Do\u011framac\u0131]]. In 1961 the School of Health Sciences and its divisions of Nursing, Medical Technology, Physical Therapy and Rehabilitation and Nutrition were opened, all centered on the Institute of Child Health.\n\nOn June 15, 1963, Hacettepe University, Faculty of Medicine was established and a general teaching hospital was built. Three months later Hacettepe University School of Dentistry was established.\n\nIn the summer of 1964, a School of Basic Sciences was opened, offering courses in the natural sciences, social sciences and the humanities. At the time, all Hacettepe teaching institutions were affiliated to Ankara University and grouped under the title \"Hacettepe Science Center\".\n\nHacettepe University was chartered through Act No. 892 of the Turkish Parliament on July 8, 1967. Hacettepe Institutes of Higher Education formed the core of Hacettepe University, and the Faculties of Medicine, Science and Engineering, and Social and Administrative sciences were established.\n\nIn 1969 Hacettepe School of Pharmacy and Health Administration were established. In 1971 with a reorganization, the former schools were given faculty status and thus they became the Faculty of Dentistry, Faculty of Engineering, Faculty of Pharmacy and Faculty of Science. In 1973 the School of Technology was established. In I982 the former faculties were reorganized as the Faculty of Letters, Faculty of Education, Faculty of Fine Arts, Faculty of Economic and Administrative Sciences and the State Conservatory was affiliated to Hacettepe University. In 1984 the School of Health services and in 1989 the School of Sport Sciences and Technology were established. Recently in 1998 the two Polatli; Vocational Schools and Kaman Vocational School have been established.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hacettepe.edu.tr/english/hakkinda/tarihce|title=Hacettepe University|website=www.hacettepe.edu.tr|access-date=2017-10-04}}</ref>\n\n===Official Seal===\nThe emblem of the University was designed in 1967 by Dr. Y\u00fccel Tanyeri, then a second year medical student, in the likeness of a stag \u2013 the symbol of a [[Hittite mythology|Hittite]] deity discovered at the royal tombs in [[Alacah\u00f6y\u00fck]]. Inspired by this archeological symbol common to the [[Central Anatolia|region]], the Stag was chosen as the symbol of the University, and was abstracted to represent a lowercase \"h\" \u2013 the first letter of the university's name.[https://web.archive.org/web/20070810010732/http://www.hacettepe.edu.tr/ortak/universite/oyku.php]\n\n===Rankings===\nIn 2018 US News Global University Rankings, Hacettepe University ranked 1st in Turkey and 208th globally, in clinical medicine <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/education/best-global-universities/search?region=asia&subject=clinical-medicine&page=3|title=US News - University Clinical Medicine Ranking by Academic Performance }}</ref> . In 2010, University Ranking by Academic Performance (URAP) ranked Hacettepe University 399th in the world and best university in Turkey.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.urapcenter.org |title=URAP - University Ranking by Academic Performance }}</ref>\nIn QS 2010 University ranking it is ranked 285 in the field of life sciences and medicine. In SCImagoir 2010 ranking it is ranked 354th worldwide, 114th in Western Europe, 1st in Turkey and 122nd worldwide in the field of Health Sciences. Locally Hacettepe University Faculty of Medicine is ranked the best in the country. Based on the minimum scores required to enroll in medical school, Hacettepe University holds the top spot among state schools for longer than a decade.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ogrencibulteni.com/2011-2012-tip-fakultesi-taban-puanlari.html |title=OSYM- Medical School Rankings by Minimum Scores |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120709025431/http://www.ogrencibulteni.com/2011-2012-tip-fakultesi-taban-puanlari.html |archivedate=2012-07-09 }}</ref> \n{{Clear}}\n\n==Campuses==\n\n=== Main Campus \u2013 Medical Center ===\n[[Image:Merkez1.jpg|right|thumb|200px|The Medical School on Main Campus, with old Ankara in the background.]]\nMain campus is located in S\u0131hhiye, Ankara. In this campus, the following are located: Faculties of Dentistry, Faculty of Medicine and Pharmacy, Institutes of Child Health, Health Sciences, Neurological Sciences, Oncology, Public Health and Population Studies, and Schools of Health Administration, HeaIth Technology, Home Economics, Nursing, Physical Therapy and Rehabilitation and Health Services, Teaching Hospitals (the Adult Hospital, Ihsan Dogramaci Children's Hospital and the Oncology Hospital), a biomedical library, biomedical research units, student dormitories, sports and recreation centers and clubs.\n\n===Beytepe Campus===\n\nThis campus is located in Beytepe. The faculties of Economic and Administrative Sciences, Education, Engineering, Fine Arts, Letters and Natural Sciences, Institutes of History of Modern Turkey, Natural Sciences, Nuclear Sciences and Social Sciences and Schools of Foreign Languages, and the Vocational School of Technology, School of Sport Sciences and Technology, and administrative offices, library, student dormitories, sports and recreation centers are located in this campus.\n\nHacettepe University currently has thirteen faculties, eight vocational schools, one conservatory, thirteen institutes and forty one research centres. \nHacettepe University is a state university supported mainly by state funds allocated by the Turkish Parliament. Over 150 different undergraduate degree programs are offered and there are also over 200 different degree programs for postgraduate studies. The University has about 49582 students enrolled for undergraduate studies and academic staff of 3.279.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nBeytepe Campus also has a large artificial forest, where different sportive activities such as trekking, mountain-biking, running can be done and it is ideal for other recreational activities.\n\n===Other campuses===\n\n*Be\u015fevler Campus: (Located at the City Center) Houses the Turkish State Conservatory\n*Bala Campus: (Located in Bala, {{convert|67| km|mi|abbr=off|0}} south of Ankara) Houses Bala Vocational School\n*Polatl\u0131 Campus:  (Located in Polatl\u0131, a district {{convert|55| km|mi|abbr=off|0}} west of Ankara) Houses the Technical Sciences Vocational School, Health Services Vocational School\n\n==Academic units==\n\n=== Faculties & schools ===\n\n====Faculties====\n* '''[https://web.archive.org/web/20110625112836/http://www.iletisim.hacettepe.edu.tr/tr/ Faculty of Communication]'''\n* '''[https://web.archive.org/web/20110919100525/http://www.dis.hacettepe.edu.tr/indexweb.php Faculty of Dentistry]'''\n* '''[http://www.iibf.hacettepe.edu.tr/ Faculty of Economics and Administrative Sciences]'''\n**Economics\n**Business Administration\n**Family and Consumer Sciences\n**Health Administration\n**International Relations\n**Political Sciences and Public Administration\n**Public Finance\n**Social Work\n* '''[http://www.egitim.hacettepe.edu.tr/ Faculty of Education]'''\n**Computer Education and Instructional Technologies\n**'''Department of Educational Sciences'''\n***Curriculum and Instruction\n***Educational Administration\n***Supervision, Planning and Economics\n***Psychological Counselling and Guidance\n***Testing and Evaluation in Education\n**'''Department of Foreign Languages Teaching'''\n***English Language Teaching\n***French Language Teaching\n***German Language Teaching\n**'''Department of Primary Education'''\n***Elementary Teaching\n***Mathematics Teaching\n***Pre-School Teaching\n***Science Teaching\n**'''Department of Science and Mathematics for Secondary Education'''\n***Biology Education\n***Chemistry Education\n***Mathematics Education\n***Physics Education\n* '''[http://www.muhfak.hacettepe.edu.tr/ Faculty of Engineering]'''\n**Chemical Engineering\n**[http://cs.hacettepe.edu.tr/ Computer Engineering],\n**[http://ee.hacettepe.edu.tr/ Electrical & Electronics Engineering],\n**Environmental Engineering\n**[http://www.food.hacettepe.edu.tr/ Food Engineering]\n**Geological Engineering\n**[http://geomatik.hacettepe.edu.tr/ Geomatics Engineering],\n**Hydrogeological Engineering\n**[http://www.ie.hacettepe.edu.tr/ Industrial Engineering],\n**Mining Engineering\n**Nuclear Engineering\n**Physics Engineering\n**Mechanical Engineering (Automotive Engineering)\n* '''[http://www.gsf.hacettepe.edu.tr/ Faculty of Fine Arts]''' :\n**Ceramics\n**Graphic Arts\n**Interior Architecture And Environmental Design\n**Painting\n**Sculpture\n* '''[http://www.sbf.hacettepe.edu.tr/ Faculty of Health Sciences]'''\n**Child Development\n**Nursing\n**Nutrition and Dietetics\n**Occupational Therapy\n**Physiotherapy Rehabilitation\n* '''[http://www.hukukfakultesi.hacettepe.edu.tr/ Faculty of Law]'''\n* '''[http://www.edebiyat.hacettepe.edu.tr/ Faculty of Letters]'''\n**American Culture and Literature,\n**Archaeology,\n**English Language and Literature,\n**French Language and Literature,\n**German Language and Literature,\n**History,\n**History of Art,\n**Information Management,\n**Linguistics,\n**Philosophy,\n**Psychology,\n**Sociology,\n**'''Translation and Interpreting'''\n***English Translation and Interpreting\n***French Translation and Interpreting\n***German Translation and Interpreting\n**'''Turkish Language and Literature'''\n***Turkish Folklore\n\nThe Faculty Of Letters was established as Faculty of Science and Humanities in 1967, inaugurated between 1968-1969 and divided into Faculty of Literature and Faculty of Economics and Administrative Sciences on July 20, 1982. The Faculty of Letters has the highest student population of the University and has 15 academic units. It is located at Beytepe Campus, Ankara. This faculty has been publishing ''Edebiyat Fak\u00fcltesi Dergisi'' since 1983. The journal is published biannually. It contains news and innovations of humanities along with essays by Turkish and international authors.\n\n* '''[http://www.tip.hacettepe.edu.tr/ Faculty of Medicine]'''\n**Medicine (Turkish Medium)\n**Medicine (English Medium)\n* '''[https://web.archive.org/web/20110625113257/http://www.kastamonutip.hacettepe.edu.tr/ Faculty of Medicine at Kastamonu]'''\n* '''[http://www.eczacilik.hacettepe.edu.tr/ Faculty of Pharmacy]'''\n* '''[http://www.fenfakultesi.hacettepe.edu.tr/tr/ Faculty of Science]'''\n**Actuarial Sciences\n**Biology\n**Chemistry\n**Mathematics\n**Statistics\n\n==== Schools ====\n* '''School of Foreign Languages'''\n**Basic English Division\n**English Preparatory Division\n**German Preparatory Division\n**French Preparatory Division\n* '''School of Sports Science and Technology'''\n\n===Institutes===\n* Atat\u00fcrk Institute for Modern Turkish History\n* Institute of Child Health\n* Institute of Population Studies\n* Institute of Pure & Applied Sciences\n* Institute of Social Sciences\n* Institute of Health Sciences\n* Institute of Fine Arts\n* Institute of Public Health\n* Institute of Neurological Sciences\n* Institute of Nuclear Sciences\n* Institute of Oncology\n* Institute of Turkology Research\n* Environmental Research and Application Center (ERAC)\n\n===Vocational schools===\n*Bala Vocational School\n*Hacettepe Vocational School\n*Health Services Vocational School\n*Polatl\u0131 Health Services Vocational School\n*Polatl\u0131 Technical Science Vocational School\n*Social Sciences Vocational School\n\n==Notable people==\n\n===Alumni===\n*[[Bilge Yildiz|Bilge Y\u0131ld\u0131z]] - Associate Professor of Nuclear Science and Engineering, [[MIT]]<ref>[http://web.mit.edu/nse/people/faculty/yildiz.html Nuclear Science and Engineering, Massachusetts Institute of Technology<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n*Prof.Dr.Erkan [[:tr:Erkan \u0130bi\u015f|\u0130bi\u015f]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.erkanibis.com/wp/|title=Rector of Ankara University|last=Prof.Dr|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416162117/http://www.erkanibis.com/wp/|archivedate=2016-04-16}}</ref>-Rector of Ankara University<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/profdrerkanibis|title=Erkan \u0130bi\u015f (@profdrErkanibis) {{!}} Twitter|website=twitter.com|access-date=2016-04-16}}</ref>\n* [[Erdal Be\u015fik\u00e7io\u011flu]] - actor\n* [[U\u011fur Erdener]] - physician specialized in ophthalmology and professor\n* [[:tr:\u00c7a\u011fr\u0131 Erhan|\u00c7a\u011fr\u0131 Erhan]] - Rector of \u0130stanbul Kemerburgaz University\n* [[Erdal \u0130nci]] - new media artist\n* [[Tekin Bing\u00f6l]] - politician and doctor\n* Esen K. Akpek - Bendann Professor of Ophthalmology, Johns Hopkins University School of Medicine\n* [[:tr:Canan Da\u011fdeviren|Canan Da\u011fdeviren]] - Assistant Professor at MIT Media Lab\n* [[Esra Bilgi\u00e7| Esra Bilgi\u00e7 T\u00f6re]] - Actress\n\n==See also== \n* [[List of universities in Ankara]] \n* [[List of universities in Turkey]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n\n{{Universities and colleges in Ankara}}\n{{Universities in Turkey}}\n\n{{coord|39|52|02|N|32|44|04|E|region:TR-06_type:edu_source:kolossus-dewiki|display=title}}\n\n...\n\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Ankara]]\n[[Category:Hacettepe University|*]]\n[[Category:1967 establishments in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1967]]\n", "name_user": "Mertsalman", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRankings", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hacettepe_University"}
{"title_page": "Petersfield Museum", "text_new": "{{short description|Local museum in Petersfield, Hampshire, England}}\n{{refimprove|date=February 2019}}\n{{coord|51.0030|-0.9362|display=title|region:GB_scale:2000}}\n\n\n'''Petersfield Museum''' tells the story of the historical market town of Petersfield and surrounding villages, its people and landscapes and is home to a number of nationally significant collections. Located in Petersfield\u2019s Victorian Police Station and Courthouse, close to the centre of the town and in the heart of the South Downs National Park (SDNPA), the museum encompasses a complete Victorian justice complex including original cells, exercise yard, stables and cart shed.\n\nThe museum is currently undergoing a major redevelopment project (Pathways into the Past) and is closed to the public but will reopen in 2021!  \n\n==Location==\nPetersfield Museum is housed in the old Police Station and Courthouse on St Peter\u2019s Road in the centre of Petersfield.\n\n==Origins==\nPetersfield Museum opened its doors for the first time on the 15th May 1999 after almost a decade of planning. The idea of a museum in the town was first muted by the Chairman of the Petersfield Area Historical Society (PAHS) and along with the dedication and enthusiasm of the group\u2019s members strived to make it happen. \nThe Petersfield Museum Trust was established in 1996 and in the same year singed the lease for the recently disused Magistrates Court. \non the 15th May 1999, Petersfield Museum was opened for the very first time, manned by volunteers and using the artefacts donated by the PAHS. The Museum was open on Wednesdays and Saturdays and the first exhibition included a Victorian penny farthing, the town charter and Minibrix.\nEver since first opening, the museum has continuously grown and developed at an astonishing rate, to today where it is in the process of a multi-million-pound National Lottery Heritage Fund redevelopment.\n\n==Collections==\nThe Museum holds photographs, archives, oral history and maps relating to the town and surrounding area. A timeline feature takes the visitor through the history of the town alongside some temporary cases which  change over annually.\n\n===Archaeology===\nThe Museum\u2019s highly successful HLF-funded People of the Heath archaeological investigation focuses on a remarkable but little-known Early Bronze Age monument complex on the edge of the town. Dating to 2200 \u2013 1500 BC this group of barrows is one of the most impressive to have survived in south east England. Our project is giving rise to significant findings including, several rare collared burial urns and pots. In addition, Mesolithic Flints dating back to 8,000 years BC have been found during separate investigations undertaken on the same site and at the same time. This project is contributing towards the national body of knowledge regarding Bronze Age burials and has proved a huge stimulus for local interest in the area\u2019s history, including attracting dozens of dedicated new local volunteers to work on the project. \n\n===Social History===\nThis rich collection of archival material, documents and objects boasts a collection of over 8,500 photographs documenting the history of the local area. The artefact collection ranges from agricultural tools to objects that tell the stories of Petersfield industries, including the brewing industry and ITS (the rubber factory that made the famous Minibrix, forerunner of Lego), to domestic items offering insights into the lives of Petersfield\u2019s residents. We hold 80 oral history interviews, recorded in the time since the Museum\u2019s foundation. \n\n===Don Eades===\nIn 2015, the Museum was donated a collection of c100,000 photographic negatives taken by local press photographer Don Eades between 1962 and 1987. These images give a unique history and record of life in Petersfield and the surrounding area from that period. \n\n===Bedales Historic Dress===\nIncludes over 1,000 items from the 18th Century to modern day and was built up over a 50-year period by the local Bedales School. The collection mirrors 250 years of social and cultural change and includes rare and nationally significant pieces including an item recently loaned to the Design Museum for the \u2018Women Fashion Power\u2019 exhibition. A number of garments have strong local provenance and the great majority of the collection formed part of Bedales\u2019 theatre wardrobe. \n\n===[[Flora Twort]]===\nEncompassing nearly 1,000 works by local artist [[Flora Twort]], her most famous works document \u2018old Petersfield\u2019 including the cattle market and the famous horse fair on Petersfield Heath. Flora was part of a bohemian set of artists around the physician and social activist Dr Harry Roberts, who spent much of their time near Petersfield and socialised with renowned literary figures of the day. Flora was an artist of considerable merit and her work includes many instantly recognisable Petersfield locations and people. Her art offers insights into the past life of the town and the countryside which she recorded with great attention to detail. In this sense the collection is a valuable historical resource that links closely to the local area whilst, at the same time, the quality and breadth of her work makes it an invaluable source for art education. \n\n==Pathways into the Past==\nPathways into the Past is Petersfield Museum's \u00a33.7million National Lottery Heritage Funded redevelopment project. The project will transform the buildings, exhibitions and programmes as well as create an exciting new outdoor space in the courtyard. There will have room to show far more than ever before, putting Petersfield Museum and its glorious surroundings on the map for local people and tourists alike. \nFor the first time the museum's collections will be combined to tell a cohesive story of Petersfield and the surrounding villages. There will also be a servery for food and drink, a dedicated learning space for educational groups as well as an exciting new programme of events from film screenings to lectures, gin tasting to after school clubs. There will also be a new gallery allowing the museum to host travelling exhibitions from national museum's.    \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.petersfieldmuseum.co.uk Petersfield Museum and the Flora Twort Gallery]\n* [http://www.culture24.org.uk/se000572 Entry] in the [[24 Hour Museum]]\n\n[[Category:Museums established in 1999]]\n[[Category:Petersfield]]\n[[Category:History of Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Museums in Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Local museums in Hampshire]]\n[[Category:1999 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Art museums and galleries in Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Biographical museums in Hampshire]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Local museum in Petersfield, Hampshire, England}}\n{{refimprove|date=February 2019}}\n{{coord|51.0030|-0.9362|display=title|region:GB_scale:2000}}\n\n\n'''Petersfield Museum''' tells the story of the historical market town of Petersfield and surrounding villages, its people and landscapes and is home to a number of nationally significant collections. Located in Petersfield\u2019s Victorian Police Station and Courthouse, close to the centre of the town and in the heart of the South Downs National Park (SDNPA), the museum encompasses a complete Victorian justice complex including original cells, exercise yard, stables and cart shed.  \n\n==Location==\nPetersfield Museum is housed in the old Police Station and Courthouse on St Peter\u2019s Road in the centre of Petersfield.\n\n==Origins==\nThe museum was formed by a group of local historians, 'The Petersfield Area Historical Society'.<ref>{{cite web|title=Petersfield Area Historical Society: Continued support for the museum|url=http://www.petersfieldhistoricalsociety.org/news/45-continued-support-for-the-museum|accessdate=28 February 2019}}</ref> Over the years, objects and archive material were collected, later formally transferred to the Museum, and now form the extensive collections. The Museum has been open since 1999 and holds materials that relates to the town of Petersfield and the surrounding villages.\n\n==Collections==\nThe Museum holds photographs, archives, oral history and maps relating to the town and surrounding area. A timeline feature takes the visitor through the history of the town alongside some temporary cases which  change over annually.\n\n===Archaeology===\nThe Museum\u2019s highly successful HLF-funded People of the Heath archaeological investigation focuses on a remarkable but little-known Early Bronze Age monument complex on the edge of the town. Dating to 2200 \u2013 1500 BC this group of barrows is one of the most impressive to have survived in south east England. Our project is giving rise to significant findings including, several rare collared burial urns and pots. In addition, Mesolithic Flints dating back to 8,000 years BC have been found during separate investigations undertaken on the same site and at the same time. This project is contributing towards the national body of knowledge regarding Bronze Age burials and has proved a huge stimulus for local interest in the area\u2019s history, including attracting dozens of dedicated new local volunteers to work on the project. \n\n===Social History===\nThis rich collection of archival material, documents and objects boasts a collection of over 8,500 photographs documenting the history of the local area. The artefact collection ranges from agricultural tools to objects that tell the stories of Petersfield industries, including the brewing industry and ITS (the rubber factory that made the famous Minibrix, forerunner of Lego), to domestic items offering insights into the lives of Petersfield\u2019s residents. We hold 80 oral history interviews, recorded in the time since the Museum\u2019s foundation. \n\n===Don Eades===\nIn 2015, the Museum was donated a collection of c100,000 photographic negatives taken by local press photographer Don Eades between 1962 and 1987. These images give a unique history and record of life in Petersfield and the surrounding area from that period. \n\n===Bedales Historic Dress===\nIncludes over 1,000 items from the 18th Century to modern day and was built up over a 50-year period by the local Bedales School. The collection mirrors 250 years of social and cultural change and includes rare and nationally significant pieces including an item recently loaned to the Design Museum for the \u2018Women Fashion Power\u2019 exhibition. A number of garments have strong local provenance and the great majority of the collection formed part of Bedales\u2019 theatre wardrobe. \n\n===[[Flora Twort]]===\nEncompassing nearly 1,000 works by local artist [[Flora Twort]], her most famous works document \u2018old Petersfield\u2019 including the cattle market and the famous horse fair on Petersfield Heath. Flora was part of a bohemian set of artists around the physician and social activist Dr Harry Roberts, who spent much of their time near Petersfield and socialised with renowned literary figures of the day. Flora was an artist of considerable merit and her work includes many instantly recognisable Petersfield locations and people. Her art offers insights into the past life of the town and the countryside which she recorded with great attention to detail. In this sense the collection is a valuable historical resource that links closely to the local area whilst, at the same time, the quality and breadth of her work makes it an invaluable source for art education. \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.petersfieldmuseum.co.uk Petersfield Museum and the Flora Twort Gallery]\n* [http://www.culture24.org.uk/se000572 Entry] in the [[24 Hour Museum]]\n\n[[Category:Museums established in 1999]]\n[[Category:Petersfield]]\n[[Category:History of Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Museums in Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Local museums in Hampshire]]\n[[Category:1999 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Art museums and galleries in Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Biographical museums in Hampshire]]\n", "name_user": "Petersfield Museum", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Petersfield_Museum"}
{"title_page": "Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa", "text_new": "{{redirect|Mahakassapa|other uses|Kassapa (disambiguation){{!}}Kassapa}}\n{{short description|Principal disciple of Gautama Buddha and leader at the First Council}}\n{{Infobox religious biography\n|honorific-prefix = [[Thero|The elder]]\n|name = Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa\n|image = File:Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa meets an \u0100j\u012bvika and learns of the parinirvana, Gandhara sculpture.jpg\n|alt = Shaven monk in robes standing next to naked, shaved man\n|caption = Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa (left) meets an ''[[\u0101j\u012bvika]]'' ascetic (right) and learns of the ''[[Parinirvana|parinirv\u0101na]]'' of the Buddha, [[Gandhara|Gandh\u0101ran]] sculpture. {{Circa}} 2nd\u20133rd century CE.\n|birth_name = Pippali\n|birth_date = 120 years before the Buddha's passing away\n|birth_place = Mah\u0101tittha, Magadha\n|death_date = 20 years after the Buddha's passing away\n|death_place = In [[Kukku\u1e6dap\u0101da]] Mountain, [[Magadha]]. According to many traditional accounts, still alive there\n|nationality = Magadha\n|religion = Buddhism\n|school = all, but most honored in [[Theravada|Therav\u0101da]] and [[Chan Buddhism]]\n|known_for = Leader of the [[First Buddhist Council]]; foremost in [[dhutanga|ascetic practices]] ({{lang-pi|dhutav\u0101d\u0101na\u1e43|italic=yes}})\n|other_names = ''Dhutaraja''{{sfn |Tournier |2014 |p=27}}\n|teacher = [[Gautama Buddha]]\n|education=''[[brahmin]]'' education\n|successor = [[\u0100nanda]]\n|students = \u015aro\u1e47a-Ko\u1e6dikar\u1e47a; Bhadra-Kapil\u0101n\u012b\n|parents = Father Nyagrodha, Kapila or Kosigotta; mother Suman\u0101dev\u012b\n}}\n\n'''Mah\u0101 K\u0101\u015byapa''' or '''Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa''' ({{lang-pi|Mah\u0101kassapa}}) was one of [[The ten principal disciples|the principal disciples]] of [[Gautama Buddha]].{{sfn |Tambiah |1984 |p=22}} He is regarded in Buddhism as an [[arhat|enlightened disciple]], being [[\u015ar\u0101vaka#Foremost disciples|foremost]] in [[dhutanga|ascetic practice]]. Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa assumed leadership of the [[Sangha|monastic community]] following the ''[[Paranirvana|paranirv\u0101\u1e47a]]'' (death) of the Buddha, presiding over the [[First Buddhist council|First Buddhist Council]]. He was considered to be the first [[zushi (Buddhism)|patriarch]] in a number of [[early Buddhism|early Buddhist schools]] and continued to have an important role as patriarch in the [[Chan Buddhism|Chan]] and [[Zen]] traditions. In Buddhist texts, he assumed many identities, that of a renunciant saint, a lawgiver, an anti-establishment figure, but also a \"guarantor of future justice\" in the time of Maitreya{{sfn |Ray |1994 |p=117}}{{em dash}}he has been described as \"both the anchorite and the friend of mankind, even of the outcast\".{{sfn |Rhys Davids |1914 |p=160}}\n\nIn canonical Buddhist texts in several traditions, Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa was born as Pippali in a ''[[brahmin]]'' family, and entered an arranged marriage with a woman named [[Bhadda Kapilani|Bhadra-Kapil\u0101n\u012b]]. Both of them aspired to lead a celibate life, however, and they decided not to consummate their marriage. Having grown weary of the agricultural profession and the damage it did, they both left the lay life behind to become mendicants. Pippali later met the Buddha, under whom he was [[upasampada|ordained as a monk]], named ''K\u0101\u015byapa'', but later called ''Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa'' to distinguish him from other disciples. Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa became an important disciple of the Buddha, to the extent that the Buddha exchanged his [[Kasaya (clothing)|robe]] with him, which was a symbol of the transmittance of the [[Buddha's Dispensation|Buddhist teaching]]. He became foremost in [[dhutanga|ascetic practices]] and attained [[enlightenment in Buddhism|enlightenment]] shortly after. He often had disputes with [[\u0100nanda]], the attendant of the Buddha, due to their different dispositions and views. Despite his ascetic, strict and stern reputation, he paid an interest in community matters and teaching, and was known for his compassion for the poor, which sometimes caused him to be depicted as an anti-establishment figure. He had a prominent role in the cremation of the Buddha, acting as a sort of eldest son of the Buddha, as well as being the leader in the subsequent First Council. He is depicted as hesitatingly allowing \u0100nanda to participate in the council, and chastising him afterwards for a number of offenses the latter was regarded to have committed.\n\nMah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa's life as described in the early Buddhist texts has been considerably studied by scholars, who have been skeptical about his role in the cremation, his role toward \u0100nanda and the historical validity of the council itself. A number of scholars have hypothesized that the accounts have later been embellished to emphasize the values of the Buddhist establishment Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa stood for, emphasizing [[vinaya|monastic discipline]], ''brahmin'' and ascetic values, as opposed to the values of \u0100nanda and other disciples. Regardless, it is clear that Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa had an important role in the early days of the Buddhist community after the Buddha's ''parinirv\u0101\u1e47a'', to help establish a stable monastic tradition. He effectively became the leader for the first twenty years after the Buddha, as he had become the most influential figure in the monastic community. For this reason, he was regarded by many early Buddhist schools as a sort of first patriarch, and was seen to have started a [[lineage (Buddhism)|lineage]] of patriarchs of Buddhism. This further amplified the idea of him being the primary heir and eldest son of the Buddha, which came to be symbolized by the robe Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa had received.\n\nIn many post-canonical texts, Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa decided at the end of his life to enter a state of [[Nirodha-sam\u0101patti|meditation and suspended animation]], which was believed to cause his physical remains to stay intact in a cave under a mountain called [[Kukku\u1e6dap\u0101da]], until the coming of [[Maitreya Buddha]] in a next age. This story has led to several [[cult (religious practice)|cults]] and practices, and affected some Buddhist countries up until early modern times. It has been interpreted by scholars as a narrative to physically connect Gautama Buddha with the next Buddha Maitreya, through the body of Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa and Gautama Buddha's robe, which covered Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa's remains. In Chan Buddhism, this account was less emphasized, but Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa was seen to have received a special mind-to-mind transmission from Gautama Buddha outside of orthodox scripture, which became essential to the identity of Chan. Again, the robe was an important symbol in this transmission. Apart from having a role in texts and lineage, Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa has often been depicted in Buddhist art as a symbol of reassurance and hope for the future of Buddhism.\n\n== In early Buddhist texts ==\nIn the [[Early Buddhist Texts]] of several textual traditions, a dozen [[sutra|discourses]] attributed to Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa have been compiled in a separate section. In the P\u0101li tradition, this is part of the collection called the ''[[Sa\u1e43yutta Nik\u0101ya]]'', and in the [[Chinese Buddhist canon|Chinese Buddhist texts]], the collection is called the ''[[\u0100gama (Buddhism)#Sa\u1e43yukta \u0100gama|Sa\u1e43yukta \u0100gama]]''. The latter collection contains two versions of the section on Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa, numbered [[Taisho Tripitaka|Taish\u014d]] 2:99 and 2:100.{{sfn |Mun-keat |2017 |p=295}} The Chinese ''[[Ekottara Agama|Ekottara \u0100gama]]'' also contains a passage that runs parallel to the P\u0101li ''Sa\u1e43yutta'', T2:99 and T2:100, describing a meeting between the Buddha and Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa,{{sfn |Analayo |2015 |pp=12\u201321}} and another passage about him and the monk [[Bakkula]].{{sfn |Analayo |2010 |p=1}} Finally, there are also [[Vinaya]] texts from the [[M\u016blasarv\u0101stiv\u0101da]] tradition about Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa in [[Tibetan Buddhist canon|Tibetan language]].{{sfn |Clarke |2014 |p=110}}\n\n=== Early life ===\n[[File:Pipphali.jpg|thumb|Pippala Cave in [[Rajgir]], where Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa is recorded to have stayed.{{sfn |Bapat |1956 |p=319}}]]\nP\u0101li accounts relate that Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa was born Pippali in a ''[[brahmin]]'' family in a village called Mah\u0101tittha, [[Magadha]], present-day India.{{sfn |Karaluvinna |2002 |p=435}} His father was a wealthy landlord who in some sources is named Nyagrodha, and in other sources Kapila or Kosigotta; his mother was Suman\u0101dev\u012b.{{refn |For the father's occupation, see {{harvtxt |Buswell |Lopez |2013 |loc=Bhadra-Kapil\u0101n\u012b}}. For Nyagrodha, see {{harvtxt |Clarke |2014 |p=110}}. For the other names, see {{harvtxt |Karaluvinna |2002 |p=435}}.}} His body had some of the [[Physical characteristics of the Buddha#The 32 Signs of a Great Man|thirty-two characteristics of a Great Man]] ({{lang-sa|Mah\u0101puru\u1e63alak\u1e63a\u1e47a|italic=yes}}; {{lang-pi|Mah\u0101purissalakkha\u1e47a|italic=yes}}), which in Buddhism are seen as the characteristics of a future Buddha.{{refn |{{harvtxt |Buswell |Lopez |2013 |loc=Bhadra-Kapil\u0101n\u012b; Mah\u0101puru\u1e63alak\u1e63a\u1e47a}} state he had seven characteristics, referring to P\u0101li sources; {{harvtxt |Kim |2011 |pp=135\u2013136}} refers to sources that state he had thirty.}} From his youth onward, he was inclined toward living a spiritual life rather than marrying, but his father wanted him to wed. To send his father on a wild goose chase, he agreed to marry but then produced a perfect golden statue of a woman, and asked his father to find him a woman that matched the statue. Four copies of the image were taken throughout the country to find the right woman.<!--110--> A ''brahmin'' from Kapila{{refn |group=note |P\u0101li sources have [[Sagala|S\u0101gala]] instead, which is in present-day Pakistan. The ''brahmin'' is called Kosigotta in the P\u0101li sources, though in some of these sources this name is used for Pippali's father.{{sfn |Karaluvinna |2002 |p=435}}}} had a daughter called [[Bhadda Kapilani|Bhadra-Kapil\u0101n\u012b]] ({{lang-pi|Bhadd\u0101-kapil\u0101n\u012b}}), who had no interest in a family life either. However, her parents wanted her to marry, and to please her mother, she agreed to pay her respects to a shrine of a goddess known for granting a marriage in a high-class family. When she approached the image, however, people noticed that the image appeared ugly compared to her. Her reputation of beauty spread, and soon after Pippali's family learned about her, she was offered in marriage to Pippali.<!--111-->{{sfn |Clarke |2014 |pp=110\u2013111}}\n\nNext, in the P\u0101li version of the story, the two exchanged letters to indicate their lack of interest, only to find their letters intercepted by their parents and being forced to marry anyway.{{sfn |Buswell |Lopez |2013 |loc=Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa}} In the M\u016blasarv\u0101stiv\u0101da version of the story, however, Pippali went to visit Bhadra, and without revealing his identity, told her that her future husband would be a bad choice for her, because he had no interest in sensual pleasures. She replied she also did not care for such matters, whereupon he revealed that he was her future husband.{{sfn |Clarke |2014 |p=111}} Although the two agreed to marry, they decided to live celibately, according to both versions of the story.{{sfn |Clarke |2014 |p=111}}{{sfn |Buswell |Lopez |2013 |loc=Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa}} Pippali's parents continued to push them to give up their shared celibacy, but to no avail.{{sfn |Clarke |2014 |p=111}}\n\nPippali is depicted in the texts as very wealthy, using much perfume and possessing much land and chariots.{{sfn |Karaluvinna |2002 |p=435}} Later, in the P\u0101li version, Pippali and Bhadra saw animals eating each other on the fertile fields as they were plowed by their workers. The sight brought pity and fear to them, and they determined to live a mendicant live instead, and leave the agricultural business behind.{{sfn |Buswell |Lopez |2013 |loc=Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa}} In the M\u016blasarv\u0101stiv\u0101da version, it was the pitiful sight of the workers instead which brought Pippali to leave his lay life.{{sfn |Clarke |2014 |p=112}} The two went their separate ways, as not to grow any attachment to each other, and to prevent gossip and disrepute.{{refn |For the attachment, see {{harvtxt |Clarke |2014 |p=112}}. For the gossip, see {{harvtxt |Karaluvinna |2002 |p=436}}.}} Shortly after that,{{refn |group=note |Later texts such as the ''[[Mahavastu|Mah\u0101vastu]]'' state this was a year after he left his household life.{{sfn |Ray |1994 |p=106}}}} Pippali met the Buddha, was struck with devotion when [[Dar\u015bana|seeing him]], recognized him as a teacher, and was ordained under him. Thenceforth, he was called ''K\u0101\u015byapa''.{{refn |See {{harvtxt |Buswell |Lopez |2013 |loc=Bhadra-Kapil\u0101n\u012b}}. {{harvtxt |Ray |1994 |p=115}} connects this event with ''dar\u015bana''. {{harvtxt |Malalasekera |1937 |loc=volume 2, [http://www.palikanon.com/english/pali_names/maha/maha_kassapa_th.htm Mah\u0101kassapa]}} hypothesized that ''K\u0101\u015byapa'' was probably his ''[[gotra]]'' name.}} \"The mutual recognition between master and disciple is immediate and intimate.\"{{sfn |Ray |1994 |p=115}} As he ordained him, the Buddha gave three directives to practice: K\u0101\u015byapa should develop a [[Repentance#Buddhism|\"lively sense of fear and regard\"]] towards his fellow monastics, regardless of their status; K\u0101\u015byapa should attentively listen and practice the [[dharma (Buddhism)|teachings of the Buddha]] ({{lang-sa|Dharma}}; {{lang-pi|Dhamma}}); and he should live in [[mindfulness (Buddhism)|mindfulness]].{{sfn |Karaluvinna |2002 |p=436}}\n\n=== Monastic life ===\n[[File:\uac00\uc12d\uc874\uc790\uc0c1 \uc870\uc120-\u8fe6\u8449\u5c0a\u8005\u50cf \u671d\u9bae-Kashyapa MET DP105204.jpg|A young Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa, wood, eighteenth century, Korea|thumb |alt=Monk in Chinese-style robes, bowing in respect with hands clasped and smiling]]\n<!-- disabled for the moment [[File:Wat Intharam (Wat Bang Yi Ruea Nok) - Mahakassapa (Mahakasyapa) pay respect to Lord Buddha's body (2).JPG|thumb|Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa pays respect to the Buddha's body; {{ill|Intharam Temple|th|\u0e27\u0e31\u0e14\u0e2d\u0e34\u0e19\u0e17\u0e32\u0e23\u0e32\u0e21}}, Bangkok, Thailand]]-->\nWhen the two met,<!--183--> (or in some versions, some time later)<!--185--> Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa exchanged his fine and expensive [[Kasaya (clothing)#Sa\u1e43gh\u0101ti|robe]] with that of the Buddha, a [[Buddhist funeral#Pansukula|robe made of rags]].<!--183--> The exchange came to be seen a gesture of great respect the Buddha had made,<!--182-->{{sfn |Silk |2003 |pp=182\u2013183 note 25, 185}} which was unprecedented, and a sign that Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa would preside over the First Council after the Buddha's demise.{{refn |For the sign, see {{harvtxt |Buswell |Lopez |2013 |loc=Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa}}. For the exchange being unprecedented, see {{harvtxt |Karaluvinna |2002 |p=436}}.}} Early and later texts from different traditions leave the impression that only a person with the great [[merit (Buddhism)|merit]] as Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa would be able to wear the robe.<!--187--> The only reason the robe was highly valuable that it had been worn by the Buddha, even though it had been obtained from what was considered the lowest source, that is, a female slave discarded in a [[charnel ground]].<!--189--> The exchange also echoed a similar exchange that took place after the Buddha's [[Great Renunciation]], when he swapped his lay robes with a hunter in the forest.<!--190--> Finally, the fact that it was a rag-robe contributed to the ascetic identity of the figure of Mah\u0101ka\u015byapa.<!--195-->{{sfn |Silk |2003 |pp=187, 189\u2013190, 195}}\n\nThroughout cultures, \"inalienable possessions\", often textiles, were symbols of authority and continuity in a family.{{sfn |Adamek |2011 |p=24}} Gautama Buddha giving his robe to Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa in the latter's early monastic years demonstrated a deep sense of respect for this disciple. Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa was seen to safeguard this robe to pass on to the future Buddha. Thus, the robe came to represent a passing on of the [[Dharma transmission|transmission of Buddhist teachings]], and Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa became a symbol of the continuity of the [[Buddha's Dispensation|Buddha's dispensation]].{{refn |See {{harvtxt|Sanvido |2017 |p=343}}. For the symbol of continuity, see {{harvtxt |Adamek |2011 |loc=Bodhidharma's Robe}} and {{harvtxt |Analayo |2015 |p=21}}.}} On a similar note, the robe, which in the early accounts was a rag-robe, is a symbol of rebirth and impermanence:<!--221--> rag-robes have historically been associated much with death, and in the early texts, the robe came from a corpse.<!--220--> In a late P\u0101li account, the same robe is also associated with birth, an association that has also been found in the fieldwork of anthropologist [[Fran\u00e7ois Bizot]], done in Cambodian temples.<!--221-->{{sfn |Strong |2007 |p=220}} On a similar note, from the fourteenth century onward,<!--352--> Japanese esoteric ''[[kirigami (Soto Zen)|kirigami]]'' texts describe the robe transmitted from Gautama Buddha to Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa as a symbol of birth and gestation.<!--361-362--> South-east Asian scholar [[Paul Mus]] (1902\u20131969) compared the transmittance of the robe of Gautama Buddha to Maitreya Buddha with [[R\u0101jy\u0101bhi\u1e63eka|Indian consecration rituals for kings]], in which a king's robe is equated with the placenta, through which rebirth takes place.{{sfn |Faure |1994 |pp=361\u2013362}}\n\nThe Buddha exhorted Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa that he should practice himself [[Bahujana sukhaya bahujana hitaya cha#In Buddhism|\"for the welfare and happiness of the multitude\"]] and impressed upon him that he should take upon himself [[dhutanga|ascetic practices]] ({{lang-sa|dh\u016btagu\u1e47a|italic=yes}}, {{lang-pi|dhuta\u1e45ga|italic=yes}}).{{sfn |Kim |2011 |p=137}} Accordingly, Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa took upon him the thirteen ascetic practices (including living in the wilderness, living only from [[alms#Buddhism|alms]] and wearing rag-robes){{sfn |Silk |2003 |p=179}} and became an enlightened disciple (''[[arahat]]'') in nine days.{{sfn |Ray |1994 |p=106}} He was then called 'K\u0101\u015byapa the Great' ({{lang-sa|Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa}}), because of his good qualities, and to distinguish him from other monks with the same name.{{refn |See {{harvtxt |Clarke |2014 |p=112}} and {{harvtxt |Karaluvinna |2002 |p=435}}. Only Karaluvinna explains the reason.}}{{refn |group=note |Buddhist studies scholar {{ill |Jonathan Silk|nl}} raises the question whether this epithet may have only become current later, and was not yet used by the Buddha himself.{{sfn |Silk |2003 |pp=175\u2013176 note 5}}}}\n\nMah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa was one of the most revered of the Buddha's disciples, the renunciant par excellence.{{sfn |Clarke |2014 |p=107}}{{sfn |Karaluvinna |2002 |p=438}} He was praised by the Buddha as foremost in ascetic practices ({{lang-pi|dhutav\u0101d\u0101na\u1e43|italic=yes}}) and a foremost forest dweller.{{refn |For the P\u0101li term , see {{harvtxt |Malalasekera |1937 |loc=vol. 2, [http://www.palikanon.com/english/pali_names/maha/maha_kassapa_th.htm Mah\u0101kassapa]}}. For being a forest dweller, see {{harvtxt |Kim |2011 |p=131}}.}} He excelled in [[\u1e5addhi|supernatural accomplishments]] ({{lang-pi|iddhi|italic=yes}}; {{lang-sa|\u1e5bddhi|italic=yes}}) and was equal to the Buddha in [[jhana|meditative absorption]] ({{lang-pi|jh\u0101na|italic=yes}}; {{lang-sa |dy\u0101na |italic=yes}}).{{refn |{{harvtxt |Buswell |Lopez |2013 |loc=Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa}} says he was second to the Buddha in this, whereas {{harvtxt |Karaluvinna |2002 |p=438}} and {{harvtxt |Ray |1994 |p=113}} state he was equal to the Buddha.}} He is depicted as a monk with great capacity to tolerate discomfort<!--59--> and contentment with the bare necessities of life.<!--60-->{{sfn |Wilson |2003 |pp=59\u201360}} In one discourse found in the P\u0101li and Chinese collections, the Buddha advised Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa that having grown old, he should give up ascetic practices and live close to the Buddha. Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa declined, however. When the Buddha asked him to explain, Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa said he found the practices of benefit to himself. He also argued he could be an example for next generations of practitioners. The Buddha agreed with him, and affirmed the benefits of ascetic practices,{{sfn |Mun-keat |2017 |p=300}}{{sfn |Analayo |2015 |p=14}} which he had himself praised for a long time.{{sfn |Mun-keat |2017 |p=301}} A second discourse found in the P\u0101li and two Chinese collections has Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa meet the Buddha as he was wearing simple rag-robes and, according to the Chinese versions, his hair and beard long. Other monks criticized Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa for not looking appropriate when meeting his master. The Buddha responded by praising Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa, however.<!--302--> In the Chinese versions, the Buddha even went so far as to allow Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa to share his seat, but Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa preferred to sit in a respectful manner instead.<!--303-->{{sfn |Mun-keat |2017 |pp=302\u2013303}} When Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa fell ill once, the Buddha went to visit him and reminded him of his efforts in practicing the Buddhist teaching. This helped him to recover.{{sfn |Karaluvinna |2002 |p=440}}\n\n=== Relation with \u0100nanda ===\n{{Multiple image\n| align = right\n| direction = \n| width = 160\n| header = Two [[Companion statues: Kashyapa and Ananda|companion statues]], eighth century, China\n| image1 = Kashyapa and Ananda, Southeast Asia Gallery, Royal Ontario Museum, Ananda front.JPG\n| caption1 = [[Mahakassapa|Mah\u0101kassapa]]\n| image2 = Kashyapa and Ananda, Southeast Asia Gallery, Royal Ontario Museum, Kashyapa front.JPG\n| caption2 = \u0100nanda\n}}\nIn another discourse, the Buddha advised Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa to teach some monks. Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa refused, however, saying that the monks were hard to instruct. He gave the example of two of them, who were in the habit of using Buddhist teachings to determine who knew the best, and quarrel as a result. The Buddha then had those two monks called to him and he taught them about the real purpose of learning Buddhism. The two monks confessed their mistakes to the Buddha. In the two Chinese versions of the story, [[\u0100nanda]], the Buddha's attendant, objected to Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa's criticism of the monks, but Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa dismissed \u0100nanda's objections critically.{{sfn |Mun-keat |2017 |p=298}}\n\nThat would not be the first time Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa criticized \u0100nanda. For example, one time Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa chastised \u0100nanda in strong words, criticizing the fact that \u0100nanda was travelling with a large following of young monks who appeared untrained and who had built up a bad reputation.{{sfn |Malalasekera |1937 |loc=vol. 1, [http://www.palikanon.com/english/pali_names/aa/aananda.htm \u0100nanda]}} According to the early texts, \u0100nanda's role in founding the ''[[bhikkhuni|bhik\u1e63un\u012b]]'' (nun) order made him popular with the ''bhik\u1e63un\u012bs''. \u0100nanda often taught them,{{sfn |Buswell |Lopez |2013 |loc=\u0100nanda}}{{sfn |Findly |2003 |p=384}} often encouraged women to ordain, and when he was criticized by Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa, several ''bhik\u1e63un\u012bs'' tried to defend him.{{sfn |Ambros |2016 |page=209}}{{sfn |Hin\u00fcber |2007 |pages=233{{en dash}}4}} Another time, shortly after the passing away of the Buddha, Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa gave a teaching to ''bhik\u1e63un\u012bs'' in the presence of \u0100nanda, to which one ''bhik\u1e63un\u012b'' called [[Sth\u016blanand\u0101]] ({{lang-pi|Thullanand\u0101}}){{refn |In the P\u0101li texts, this is another ''bhik\u1e63un\u012b'' called Thullatiss\u0101, not Thullanand\u0101.{{sfn |Mun-keat |2017 |p=303 note 41}}{{sfn |Karaluvinna |2002 |p=439}}}} responded by criticizing Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa. She felt it inappropriate that Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa should teach in \u0100nanda's presence, whom she thought of as the superior monk. Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa asked whether \u0100nanda agreed with her, but he dismissed her as a foolish woman.{{refn |See {{harvtxt |Mun-keat |2017 |pp=303\u2013304}} and {{harvtxt |Ohnuma |2013 |pp=48\u201349}}. For the time period, see {{harvtxt |Karaluvinna |2002 |p=438}}.}} Then Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa proceeded to have \u0100nanda admit that the Buddha publicly had acknowledged Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa for numerous attainments.{{sfn |Analayo |2010 |p=15}} Karaluvinna hypothesizes that Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa did this to dispel doubts about his role as leader of the ''sa\u1e43gha'' ({{lang-pi|sa\u1e45gha|italic=yes}}; monastic community).{{sfn |Karaluvinna |2002 |p=438}} In a similar event, Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa reprimanded \u0100nanda for not taking responsibility for his pupils. In this case, Sth\u016blanand\u0101 heavily criticized Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa for doing so, and accused him in a hateful rush for having been an adherent of a non-Buddhist religious sect.{{sfn |Ohnuma |2013 |p=47}} In some accounts, she even undressed herself in front of him to insult him.{{sfn |Ray |1994 |p=107}} He tried to convince her that he was a legitimate disciple of the Buddha, but to no avail. Shortly after, she left the nun's life,{{sfn |Ohnuma |2013 |p=48}} and in some accounts, died and was reborn in [[hell in Buddhism|hell]].{{sfn |Ray |1994 |p=107}}\n\nAccording to Indologist [[Oskar von Hin\u00fcber]], \u0100nanda's pro-''bhik\u1e63un\u012b'' attitude may well be the reason why there was frequent dispute between \u0100nanda and Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa, eventually leading Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa to charge \u0100nanda with several [[apatti (Buddhist monastic discipline)|offenses]] during the [[First Buddhist Council]], and possibly leading to two factions in the ''sa\u1e43gha''.{{sfn |Ohnuma |2013 |page=51}}{{sfn |Findly |1992 |pages=253{{en dash}}4}} Scholar of religion [[Reginald Ray]] raises the question whether more can be read in the disputes between \u0100nanda and his ''bhik\u1e63un\u012b'' followers on the one hand, and Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa on the other hand. He hypothesizes that \u0100nanda and the ''bhik\u1e63un\u012bs'' may represent established monasticism, and Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa represents forest renunciant movements.<!--note 18-->{{sfn |Ray |1994 |p=142 note 18}}\n\nIn general, Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa was known for his aloofness and love of solitude. But as a teacher, he was a stern mentor who held himself and his fellow renunciates against high standards. He was considered worthy of reverence, but also a sharp critic who impressed upon others that respect to him was due. Compared to \u0100nanda, he was much colder and stricter,<!--57--> but also more impartial and detached, and religion scholar Reiko Ohnuma argues that these broad differences in character explain the events between Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa and \u0100nanda better than the more specific idea of pro- and anti-''bhik\u1e63un\u012b'' stances.<!--59-->{{sfn |Ohnuma |2013 |pp=57, 59}}{{refn |group=note |Silk follows Buddhist studies scholar [[Gregory Schopen]] in noting an important difference between the two disciples with regard to the Buddha's robes. Whereas Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa exchanged his robes with that of the Buddha, \u0100nanda requested when he became the Buddha's attendant that the Buddha should never give him a robe, lest he should be accused of attending to him for personal gain.{{sfn |Silk |2003 |p=195 note 70}} Moreover, during the First Council, \u0100nanda was accused of an offense for having stepped on the Buddha's robe.{{sfn |Deeg |1999 |p=164 note 63}}}} P\u0101li scholar Rune Johansson (1918\u20131981) argued that the events surrounding Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa, \u0100nanda and the ''bhik\u1e63un\u012bs'' prove that in Buddhism, enlightened disciples can still be seen to make mistakes. Going against this, however, [[Buddhist studies]] scholar [[Bhikkhu Analayo]] hypothesizes that Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa chose to teach \u0100nanda to abandon favoritism, and left the ''bhik\u1e63un\u012bs'' for \u0100nanda himself to deal with.{{sfn |Analayo |2010 |p=16}}\n\n=== Teacher and mentor ===\n[[File:Dinastia tang, testa del grande discepolo mahakasyapa, grotte di mogao, VII-VIII sec.JPG|thumb |Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa. Seventh-eighth century, [[Mogao Caves]], China |alt=Elderly man smiling, with shaved hair, a slight protrusion in the skull and long earlobes |left]]\nP\u0101li texts state that the Buddha regarded Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa as his equal in exhorting monks to lead active and zealous lives, and the Buddha praised him for his capacity to instill faith to lay people by teaching. Karaluvinna believes that the Buddha may have been grooming Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa for his later role as leader of the ''sa\u1e43gha''.{{sfn |Karaluvinna |2002 |p=438}} In the Sa\u1e43yutta discourses featuring Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa in the P\u0101li and its Chinese parallels, Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa is raised as an example of teaching doctrine from a pure and compassionate intention.{{sfn |Analayo |2010 |pp=14\u201315}}{{sfn |Aronson |1996 |p=11}} Religion scholar Shayne argues that the aloof and austere ascetic as he is presented in most texts does not provide a complete picture.{{sfn |Clarke |2014 |pp=107, 109}} An\u0101layo notes that he did take an active concern in community matters, spent time teaching doctrine<!--17, 19--> and persuaded fellow monastics to practice [[asceticism]].<!--18--> This is also shown in his role as leader of the First Council.<!--16-->{{sfn |Analayo |2010 |pp=16\u201319}} In one early discourse, he was asked by [[Payasi|P\u0101y\u0101si]], a philosopher with [[Materialism#Axial Age|materialist]] teachings, why virtuous Buddhist monks do not commit suicide. Since they have done much good [[karma (Buddhism)|karma]], and since Buddhists believe in an afterlife in which this karma gives fruit, he argued, why not go there straight away? Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa responded that virtuous monks would not do that, because they live with compassion for other people, and do much good by teaching them: their purpose \"is gained by life\".{{refn |See {{harvtxt |Harvey |1998 |pp=408\u2013409}} and {{harvtxt |Wiltshire |1983 |pp=130\u2013131}}. Citation is from the primary source (''P\u0101y\u0101si Sutta''), cited by Harvey.}} The Sanskrit ''Mah\u0101karmavibha\u1e45ga'' states that Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa carried out important teaching work, and was able to bring Buddhism to the people in the northwest, starting with [[Avanti (Ancient India)|Avanti]].{{sfn |Ray |1994 |pp=109, 116}}\n\nHowever, because of his stern tone of teaching and his being selective in people to teach, his teaching style came under criticism by other monks and ''bhik\u1e63un\u012bs'':<!--16-->{{sfn |Analayo |2010 |p=16}} he was not popular, especially not among ''bhik\u1e63un\u012bs''.{{sfn |Karaluvinna |2002 |p=439}} This caused him to gradually withdraw from teaching, An\u0101layo argues. A similar monk called Bakkula completely withdrew from teaching for similar reasons, which led him to emphasize ascetic values even more than Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa, to compensate and still be worthy of support from lay people. Such an ideal of an enlightened disciple with ascetic values, as depicted in Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa and in a more extreme form in Bakkula, could reflect sentiments and inclinations among some groups of early Buddhists,<!--19--> and may have contributed to how [[Mahayana|Mah\u0101y\u0101na]] authors later polemicized against what they perceived as \"selfish arahants\".<!--20 note 58-->{{sfn |Analayo |2010 |pp=19\u201320, note 58}}\n\nClarke argues that the image of Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa as a detached ascetic was the way he was \"branded\" by the early Buddhists to the public in general. Studying M\u016blasarv\u0101stiv\u0101da texts of [[Vinaya|monastic discipline]], Clarke points out that there is also an \"in-house\" perspective on Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa, which shows that he interacted with his former wife turned ''bhik\u1e63un\u012b'' frequently<!--107, 109--> to mentor her.<!--113--> Shortly after Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa became ordained under the Buddha, he met his former wife Bhadra, who had joined an order of [[History of nudity#India|naked ascetics]] led by [[Purana Kassapa|Nirgrantha P\u016bra\u1e47a]] ({{lang-pi |P\u016bra\u1e47a Kassapa}}). She was regularly targeted for rape her fellow ascetics, however. Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa pitied her and persuaded her to become ordained as a Buddhist ''bhik\u1e63un\u012b'' instead.<!--112-->{{refn |group=note |However, in some accounts she is only ordained five years after having met the Buddha, after the ''bhik\u1e63un\u012b'' order was founded.{{sfn |Bodhi |2000 |p=388}}}} Nevertheless, she was still harassed often, but now only when going outside. Since this happened when Bhadra went out in villages to obtain alms, Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa requested the Buddha's permission to daily give half of the alms food he had gained to her, so she did not need to go out anymore. His actions came under criticism, however, coming from monks (the [[\u1e62a\u1e0dv\u0101rgika|Group of Six]]) and the ''bhik\u1e63un\u012b'' Sth\u016blanand\u0101. Although these monastics were known for their misbehavior, Clarke thinks their criticism was probably indicative of \"the general monastic ambivalence toward those of an ascetic bent\".<!--113-->{{refn|{{harvtxt |Clarke |2014 |pp=107, 112\u2013113}}. Quote is on page 113.}} Writing about Sth\u016blanand\u0101, Ohnuma says that Sth\u016blanand\u0101 went against the idea of detachment and renunciation as generally advocated in early Buddhist monasticism, which is why she hated Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa and Bhadra. She expressed criticism of Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa often, even when he did not act with typical ascetic detachment.{{sfn |Ohnuma |2013 |p=32}} Regardless, Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa continued to guide his former wife and she attained ''[[arhat]]'' ({{lang-pi|arahant|italic=yes}}) afterwards.<!--113-->{{sfn |Clarke |2014 |p=113}} In a poem attributed to her, she praises her ex-husband's gifts, shared vision of the truth and [[kalyanamitta|spiritual friendship]]. Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa did not mention her in his poems though.{{sfn |Rhys Davids |1914 |p=160}}\n[[File:Head of Kashyapa, wood, Tang Dynasty.JPG|Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa, wood sculpture, seventh\u2013tenth century, China|thumb |alt=Elderly man smiling, with shaved hair and long earlobes]]\nMah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa was sometimes consulted by other leading monks on points of doctrine. After some [[Tirthika|teachers from non-Buddhist sects]] asked the elder [[Sariputta|\u015a\u0101riputra]] about [[the unanswered questions]], he consulted with Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa as to why the Buddha had never given an answer to these questions.{{sfn |Mun-keat |2017 |pp=305\u2013306}} At another occasion, \u015a\u0101riputra consulted him about developing effort in the practice of Buddhist teachings.{{sfn |Karaluvinna |2002 |p=439}} Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa was also \u015aro\u1e47a-Ko\u1e6dikar\u1e47a's ({{lang-pi|So\u1e47a-Ko\u1e6dika\u1e47\u1e47a}}) teacher and friend of the family, and later his ''[[Upadhyay#In Buddhism|up\u0101dhy\u0101ya]]'' ({{lang-pi|upajjh\u0101ya|italic=yes}}).{{refn |group=note |An ''up\u0101dhy\u0101ya'' is a preceptor in Buddhist ordinations.}} He taught the ''[[Atthakavagga|A\u1e6d\u1e6dhakavagga]]'' to him, and later \u015aro\u1e47a became well known for the recitation of it.{{sfn |Buswell |Lopez |2013 |loc=So\u1e47a-Ko\u1e6dika\u1e47\u1e47a}}\n\nAnother aspect of Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa's role as teacher was his compassion for the poor.{{sfn |Wilson |2003 |p=57}}{{sfn |Karaluvinna |2002 |p=440}} Numerous accounts describe how he went out of his way to give impoverished donors the chance to give to him and support him in his livelihood. Such donors would typically provide him with secondhand food, which in the culture of [[Brahminism]] at the time was considered impure. By receiving food from these donors, Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa was considered a [[field of merit]] for them, or, in other words, an opportunity for them to make merit and \"vanquish their bad karma\".<!--57--> In one case, he sought out a very poor woman who was at the end of her life, just to give her an opportunity to give a little. At first she did not dare to because she felt the food's quality was too low, but when Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa kept waiting, she eventually realized he had just come for her, and gave.<!--62--> Religion scholar Liz Wilson argues that these accounts of generosity have been influenced by pre-Buddhist beliefs of [[Vedic sacrifice]], in which the sacrificer and the sacrificed are connected, and the offering contains something of the person offering.<!--58--> By giving something of themselves, the donors acquire a new self,<!--66--> and purify themselves by means of the monastic recipient.<!--68--> In one account, a leprose person accidentally lets her finger fall off in a bowl of food she is offering. Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa accepts and consumes the offering anyway.<!--58--> Further, Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa's choice for poor people to make merit is further amplified by having supernatural or extraordinary donors like [[deva (Buddhism)|deities]]<!--57, 60--> or a wealthy merchant<!--65--> compete with the poor, and Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa accepting only the poor as donor.<!--57, 60-->{{sfn |Wilson |2003 |pp=57\u201358, 60, 62, 65\u201366, 68}} In one discourse, he even advises other monastics against visiting \"high-born families\".{{sfn |Ray |1994 |p=93}} The poor donors making an offering to Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa thus become empowered with a high status and power through their [[merit-making]].<!--58, 68--> Wilson surmises, \"[t]he perfect donor, in Mahakassapa's eyes, is the donor who has the least to give...\".<!--63-->{{refn |{{harvtxt |Wilson |2003 |pp=58, 63, 68}}. Quote is on page 63.}}\n\nMah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa's insistence on accepting offerings from the poor and refusing those from high-standing or supernatural donors was part of the anti-establishment character with which Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa is depicted. This also includes his long hair and beard. In one text, Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa's refusal of high-profile donors led to the Buddha issuing a rule that donations must not be refused.{{sfn |Ray |1994 |p=110}}\n\n=== Final respects to the Buddha ===\n[[File:Burma, mid 19th century, Mah\u0101kassapa paying homage to the Buddha's feet.jpg|thumb|Burma, mid 19th century. Mah\u0101kassapa meeting the ''\u0101j\u012bvika'' ascetic (above) and paying homage to the Buddha's feet before the funeral pyre is lit (below) |alt=Monk holding hands in the air, standing next to nearly naked man holding flower (above). Funeral pyre with feet sticking out, two monks holding hands clasped facing the feet (below)]]\nAccording to [[Mahaparinibbana Sutta|the early P\u0101li discourse about the Buddha's last days and passing into Nirv\u0101\u1e47a]] ({{lang-pi|Mah\u0101parinibb\u0101na Sutta|italic=yes}}), Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa learnt about the Buddha's ''parinirv\u0101\u1e47a'' ({{lang-pi|parnibb\u0101na|italic=yes}}) after seven days.{{sfn |Lee |2010 |p=57}} He was resting from a journey with a following of monks when he met an ''[[\u0101j\u012bvika]]'' ascetic who was carrying a flower from a [[coral tree]] which originated from [[heaven (Buddhism)|heaven]]. He asked him about the flower, and it turned out it the entire area of [[Kushinagara|Ku\u015binagara]] ({{lang-pi|Kusinara}}), where the Buddha had passed away, was covered in it.{{refn |See {{harvtxt|Gethin |2008 |p=135}}; {{harvtxt|Harvey |2013 |p=222}} and {{harvtxt |Karaluvinna |2002 |p=437}}. Karaluvinna mentions the name of the flower and its origin. {{harvtxt |Frank |1908 |p=10 footnote}} mentions that it covered Ku\u015binagara.}} According to some Tibetan sources, however, Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa knew of the Buddha's passing because of an earthquake.{{sfn |Karaluvinna |2002 |p=437}}{{sfn |Oldenberg |1899 |p=658 note 1}} In the P\u0101li texts, Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa then rushed back from the [[Pava|P\u0101va Mountain]] to arrive in Ku\u015binagara seven days later. But in the Tibetan texts, Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa was concerned that King Aj\u0101ta\u015batru might die of shock when he heard of the Buddha's passing. He therefore warned a ''brahmin'' who worked at the court, who was able to prevent the king from dying. Only then did he proceed to Ku\u015binagara.{{sfn |Karaluvinna |2002 |p=437}}\n\nIt turned out the [[Malla (India)|Malla]] people from Ku\u015binagara had attempted to light the funeral pyre, but were unable to.{{sfn |Gethin |2008 |p=135}} P\u0101li accounts state that the monk [[Anuruddha]] explained to them that deities prevented the funeral pyre from being lit until the arrival of Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa,{{sfn |Kim |2011 |p=131}}{{sfn |Gethin |2008 |p=135}} although sixth-century Chinese Buddhist texts say it was the spiritual power of the Buddha instead which caused the delay.{{sfn |Lee |2010 |p=94}} The accounts continue that Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa paid \"deep and tender homage\" to the Buddha's feet.<!--57-58--> The Buddha's feet miraculously emerged from the coffin, in which the Buddha's body was enshrouded with many layers of cloth.<!--Strong, Bareau--> As soon as he had finished, the pyre lit spontaneously,<!--91--> although in some versions, Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa lit the pyre himself in the traditional Indian role of the eldest son.{{refn |For the Chinese accounts, see {{harvtxt |Lee |2010 |pp=57\u201358, 91}}. For the P\u0101li accounts, see {{harvtxt |Karaluvinna |2002 |p=437}}. For the eldest son, see {{harvtxt |Strong |2007 |p=115}}. For the quote, see {{harvtxt |Ray |1994 |p=107}}. Also see {{harvtxt |Strong |2001 |p=138}}.}}\n\nBuddhologist [[Andr\u00e9 Bareau]] (1921\u20131993) regarded the episode of Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa learning of the Buddha's ''parinirv\u0101\u1e47a'' and his lighting of the pyre as an embellishment that was inserted by authors of monastic discipline in three layers (in the fifth,<!--74--> fourth and third centuries BCE) to emphasize the person of Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa. In the original version of the account, Bareau reasoned, Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa did not attend the Buddha's cremation. Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa did not need to travel for seven days. He could have travelled from P\u0101va to Ku\u015binagara in a few hours, and the delay in lighting the pyre was unnecessary.<!--75-->{{sfn |Bareau |1979 |pp=74\u201375}} Regardless, the story of the delay and Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa eventually lighting the funeral pyre indicates how much Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa was respected,{{sfn |Buswell |Lopez |2013 |loc=Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa}}{{sfn |Ray |1994 |p=115}} as he was regarded as the most important heir to the Buddha's dispensation.{{sfn |Deeg |1999 |p=160 note 46}}\n\n=== First Buddhist Council and death ===\n==== Narratives ====\n\n[[File:Wat Tham Khao Rup Chang - 100 75 sa po he (14665768295).jpg|thumb |Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa, [[d:Q40188656|Tham Khao Rup Chang Temple]], [[Songkhla Province]], Thailand |alt=Monk in robes, stern face, bushy eyebrows, holding staff and prayer beads |left]]\n\nWhen the Buddha had attained ''[[parinirvana|parinirv\u0101\u1e47a]]'' (death), and when Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa was reportedly hundred twenty years old, the number of disciples that had once witnessed the Buddha teaching or that had attained enlightenment were becoming less.{{refn |For the witnesses decreasing, see {{harvtxt |Powers |2016 |p=19}}. For the enlightened decreasing, and the age of Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa, see {{harvtxt |Karaluvinna |2002 |p=440}}.}} Some monks, among which a monk called Subhadra ({{lang-pi|Subhadda}}), expressed satisfaction that they could now do as they pleased, because their teacher the Buddha was no longer there to prohibit them from anything.{{sfn |Mun-keat |2017 |p=295}}{{sfn |Analayo |2016 |pp=170\u2013171}} Some Chinese and Tibetan texts state that there was \"doubt and consternation\" among many disciples.{{sfn |Bapat |1956 |pp=35\u201336}} The Sanskrit ''[[Asokavadana|A\u015bokavad\u0101na]]'' and the Chinese ''[[Mah\u0101praj\u00f1\u0101p\u0101ramit\u0101\u015b\u0101stra]]'' say that many enlightened disciples wished to stop teaching, leave the world behind and attain ''paranirv\u0101\u1e47a''. This alarmed Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa, and he attempted successfully to stop his fellow disciples from leaving the world.{{sfn |Strong |1994 |p=62}} He then set up the First Buddhist Council,{{sfn |Mun-keat |2017 |p=295}}{{sfn |Analayo |2016 |pp=170\u2013171}} to record the Buddhist discourses and details of the monastic discipline and thereby prevent them from becoming corrupted.{{sfn |Powers |2016 |p=19}}{{sfn |Buswell |Lopez |2013 |loc=Council, 1st}} According to the texts, the First Buddhist Council was held in a cave called Saptapar\u1e47aguh\u0101 in R\u0101jag\u1e5bha ({{lang-pi|Sattapa\u1e47\u1e47aguh\u0101; R\u0101jagaha}}, present-day [[Rajgir]]), which was the site of many Buddhist discourses.{{refn |For the city, see {{harvtxt |Powers |2016 |p=19}}. For the cave, see {{harvtxt |Deeg |1999 |pp=160\u2013161}}.}} In the first [[vassa|rains retreat]] ({{lang-sa|var\u1e63a|italic=yes}}, {{lang-pi|vassa|italic=yes}}) after the Buddha had died, Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa called upon \u0100nanda to recite the discourses he had heard, as a representative on this council.{{sfn |Keown |2004 |page=12}}<ref>{{cite web |last1=Thorp |first1=Charley Linden |title=The Evolution of Buddhist Schools |url=https://www.ancient.eu/article/1043/the-evolution-of-buddhist-schools/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180829212020/https://www.ancient.eu/article/1043/the-evolution-of-buddhist-schools/ |archive-date=29 August 2018 |url-status=live |website=Ancient History Encyclopedia |date=3 April 2017}}</ref> There was a rule issued, however, that only ''arhats'' were allowed to attend the council, to prevent bias like favoritism or sectarianism from clouding the disciples' memories. \u0100nanda had not attained enlightenment yet, in contrast with the rest of the council, consisting of 499 ''arhats''.{{sfn |Powers |2007 |p=56}}{{sfn |Prebish |2005 |pages=225{{en dash}}6}} Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa therefore did not yet allow \u0100nanda to attend. Although he knew that \u0100nanda's presence in the council was required, he did not want to be biased by allowing an exception to the rule.{{sfn |Witanachchi |1965 |p=532}}{{sfn |Buswell |Lopez |2013 |loc=Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa}} The M\u016blasarv\u0101stiv\u0101da tradition adds that Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa initially allowed \u0100nanda to join as a sort of servant assisting during the council, but then was forced to remove him when the disciple Anuruddha saw that \u0100nanda was not yet enlightened.{{sfn |Witanachchi |1965 |p=532}}{{sfn |Ohnuma |2013 |pp=49\u201350}}\n\nNevertheless, that night, \u0100nanda was able to attain enlightenment.{{sfn |Prebish |2005 |p=231}} When the Council began the next morning, Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa questioned [[Upali|Up\u0101li]], to establish the texts on monastic discipline for monks and ''bhik\u1e63u\u1e47is''.{{sfn |Buswell |Lopez |2013 |loc=Council, 1st}} \u0100nanda was consulted to recite the discourses and to determine which were authentic and which were not.{{sfn |Keown |2004 |page=164}}{{sfn |MacQueen |2005 |page=314}} Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa asked of each discourse that \u0100nanda listed where, when, and to whom it was given,{{sfn |Buswell |Lopez |2013 |loc=\u0100nanda}}{{sfn |Zurcher |2005 |page=378}} and at the end of this, the assembly agreed that \u0100nanda's memories and recitations were correct,{{sfn |Powers |2007 |pp=57{{en dash}}8}} after which the [[Sutta Pitaka|discourse collection]] ({{lang-sa|S\u016btra Pi\u1e6daka|italic=yes |link=no}}, {{lang-pi|Sutta Pi\u1e6daka|italic=yes |link=no}}) was considered finalized and closed.{{sfn |MacQueen |2005 |page=314}} In some versions of the account, the [[Abhidharma]] ({{lang-pi|Abhidhamma}}) was also standardized during this council, or rather its precursor the ''[[matika|M\u0101t\u1e5bka]]''. Some texts say it was Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa who reviewed it, and other texts say it was \u0100nanda or \u015a\u0101riputra.{{refn |For \u0100nanda, see {{harvtxt |Buswell |Lopez |2013 |loc=Council, 1st}}. For \u015a\u0101riputra, see {{harvtxt |Migot |1954 |p=525}}. For the ''M\u0101t\u1e5bka'', see Migot and {{harvtxt |Morrison |2010 |p=21}}.}} During the recitations, one problem was raised. Before the Buddha's ''parinirv\u0101\u1e47a'', he had mentioned to \u0100nanda that, if required, minor rules could be abolished after his passing. Now the question remained what the Buddha had meant when he said ''minor rules''.{{sfn |Prebish |2005 |p=226}} The monks present at the council discussed several possibilities, but it was not resolved.{{sfn |Tsukamoto |1963 |p=57}} To prevent disrepute of the ''sa\u1e43gha'' and criticism from non-Buddhists, Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa opposed to abolish any rules of discipline.{{refn |{{harvtxt |Prebish |2005 |p=226}}. For the non-Buddhists, see {{harvtxt |Tsukamoto |1963 |p=57}}.}} After the council, Mah\u00e1k\u00e1yapa attempted to have the monks [[Gavampati (Buddha's disciple)|Gav\u0101mpati]] and Pur\u0101\u1e47a approve the results of the council, but both preferred not to give their opinion about the matter.{{sfn |Dutt |1941 |p=331}}\n\nDuring the same council, \u0100nanda was charged for an offense by Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa and other members of the ''sa\u1e45gha'' for having enabled women to join the monastic order.{{sfn |Keown |2004 |page=164}} Besides this, he was charged for having forgotten to request the Buddha to specify which offenses of monastic discipline could be disregarded;{{refn |group=note |The Buddha mentioned to \u0100nanda that \"minor rules\" could be abolished.{{sfn |Powers |2007 |p=55}}}} for having stepped on the Buddha's robe; for having allowed women to honor the Buddha's body after his death, which was not properly covered, and during which his body was sullied by their tears;<!--Ananda, Council, 1st--> and for having failed to ask the Buddha to continue to live on.<!--all three entries--> \u0100nanda did not acknowledge these as offenses, but he conceded to do a formal confession anyway,<!--Ananda--> \"... in faith of the opinion of the venerable elder monks\".{{sfn |Buswell |Lopez |2013 |loc=\u0100nanda; C\u0101p\u0101lacaitya; Council, 1st}}{{sfn |Hin\u00fcber |2007 |pp=235{{en dash}}6}}\n\n==== Historicity ====\n[[File:Luohan Kashyapa, China, Liao dynasty, 1000 AD, wood, Prague NG Vp 2886, 151195.jpg|thumb|Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa sitting, holding a staff (missing). Wood, China, {{circa}} 1000 |alt=Monk with stern face and slight protrusion in skull, sitting and holding his hand as though he is holding a staff]]\n\nThe most well-known version of the First Council is that of Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa being the head. However, texts of the Sarv\u0101stiv\u0101da, M\u016blasarv\u0101stiv\u0101da, and Mah\u012b\u015b\u0101saka traditions relate that this was [[Kaundinya|\u0100j\u00f1\u0101ta Kau\u1e47\u1e0dinya]] ({{lang-pi |A\u00f1\u00f1a-Ko\u1e47\u1e0da\u00f1\u00f1a}}) instead, as Kau\u1e47\u1e0dinya was the most senior disciple.{{sfn |Prebish |2005 |p=230}} Buddhologist [[Jean Przyluski]] (1885\u20131944) argued that the earliest accounts placed Kau\u1e47\u1e0dinya at the head of the ''sa\u1e43gha'', and that originally, Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa was a conventional figure, with no administrative or leading role. However, because of his unquestioned ascetic saint-like reputation, Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa came to replace Kau\u1e47\u1e0dinya's role as leader during the cremation and the First Council.{{sfn |Ray |1994 |p=118}} Przyluski's theory has been criticized, however, on the grounds that it is difficult to maintain that the three textual traditions he mentioned are the oldest.{{sfn |Prebish |2005 |p=230}} Still, Bareau argued that the incident with Subhadra leading to Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa summoning the council is a later insertion, though early enough to be found in all traditions of early Buddhist texts.<!--74--> He believed it was the authors of texts of monastic discipline that inserted it shortly after the Buddha's passing away, at the end of the fifth century BCE, to glorify Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa.<!--71-->{{sfn |Bareau |1979 |pp=71, 74}}\n\nTradition states that the First Council lasted for seven months.{{sfn |Buswell |Lopez |2013 |loc=Council, 1st}} However, many scholars, from the late 19th century onward, have considered the historicity of the First Council improbable. Some scholars, such as Orientalist [[Ivan Minayev]] (1840\u20131890), thought there must have been assemblies after the Buddha's death, but considered only the main characters and some events before or after the First Council historical, and not the council itself.{{sfn |Prebish |2005 |page=226}}{{sfn |Mukherjee |1994 |pp=453}} Other scholars, such as Bareau and Indologist [[Hermann Oldenberg]] (1854\u20131920), considered it likely that the account of the First Council was written after the [[Second Buddhist Council|Second Council]], and based on that of the Second, since there were not any major problems to solve after the Buddha's death, or any other need to organize the First Council.{{sfn |Prebish |2005 |page=231}}{{sfn |Mukherjee |1994 |pp=454{{en dash}}6}} On the other hand, archaeologist [[Louis Finot (archaeologist)|Louis Finot]] (1864\u20131935) and Indologist {{ill|E. E. Obermiller|ru|\u041e\u0431\u0435\u0440\u043c\u0438\u043b\u043b\u0435\u0440,_\u0415\u0432\u0433\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0439_\u0415\u0432\u0433\u0435\u043d\u044c\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447}} (1901\u20131935) thought the account of the First Council was authentic, because of the correspondences between the P\u0101li texts and the [[Agama (Buddhism)|Sanskrit traditions]].{{sfn |Mukherjee |1994 |p=457}} Orientalist [[Louis de La Vall\u00e9e-Poussin]] (1869\u20131938) and Indologist Nalinaksha Dutt (1893\u20131973) thought it was historical, but in the form of a simple [[patimokkha|recitation of discipline]] ({{lang-sa|pr\u0101timok\u1e63a|italic=yes}}, {{lang-pi|p\u0101timokkha|italic=yes}}; according to Dutt, in order settle the \"minor rules\") not a complete council with a full review of the discourses.{{sfn |Dutt |1941 |pp=339\u2013340}} Indologist [[Richard Gombrich]], following Bhikkhus [[Bhikkhu Sujato|Sujato]] and Brahmali's arguments, considers that the Council \"makes good sense\". They argue that the Council was historical, because all the known versions of monastic discipline relate it.<!--126--> Some of those, such as the Therav\u0101da discipline, do not include the recitation of the Abhidharma in their account, even though it was an important part of their identity{{em dash}}this shows the historical nature of the accounts.<!--127-->{{sfn |Sujato |Brahmali |pp=126\u2013127}}{{sfn |Gombrich |2018 |p=73}}\n\nIndologist [[Erich Frauwallner]] (1898\u20131974) noted that in the earliest Buddhist discourses little mention is made of Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa, especially when compared to \u0100nanda. However, in the accounts about the First Council, Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa appears very prominent, whereas \u0100nanda is humbled and given far less credit. Frauwallner argued this points at \"a deep reaching modification and revaluation of the tradition\" concerning the position of these two figures.{{sfn |Frauwallner |1956 |pp=161\u2013162}}{{sfn |Analayo |2010 |p=17 note 52}} On a similar note, Buddhist studies scholar {{ill |Jonathan Silk|nl}} remarks that the earliest Chinese translations hardly mention Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa.{{sfn |Silk |2003 |pp=176\u2013177 note 7}} Ray argues there is a difference in this between P\u0101li texts and texts from other early schools: the P\u0101li version of Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa is a much more ordinary person, depicted with far less supernatural powers and moral authority than in texts such as those from the M\u016blasarv\u0101stiv\u0101da discipline and in the ''Mah\u0101vastu''.<!--110-113--> Although there are some P\u0101li texts that do emphasize forest renunciation, these are fragmented elements<!--114--> that stand in stark contrast<!--137--> with Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa's general role in the P\u0101li history of the monastic establishment.<!--114-->{{sfn |Ray |1994 |pp=110\u2013114, 137}}\n[[File:2015-09-27-104022 - Kasyapa und Ananda (Song, 960-1279 n. Chr.).jpg|Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa (left) and \u0100nanda (right), China, [[Song Dynasty]] (960\u20131279) |thumb |alt=Two monks, one holding hands in front of chest, the other hands folded in front of belly]]\nVon Hin\u00fcber, Przyluski and Bareau have argued that the account of \u0100nanda being charged with offenses during the council indicate tensions between competing [[early Buddhism|early Buddhist]] schools, i.e. schools that emphasized the discourses and schools that emphasized monastic discipline. These differences have affected the scriptures of each tradition:{{refn |See {{harvtxt |Findly |1992 |pages=253}}. For Bareau, see {{harvtxt |Analayo |2016 |p=172, note 75}}}} e.g. the P\u0101li and [[Mahisasaka|Mah\u012b\u015b\u0101saka]] textual traditions portray a Mah\u0101kassapa that is more critical of \u0100nanda than that the [[Sarvastivada|Sarv\u0101stiv\u0101da]] tradition depicts him,{{sfn |Findly |1992 |page=254}}{{sfn |Tsukamoto |1963 |p=821}} reflecting a preference for discipline on the part of the former traditions, and a preference for discourse for the latter.{{sfn |Findly |1992 |page=254}} Analyzing six [[recension]]s of different textual traditions of the ''[[Mah\u0101parinibb\u0101na Sutta]]'' extensively, Bareau distinguished two layers in the text, an older and a newer one, the former, fifth century BCE, belonging to the compilers that emphasized discourse, the latter, mostly fourth and third century BCE, to the ones that emphasized discipline; the former emphasizing the figure of \u0100nanda, the latter Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa.{{sfn |Bareau |1979 |page=70}} Buddhologist [[Andr\u00e9 Migot]] (1892\u20131967) argued, too, that the oldest texts (fifth century BCE) mostly glorify \u0100nanda as being the most [[bahu\u015bruta|well-learned]] ({{lang-sa|bahu\u015bruta|italic=yes}}, {{lang-pi|bahussutta|italic=yes}}); a second series of newer texts (fourth century-early third century BCE) glorify Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa as being eminent in [[\u015b\u012bla|discipline]] ({{lang-sa|\u015b\u012bla|italic=yes}}, {{lang-pi|s\u012bla|italic=yes}}); and the newest texts (mid third century BCE) glorify \u015a\u0101riputra as being the [[pa\u00f1\u00f1\u0101|wisest]] ({{lang-sa|praj\u00f1\u0101|italic=yes}}, {{lang-pi|pa\u00f1\u00f1\u0101|italic=yes}}). Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa was mostly associated with the texts of monastic discipline, during the fourth century until early third century BCE when Buddhism was prominent in [[Vaishali (ancient city)|Vai\u015b\u0101l\u012b]].{{sfn |Migot |1954 |pp=540\u2013541}} Bareau, Przyluski and Indologist [[I. B. Horner]] (1896\u20131981) therefore argued that the offenses \u0100nanda were charged with were a later interpolation. Scholar of religion Ellison Banks Findly disagrees, however, because the account in the texts of monastic discipline fits in with the ''Mah\u0101parinibb\u0101na Sutta'' and with \u0100nanda's character as generally depicted in the texts.{{sfn |Findly |1992 |p=268}} Minayev thought the charges were an ancient tradition, because they are not usually the material of legends, because the Chinese pilgrim [[Xuanzang]] (602\u2013664) reported about a ''[[stupa|st\u016bpa]]'' ({{lang-pi|th\u016bpa|italic=yes}}; a memorial mound or monument) that was erected in memory of the event,<!--31--> and because the ambiguity about what constitutes major and minor rules would have been typical for that period.<!--32-->{{sfn |Minayev |1894 |pp=31\u201332}}\n\nExpanding on the theory of the two factions, Przyluski noted that the figure of \u0100nanda represents Buddhism in an early form, whereas Mah\u0101ka\u015byapa represents a Buddhism that had undergone reform. \u0100nanda represents a \"religion of love\", whereas Mah\u0101ka\u015byapa represents \"a rough ascetic spirit\".{{sfn |Analayo |2016 |p=172, note 75}} Migot interpreted \u0100nanda's figure as a devotionalist form of Buddhism focused on the guru, replaced by Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa's established monasticism with less focus on devotion.{{sfn |Ray |1994 |p=147 note 57}}\n\nAlthough the Buddha did not appoint a formal successor, Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa's leading role and seniority effectively made him the head of the ''sa\u1e43gha'' during the first twenty years after the Buddha's ''parinirv\u0101\u1e47a''.{{sfn |Heim |2004 |p=468}} After the passing away of the Buddha and his close disciples \u015a\u0101riputra and Maudgaly\u0101yana, he had become the most influential figure in the Buddhist order.{{sfn |Hirakawa |1990 |pp=84\u201385}} In the Early Buddhist Texts, Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa's death is not discussed. This is discussed in post-canonical texts, however.{{sfn |Buswell |Lopez |2013 |loc=Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa}}\n\n=== Previous lives ===\nIn some early texts, accounts of Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa and Bhadra's previous lives are told, which illustrate how they vowed to lead celibate lives. In one life, they were making love in a forest and disturbed a ''[[pratyekabuddha]]'' ({{lang-pi|paccekabuddha|italic=yes}}) who was living and meditating there. When they discovered they had broken his [[samadhi|meditative concentration]], they felt so ashamed they took a vow together that from then onward, they would be reborn without sexual desire.{{sfn |Clarke |2014 |p=114}} In another life, in the time of the previous Buddha [[Padumuttara]], he was born in a wealthy family and was called Videha.<!--436--> He saw a disciple of Patumuttara Buddha who was declared to be eminent in ascetic practices, and wanted to be like him in a future life. In subsequent lives, he strove to achieve this aim by doing meritorious deeds, which involved offering robes and cloaks to [[List of the named Buddhas|Buddhas]] and ''pratyekabuddhas''.<!--437-->{{sfn |Karaluvinna |2002 |pp=436\u2013437}}\n\n== In post-canonical texts ==\n=== Patriarch ===\n[[File:\u0e27\u0e31\u0e14\u0e44\u0e15\u0e23\u0e21\u0e34\u0e15\u0e23\u0e27\u0e34\u0e17\u0e22\u0e32\u0e23\u0e32\u0e21\u0e27\u0e23\u0e27\u0e34\u0e2b\u0e32\u0e23 \u0e40\u0e02\u0e15\u0e2a\u0e31\u0e21\u0e1e\u0e31\u0e19\u0e18\u0e27\u0e07\u0e28\u0e4c \u0e01\u0e23\u0e38\u0e07\u0e40\u0e17\u0e1e\u0e21\u0e2b\u0e32\u0e19\u0e04\u0e23 %2841%29.jpg|thumb|Thai statue of Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa, {{ill|Wat Traimit|de}}]]\nIn many Indian Sanskrit and East Asian texts, from as early as the second century CE, Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa is considered the first patriarch of the [[Lineage (Buddhism)|lineage]] which transmitted the teaching of the Buddha, with \u0100nanda a being the second.{{refn |See {{harvtxt |Buswell |Lopez |2013 |loc=Damoduoluo chan jing; Madhy\u0101ntika}} and {{harvtxt |Welter |2004 |pages=462\u2013463}}. For the second century, see {{harvtxt |Morrison |2010 |p=20}}.}} One of the earliest texts that mention a tradition of patriarchs, is that of the [[Five Masters of the Dharma]] ({{lang-sa|dharm\u0101c\u0101rya|italic=yes}}), found in Sanskrit texts from the second century CE, including the ''A\u015bok\u0101vad\u0101na'' and the ''[[Mah\u0101y\u0101na Mah\u0101parinirv\u0101\u1e47a S\u016btra]]'',{{sfn |Morrison |2010 |p=20}} and many archaeological findings.{{sfn |Ray |1994 |p=148 note 70}} This tradition may in itself be based on early Buddhist accounts about the First Council, but further expanded on the idea of the preservation of the teachings.<!--21--> The accounts about the Five Masters seems to derive not so much from a concern about the transmission of the teaching though, but rather a concern regarding the absence of the Buddha himself.<!--22-->{{sfn |Morrison |2010 |pp=21\u201322}} The texts gave the Masters of the Dharma each a similar role and charisma as the Buddha, or, as Buddhist studies scholar [[John S. Strong]] puts it, \"all, in a sense, Buddhas in their own time\". This fit in with the concept of inheritance in ancient India, in which a son would not only inherit his father's possessions, but also his position and identity.<!--22-->{{refn |For Strong's quote, see {{harvtxt |Morrison |2010 |p=22}}. {{harvtxt |Silk |2003 |pp=180\u2013181}} discusses similar tendencies, but with regard to the patriarchs in general, not specifically the Five Masters.}} Several early Buddhist schools would expand on the idea of the Five Masters of the Dharma, including the Sarv\u0101stivadins, the M\u016blasarv\u0101stiv\u0101dins and the [[Sthavira|Sth\u0101viras]],{{refn |group=note |Nevertheless, the idea of transmission of the [[Dharma (Buddhism)|Dharma]] (Buddhist doctrine) through a list of patriarchs is not found in P\u0101li sources.{{sfn |Lamotte |1988 |p=210}}{{sfn |Ray |1994 |p=148 note 70}}}} each of which extended the list to include their own masters as patriarchs.<!--23-->{{sfn |Morrison |2010 |p=23}}\n\nThere is an account dating back from the Sarv\u0101stiv\u0101da and M\u016blasarv\u0101stiv\u0101da textual traditions which states that before Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa died, he bestowed the Buddha's teaching on \u0100nanda as a formal passing on of authority, telling \u0100nanda to pass the teaching on to his pupil [[Shanavasa|\u015a\u0101\u1e47akav\u0101s\u012b]] ({{lang-pi|Sa\u1e47av\u0101s\u012b}}; {{aka}} \u015a\u0101\u1e47akav\u0101sin or \u015a\u0101\u1e47\u0101vasika).{{refn |See {{harvtxt |Baruah |2000 |pp=9, 453}}. For the moment being just before Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa's death, see {{harvtxt |Strong |1994 |page=62}} and {{harvtxt |Karaluvinna |2002 |p=439}}. For the M\u016blasarv\u0101stiv\u0101da, see {{harvtxt |Hirakawa |1993 |page=85}}.}} Mah\u0101kassapa made a prediction that later would come true that a lay person called \u015a\u0101\u1e47akav\u0101s\u012b would make many gifts to the ''sa\u1e45gha'' during a feast. After this event, \u0100nanda would successfully persuade him to become ordained and be his pupil.{{sfn |Strong |1994 |p=65}}{{sfn |Baruah |2000 |pages=8, 453}} Later, just before \u0100nanda died, he passed the teaching on to his pupil as Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa had told him to.{{sfn |Witanachchi |1965 |p=532}} Ray notes that Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa is depicted here as choosing not only his successor, but also the successor of his successor, which emphasizes the preeminent position that Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa was seen to have.{{sfn |Ray |1994 |p=108}}\n\nBuddhist studies scholars [[Akira Hirakawa]] (1915\u20132002) and Bibhuti Baruah have expressed skepticism about the teacher{{en dash}}student relationship between Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa and \u0100nanda. They have argued that there was discord between the two, as indicated in the early texts.{{sfn |Baruah |2000 |p=10}}{{sfn |Hirakawa |1993 |page=85}} Hirakawa has further hypothesized that Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa and \u0100nanda were co-disciples, with the same teacher being Gautama Buddha, so there would be no need for a transmission between the two.{{sfn |Silk |2003 |p=204 note 81}} East Asian religion scholar Elizabeth Morrison cites a tract by the Zen scholar [[Qisong]] (1007\u20131072) about the tradition of patriarchs in Buddhism. He noted the problem of a transmission between co-disciples who are not master and student. He resolved the problem by comparing Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa and \u0100nanda to siblings who inherit according to birth order.{{sfn |Morrison |2010 |p=212 note 50}} Responding to Hirakawa's arguments, Silk further argues that the [[unilinear]] nature of the transmission made it impossible for both Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa and \u0100nanda to receive the transmission from the Buddha, so \u0100nanda had to receive the transmission from Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa instead.{{sfn |Silk |2003 |p=204 note 81}}\n\n=== Preserving the Buddha's relics ===\n[[File:China, Hebei province, Southern Xiangtangshan caves, Northern Qi dynasty - Standing Disciple Mahakasyapa Holding a Cylindrical Reliquary - 1972.166 - Cleveland Museum of Art.tif|Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa holding a reliquary, sixth century, [[Hebei province]], China |alt=Monk holding cylinder-shaped object. Monk is depicted with aura-like shape around the head |thumb]]\nThe [[atthakatha|commentary]] to the ''[[D\u012bgha Nik\u0101ya]]'' (fifth century) relates that after the Buddha's ''paranirv\u0101\u1e47a'', Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa was concerned that the [[Relics associated with Buddha|Buddha's remains or relics]] would become too dispersed, since they were now divide in eight portions.{{refn |For the exact motivation, see {{harvtxt |Strong |2001 |p=141}}. For the text, see {{harvtxt |Lagirarde |2006 |p=84}}.}} He gathered the portions of the Buddha's relics, by asking the families who had preserved them, though he left a token amount of relics with the families.{{refn |For the families, see {{harvtxt |Lagirarde |2006 |p=84}}. For the token amount, see {{harvtxt |Strong |2007 |p=121}}.}} With the help of King Aj\u0101ta\u015batru, he then preserved them in an underground chamber called the \"shrine for the [[\u015ar\u0101vaka#Foremost disciples|eighty disciples]]\" to the east of R\u0101jag\u1e5bha.{{refn |For the chamber, see {{harvtxt |Bautze-Picron |2010 |p=12}}. For R\u0101jag\u1e5bha, see {{harvtxt |Lagirarde |2006 |p=84}}.}} Because of the name, Southeast Asia scholar Fran\u00e7ois Lagirarde raises the question whether this chamber may also have been intended for the burial of relics of foremost disciples,{{sfn |Lagirarde |2006 |p=85}} but Strong interprets that it was a ruse: the whole operation was done in secrecy because Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa feared for the safety of the Buddha's relics.{{sfn |Strong |2007 |p=128}} Later, according to [[post-canonical Buddhist texts]] such as the Therav\u0101da ''[[Pa\u1e6dhamasambodhi]]'', the remains thus enshrined in one place were taken out and divided by emperor [[Ashoka|A\u015boka]] ({{circa}}268\u2013232 BCE) throughout India in 84,000 portions.{{refn |For the texts, see {{harvtxt |Swearer |2012 |pp=43, 47}}. For the number of portions, see {{harvtxt |Strong |2001 |p=141}}.}} Instead of the relics being hid away somewhere, they were now accessible to the population at large.{{sfn |Strong |2007 |p=236}}\n\nThe earliest accounts have Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa merely visit and pay his respects to each of the eight portions of the relics; later accounts have him gather the relics as well. There is a parallel here with the First Council, in which Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa gathered the [[Dharmak\u0101ya#Therav\u0101da|entire body of the Buddha's teachings]] ({{lang-sa|dharmak\u0101ya|italic=yes}}; {{lang-pi|dhammak\u0101ya|italic=yes}}) in one place, as he is depicted gathering the Buddha's remains ([[Sanskrit]] and {{lang-pi|r\u016bpak\u0101ya|italic=yes}}) in one place.<!--128--> Still, there may be a historical basis to the motif of the single place with the Buddha's relics. Przyluski and Bareau have argued on textual and other grounds that the Buddha's relics were originally kept in one single place, in a sepulcher (Przyluski) or a ''st\u016bpa'' (Bareau).<!--121-->{{sfn |Strong |2007 |pp=121, 128}}\n\n=== Awaiting Maitreya ===\n==== Accounts ====\nPost-canonical Sanskrit texts such as ''[[Avadana|Avad\u0101nas]]'', as well as the travelogues of medieval Chinese pilgrims, numerous Chinese translations in the Chinese Buddhist Canon, and Southeast Asian vernacular texts, relate Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa's death.{{refn |See {{harvtxt |Strong |2007 |page=45\u201346}}. For the Sanskrit texts, see {{harvtxt |Tournier |2014 |pp=11\u201312}}. For the travelogues and the translations, see {{harvtxt |Kim |2011 |pp=131, 135}}. For the Southeast Asian texts, see {{harvtxt |Lagirarde |2006 |loc=passim.}}}} Some of the earliest of these are a Chinese translation from the fourth century CE<!--89--> and the ''A\u015bokavad\u0101na'', which is dated to the second century CE.<!--90-->{{sfn |Lagirarde |2006 |pp=89\u201390}} They state that Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa's body was enshrined underneath the mountain [[Kukku\u1e6dap\u0101da]] ({{aka}} Gurup\u0101daka, in Magadha) where it remains until the arising of the next Buddha, [[Maitreya]] ({{lang-pi|Mettiya}}).{{sfn |Strong |2007 |page=45\u201346}}{{sfn |Tournier |2014 |pp=11\u201312}}\n[[File:Kasagi Mandala (Yamato Bunkakan).jpg|Painting of an image with Maitreya and Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa offering him Gautama Buddha's robe. [[Kasagidera]] Temple, Kasagi, [[Kyoto]]. The original eight-century colossal cliff-face image depicted here was destroyed by fire at an uncertain date.|thumb |alt=Painting with temple tower, a huge image on a cliff and two people looking at it.]]\nA Thai text relates that Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa knew through his meditation that he was about to die and attain ''paranirv\u0101\u1e47a'' on the next day.<!--86--> The day after, he informed his pupils of his death<!--88--> and taught them, then went for alms, wearing the robe he had received from the Buddha. In the texts on discipline from the M\u016blasarv\u0101stiv\u0101da tradition, it says he also went to pay his respects to the Buddha's relics.<!--89--> In several texts, he attempted to visit King Aj\u0101ta\u015batru, but the king was asleep.<!--86, 89--> Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa then cleaned the monastery, and proceeded to Kukku\u1e6dap\u0101da, the place of burial he had selected.<!--86--> He gave a final teaching to the lay people, and performed supernatural accomplishments.<!--86, 88-->{{sfn |Lagirarde |2006 |pp=86, 88\u201389}}\n\nHaving settled in a cave there in the middle of three peaks, he covered himself in the robe he had received from the Buddha.{{refn |See {{harvtxt |Tournier |2014 |p=12}}; {{harvtxt |Kim |2011 |p=131}} and {{harvtxt |Lagirarde |2006 |p=86}}. For the covering, see Tournier. For the cave, see Kim. For the three peaks, see Lagirarde.}} The texts then state he took a [[adhi\u1e6d\u1e6dh\u0101na|vow]] that his body would stay there until the arriving of Maitreya Buddha,<!--13--> which is an uncountable number of years. His body would not decay in that time, but become visible and disintegrate in the time of Maitreya Buddha.<!--16-->{{refn |{{harvtxt |Tournier |2014 |pp=13, 16}}. For the uncountable number, see {{harvtxt |Adamek |2011 |loc=Bodhidharma's Robe}}. For the visibility, see {{harvtxt |Lagirarde |2006 |p=88}}.}}{{refn |group=note |The Sanskrit ''S\u016btra on Maitreya's Birth'' has it that it was Gautama Buddha who told him to do so.{{sfn |Lagirarde |2006 |p=89}} Ray explains that this state of meditation, called ''[[Nirodha-Samapatti|nirodha-sam\u0101patti]]'', is associated with the prolonging of life, invulnerability to fire, and the attainment of Nirvana.{{sfn |Ray |1994 |p=372}}}} Though Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa died after the vow, his body remained intact according to his resolution.<!--15 n 49, 51-->{{sfn |Tournier |2014 |pp=15 notes 49, 51}} The three mountain peaks then closed in on the body. Later, King Aj\u0101ta\u015batru heard about the news of Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa's passing, and fainted of grief. He wanted to visit Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa once more.{{sfn |Lagirarde |2006 |p=87}} \u0100nanda and King Aj\u0101ta\u015batru went to the mountain, which slightly opened, just enough for the two to see Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa's body.{{sfn |Lagirarde |2006 |p=87}} In the M\u016blasarv\u0101stiv\u0101da discipline and the ''A\u015bok\u0101vad\u0101na'', the king wanted to cremate the body, but \u0100nanda told him it would remain until the time of Maitreya Buddha. When they left, the mountain closed up again.{{sfn |Kim |2011 |p=134}}{{sfn |Lagirarde |2006 |p=89}} Later, emperor A\u015boka would also visit the mountain. This happened when the monk [[Upagupta]] led A\u015boka to visit the ''st\u016bpa'' of the Buddha's disciples.{{sfn |Lagirarde |2006 |p=90}}\n\nThe accounts say that in the time of Maitreya Buddha the mountain opens upon his visit, in \"the way a ''[[cakravartin]]'' opens a city gate\".<!--219--> People in Maitreya Buddha's time are much taller than during the time of Gautama Buddha.<!--220-->{{sfn |Strong |2007 |page=220}}{{sfn |Buswell |Lopez |2013 |loc=Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa}} In one text, Maitreya Buddha's disciples are contemptuous of Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa, whose head is no larger than an insect to them. Gautama Buddha's robe barely covers two of their fingers, making them marvel how small Gautama Buddha was.{{refn |See {{harvtxt |Strong |2007 |page=220}}. {{harvtxt |Buswell |Lopez |2013 |loc=Maitreya}} also mention the two fingers.}} Eventually, in several accounts, Maitreya Buddha takes Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa's body in his hands, explains to his pupils what great person he was, and sees the body miraculously burn in his hands, according to Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa's vow.{{refn |For the P\u0101li account, see {{harvtxt |Strong |2007 |p=220}}. For the Thai account, see {{harvtxt |Lagirarde |2006 |p=86}}. For a Chinese account, see {{harvtxt |Deeg |1999 |p=158}}. For Maitreya Buddha's explanation, see Larigarde and Deeg.}} But in the well-known account of Xuanzang, as well as the [[Tocharian languages|Tocharian]] ''[[Maitreyasamitin\u0101\u1e6daka]]'' and other accounts, Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa is alive and waiting in his \"cavern of meditation\", until the time of Maitreya: he hands over the robe to Maitreya Buddha explaining who it is from, and expresses his joy at having met two Buddhas. He then hovers in the air, displays supernatural accomplishments that are reminiscent of Gautama Buddha, and bursts miraculously into flames.{{refn |See {{harvtxt |Kim |2011 |p=135}} and {{harvtxt |Adamek |2011 |loc=Bodhidharma's Robe}}. Kim mentions the supernatural accomplishments; Adamek says that Xuanzang's account is well-known. {{harvtxt|Kumamoto|2009|p=5}} mentions the Tocharian text. For the words of Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa and the mention of other accounts, see {{harvtxt |Strong |2007 |p=219}}. For the expression \"cavern of meditation\", see {{harvtxt |Ray |1994 |p=114}}. For the reminiscence, see {{harvtxt |Deeg |1999 |p=158 note 39}}.}} In the M\u016blasarv\u0101stiv\u0101da discipline and the ''A\u015bok\u0101vad\u0101na'', the account ends with Maitreya Buddha's disciples attaining ''arhat'', as the encounter has caused their pride to be humbled.{{refn |For the M\u016blasarv\u0101stiv\u0101da texts, see {{harvtxt |Lagirarde |2006 |p=89}}. For the ''A\u015bok\u0101vad\u0101na'' and the pride, see {{harvtxt |Ray |1994 |p=109}}.}}\n\n==== Cults and practices ====\n[[File:Sculptures at Sheh, image of Maitreya.png|thumb|Image of Maitreya, Tibet, 10th century. {{harvtxt |Deeg |1999 |p=167 note 76}} identifies the image at the right with Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa.]]\nThe Kukku\u1e6dap\u0101da Mountain was identified by traditional authors with several places in North India, and some of these places had become famous place of pilgrimage and [[cult (religious practice)|cult]] by the time the Chinese pilgrim [[Faxian]] (337\u2013{{circa}}422 CE) and later Xuanzang visited.{{refn |For pilgrimage, see {{harvtxt |Strong |2007 |p=219}}. For the [[cult (religious practice)|cult]], see {{harvtxt |Ray |1994 |pp=114\u2013115}}.}} These pilgrimage places, with depictions of Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa, have been connected by Buddhist studies scholar Vincent Tournier with an aspiration to be born in Maitreya's following.{{sfn |Tournier |2013 |p=375}}\n\nIn sixth-century Chinese steles, Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa is often depicted waiting for Maitreya Buddha in the cave, cloaked in the robe and a hood.<!--131--> He is given a role as successor of the Gautama Buddha.<!--133--> Buddhist studies scholar Miyaji Akira proposes that Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa waiting in the cave became the basis of a theme in [[Korean Buddhist art]] featuring monks meditating in caves.<!--135--> [[Korean studies]] scholar Sunkyung Kim does point out, however, that similar motifs can already be found in earlier Buddhist art, showing Buddha Gautama sitting.<!--126-->{{sfn |Kim |2011 |pp=126, 131, 133, 135}} The story of Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa awaiting Maitreya Buddha had an important impact in Japan, up until early modern times. [[Jikigy\u014d]] (1671\u2013{{circa}}1724), the leader of a [[chiliastic]] religious movement, locked himself in his monastic cell to starve to death, and have his [[Buddhist mummification|mummified corpse]] meet with Maitreya Buddha in the future.{{sfn |Deeg |1999 |p=168}}\n\nWith regard to South- and Southeast Asia, the interest in the relationship between Maitreya and Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa spread to [[Ceylon]] during the reign of [[Kassapa II of Anuradhapura|Kassapa II]] (652\u2013661) and [[Kassapa V of Anuradhapura|Kassapa V]] (929\u2013939). They most likely honored Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa for his role in the Abhidharma recitations at the First Council. Kassapa V identified with Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa ({{lang-pi|Mah\u0101kassapa}}) and aspired to be reborn with Maitreya as well.{{sfn |Deeg |1999 |p=153 note 30}} Presently, the account of Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa's ''parinirv\u0101\u1e47a'' is not widely recognized in dominant Buddhist traditions in Thailand, but Lagirarde raises the question whether this is only a recent development.<!--91--> It is still a common belief among the Thai that the body of a [[Luang Por|very pure and venerated monk]] will not decompose.<!--87-->{{sfn |Lagirarde |2006 |pp=87, 91}}\n\n==== Scholarly analysis ====\n[[File:Rajgir - 062 Mahakasyapa (9244726682).jpg|Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa, woodblock print by [[Munakata Shiko]], Japan, 1939 |thumb |alt=Abstract woodblock print in black ink with monk, holding his arms crossed in front of his chest]]\nIn the early texts, Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa is depicted as the keeper of the Buddhist teaching during the First Council; in the story of him awaiting Maitreya Buddha this role is extended. In some early Chinese texts, Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa is seen stating to \u0100nanda that all devotees present at the ''parinirv\u0101\u1e47a'' of the Buddha Gautama will be reborn in [[Tusita]] heaven and meet Maitreya; in the story of the cave this association with Maitreya is further extended.<!--161--> Since the end of Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa's life after the First Council was not discussed in the early texts, it was easy for legends to be developed around his demise, or the postponement thereof.<!--165-->{{sfn |Deeg |1999 |pp=161, 165}}\n\nTournier speculates that the story of Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa resolving that his body endure until the next Buddha is a \"conscious attempt to dress the ''arhat'' in a ''[[bodhisattva]]'' (Buddha-to-be) garb\".{{sfn |Tournier |2014 |pp=44\u201345}} On a similar note, Strong argues the story shows sentiments that are at the root of the ''bodhisattva'' ideal,<!--62--> and may have led to the idea of the [[Eighteen Arhats]] ({{zh|p=lo-han}}) that \"postpone\" their death to protect the Buddhist teaching till the arrival of Maitreya.<!--64-->{{sfn |Strong |1994 |pp=62, 64}} Indologist [[Padmanabh Jaini]] argues that the story was created by the M\u016blasarv\u0101stiv\u0101dins to connect Maitreya Buddha to Gautama Buddha, through a line of transmission. In this, they may have been influenced by [[Indo-Greeks]] and Persians, who ruled the area where the M\u016blasarv\u0101stiv\u0101dins lived.{{refn |group=note |Just like Jaini, Silk mentions there may be influence from Iranian traditions.{{sfn |Silk |2003 |pp=181\u2013182 note 18}} Buddhist studies scholar [[Jan Nattier]] notes the resemblance with the Iranian figure [[Gershasp (gladiator)|K\u0259r\u0259saspa]], a similar name, who waits in suspended animation for his savior [[Saoshyant|Sao\u0161yant]].{{sfn |Nattier |1988 |p=46 note 60}}}} Historian Max Deeg raises the question, however, that if Jaini is correct, why no traces of an early development of the legend can be found.{{sfn |Deeg |1999 |p=159 note 43}} Silk also hypothesizes that the story was developed by Mah\u0101y\u0101na authors to create a narrative to connect the two Buddhas physically through Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa's ''paranirv\u0101\u1e47a'' and the passing on of the robe. Lagirarde notes, however, that not all \u0100gama sources insist on connecting the two [[Buddha (title)|Buddhas]]. Furthermore, P\u0101li, Thai and Laotian sources do not mention the passing on of the robe, yet the meeting is still narrated as significant.{{refn |{{harvtxt |Lagirarde |2006 |p=91}}. Lagirarde cites {{harvtxt |Jaini |1988 |p=75}}. Silk explains his ideas in {{harvtxt |Silk |2003 |pp=175\u2013176}}.}} Silk also notes that the Sanskrit texts the ''[[Dharmaguptaka#Abhini\u1e63krama\u1e47a S\u016btra|Abhini\u1e63krama\u1e47a S\u016btra]]'', the ''[[Mah\u0101praj\u00f1\u0101p\u0101ramit\u014dpade\u015ba]]'' and the ''[[Divyavadana|Divy\u0101vad\u0101na]]'' contain the story of Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa under the mountain, and do not mention the robe of the Buddha at all. But in every version of the account there is a physical connection between Gautama Buddha, Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa and Maitreya Buddha.<!--200--> He concludes that Mah\u0101y\u0101na authors used Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa as a way to legitimize the Mah\u0101y\u0101na teachings, by affirming that there were more authentic teachings which had not yet come.<!--207-->{{sfn |Silk |2003 |pp=200, 207}}\n\nTranslator Saddhatissa, and with him Silk, argue that there is no equivalent account about Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa waiting in the cave that can be found in the P\u0101li tradition apart from a single reference in a post-canonical text. But Lagirarde points out that the reference found by Saddhatissa and Silk (called the ''Mah\u0101sampi\u1e47\u1e0danid\u0101na'', which Saddhatissa dates to the twelfth century) does indicate the story was known in the P\u0101li tradition.{{sfn |Lagirarde |2006 |p=80}}{{sfn |Silk |2003 |p=182 note 19}} Lagirarde also lists several later vernacular texts from Therav\u0101da countries that mention the account, in [[Thai language|Siamese]], [[Lanna language|Northern Thai]] and [[Laotian language|Laotian]] language.<!--81, 91-->{{sfn |Lagirarde |2006 |pp=81, 91}} Indeed, Silk himself points at a P\u0101li [[Sub-commentaries (Therav\u0101da)|sub-commentary]] to the ''[[A\u1e45guttara Nik\u0101ya]]'' which mentions that Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa retreated at age hundred twenty in a cave close to where the First Council was held. He would dwell there and \"make the Buddha's teaching last for 5000 years\".{{sfn |Silk |2003 |p=205 note 81}} The First Council itself was held in a cave too, and it may have led to the motif of Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa waiting in a cave.<!--161--> Furthermore, in some canonical P\u0101li texts Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa talks about the decay and disappearance of the Buddhist dispensation, which may also have been a foundation for the story.<!--163-->{{sfn |Deeg |1999 |pp=161, 163}}\n\n=== In Mah\u0101y\u0101na discourses ===\nIn general, Sanskrit texts often mention Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa.{{sfn |Buswell |Lopez |2013 |loc=Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa}} Silk argues that Mah\u0101y\u0101na polemicists used Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa as an interlocutor in their discourses, because of his stern conservative stance in the early texts and opposition of innovation,<!--179\u2013180--> and his close association with Gautama Buddha.<!--204--> This fit with the conservative ideas on Buddhist practice among the early Mah\u0101y\u0101na authors,<!--179\u2013180--> and the need to legitimize Mah\u0101y\u0101na doctrine,<!--204--> surrounding them with an aura of authenticity.<!--205-->{{sfn |Silk |2003 |pp=179\u2013180, 204\u2013205}}\n\n==== In Chan Buddhism ====\n[[File:Mahakasyapa smiling at the lotus flower.jpg|thumb|Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa smiling at the lotus flower, by [[Hishida Shuns\u014d]], 1897, [[Nihonga]] style. |left |upright=1.2]]\nMah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa has a significant role in texts from the [[Chan Buddhism|Chan]] tradition.{{sfn |Buswell |Lopez |2013 |loc=Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa}} In East Asia, there is a Chan and [[Zen]] tradition, first recounted in the ''[[The Jingde Record of the Transmission of the Lamp]]'' ({{zh|p=Tiansheng Guangdeng-lu|t=\u666f\u5fb7\u50b3\u71c8\u9304}}), which is a 1036 genealogical record about Chan Buddhism.{{sfn |Silk |2003 |p=203}}{{sfn |Welter |2000 |p=96}} According to this tradition, Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa once received a direct \"transmission\" from Gautama Buddha. Chan and Zen purport to lead their adherents to insights akin to that mentioned by the Buddha in the ''[[Flower Sermon]]'' ({{zh|p=Nianhua weixiao|t=\u62c8\u83ef\u5fae\u7b11 |l=Holding up a flower and smiling subtly}}){{refn |group=note |The English title ''Flower Sermon'' is a Western invention.{{sfn |Buswell |Lopez |2014 |loc=nianhua weixiao}} It is also known as the \"First Zen Story\".{{sfn |Voros |2014 |p=388}}}} given on the [[Vulture Peak]], in which he held up a white flower and just admired it in his hand, without speaking. All the disciples just looked on without knowing how to react, but only Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa smiled faintly, and the Buddha picked him as one who truly understood him and was worthy to be the one receiving a special \"mind-to-mind transmission\" ({{zh|p=yixin chuanxin}}).{{refn |For the intention of Zen and the Flower Sermon, see {{harvtxt |Tarrant County College, 2007 |p=11}}. For the Vulture Peak, see {{cite web |last1=Hershock |first1=P. |title=Chan Buddhism |url=https://plato.stanford.edu/entries/buddhism-chan/ |website=The Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy |publisher=Metaphysics Research Lab, [[Stanford University]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190911034819/https://plato.stanford.edu/entries/buddhism-chan/ |archivedate=11 September 2019 |url-status=live |date=2019}} For the Chinese terms, see {{harvtxt |Buswell |Lopez |2014 |loc=nianhua weixiao}}.}}\n[[File:Mahakasyapa.jpg|thumb|Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa holding a flower. |alt=Monk meditating and holding a flower]]\nThus, a way within Buddhism developed which concentrated on direct experience rather than on rational creeds or revealed scriptures. Chan therefore became a method of meditative religion which seek to enlighten people in the manner that Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa experienced:{{sfn |Tarrant County College, 2007 |p=11}}<ref name=\"Herschock\">{{cite web |last1=Hershock |first1=P. |title=Chan Buddhism |url=https://plato.stanford.edu/entries/buddhism-chan/ |website=The Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy |publisher=Metaphysics Research Lab, [[Stanford University]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190911034819/https://plato.stanford.edu/entries/buddhism-chan/ |archivedate=11 September 2019 |url-status=live |date=2019}}</ref> \"A special transmission outside the scriptures, directly pointing at the heart of man, looking into one's own nature.\" This transmission was then purportedly passed on by the Buddha to Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa, who then passed it on to a long list of Indian and Chinese patriarchs, eventually reaching [[Bodhidharma]] (5th or 6th century CE), who brought Chan Buddhism to China, and passed it on to [[Huike]] (487\u2013593 CE).{{sfn |Powers |2016 |p=47}} The Jingde Record took the passing on of the robe from Buddha Gautama to Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa to refer to a secret transmission of Chan teachings, within the specific Chan lineage.{{sfn |Sanvido |2017 |p=343}} The story of the Flower Sermon was also recorded in later texts, between the 11th and 14th centuries. At least one of these texts was probably written to defend the authenticity of the Flower Sermon, which was even questioned in Chan circles. Eventually, the story became well known among both Buddhist monks and Chan-oriented [[scholar-official|literati]]. It was incorporated as a meditative topic in the 1228 Chan text ''[[The Gateless Barrier]]'' ({{zh|p=Wumen Guan}}), in which the Buddha confirmed that the mind-to-mind transmission was complete.{{refn |See {{harvtxt |Buswell |Lopez |2014 |loc=nianhua weixiao}} and {{harvtxt |Harvey |2013 |p=222}}. Harvey states that the story originated among the \"Chan literati\".}} Although the Flower Sermon's main point is to depict a wordless special transmission \"outside the teaching\", the tradition was defended and authorized through Buddhist scripture.{{sfn |Welter |2000 |p=97}}\n\nThe Flower Sermon event is regarded by modern scholars as an invention, but does provide insight into the philosophical concerns and identity of Chan Buddhism.<ref name=\"Herschock\" /> Since Chan Buddhism values the direct transmission from the teacher's mind to that of the student, more so than scriptures, the unbroken lineage of patriarchs is an important part of the tradition.{{sfn |Buswell |Lopez |2013 |loc=fozu}} Moreover, whereas in many Buddhist traditions it was recounted that Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa would pass on Gautama Buddha's robe to Maitreya Buddha, in Chan a different tradition developed, in which Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa passed on the robe to the next patriarch \u0100nanda, and so on through a list of Indian and Chinese patriarchs.<!--339--> Some Chan masters, such as [[D\u014dgen]] (1200\u20131253), did believe that this robe would eventually be passed forward to Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa and eventually Maitreya.<!--340-->{{sfn |Faure |1995 |pp=339\u2013340}}\n\nAs Japanese Buddhist texts saw the transmission of Gautama Buddha's robe as a symbol of birth and gestation, similarly, the flower in the Flower Sermon was seen as a symbol of death and cremation.{{sfn |Faure |1995 |p=361, note 119}} Besides the Flower Sermon, the appearance of the Buddha's feet when Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa pays his final respects, as well as the Buddha sharing his seat with Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa are also considered mind-to-mind transmissions.{{sfn |Do-Ryun |1964 |p=41}}\n\n== Legacy ==\n=== Values ===\n[[File:Mahakasyapa, Kizil, Cave above the Largest Cave, c. 422-529 AD, wall painting - Ethnological Museum, Berlin - DSC01724.JPG|Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa depicted with hair and beard. Mural painting, [[Kizil Caves]], [[Xinjiang]], China, fourth\u2013fifth century CE |thumb |alt=Bearded man with stern face, long earlobes and one shoulder uncovered]]\nBeing one of the most well-known disciples of the Buddha, Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa embodies the highest ideals of early Buddhist monasticism.{{refn |{{harvtxt |Ray |1994 |p=105}}, cited in {{harvtxt |Clarke |2014 |p=110}}.}} Buddhist studies scholar Asanga Tilakaratne points out that Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa's ascetic and austere values and dislike for women on the one hand, and \u0100nanda's active, city-dwelling values and support for women on the other hand, are two sides of the spectrum than can be seen throughout the history of Buddhist monasticism. Monastic vocations and monastic orders tend to be along these two ends of the spectrum,<!--177-178--> with compassionate engagement on the one hand, and dispassionate detachment on the other hand.<!--187--> This can be traced back to these two disciples.<!--178-->{{sfn |Tilakaratne |2003 |pp=177\u2013178, 187}} Specifically, the Therav\u0101da tradition has been influenced much by the model of Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa.{{sfn |Analayo |2010 |p=17}} In some early Therav\u0101da texts about Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa, the values of forest renunciation are contrasted with that of settled monasticism. Renunciation in the forest is considered superior, and settled monasticism is considered a deterioration of the holy life.<!--113-114-->{{sfn |Ray |1994 |pp=113\u2013114}}\n\nPrzyluski and several other scholars have argued that in the early texts, Mah\u0101ka\u015byapa represents ascetic and ''brahmin'' values.{{refn |See {{harvtxt |Analayo |2010 |p=14, note 42}}, {{harvtxt |Analayo |2016 |p=173}} and {{harvtxt |Clarke |2014 |p=107}}. Only An\u0101layo mentions both.}} The ascetic values are seen in the account in which Mah\u0101ka\u015byapa refuses to give up ascetic practices, going against the advice of the Buddha.{{sfn |Analayo |2016 |p=173}}{{sfn |Analayo |2010 |p=14}} Such refusal was highly unusual for a disciple of the Buddha.<!--note 78--> The ''brahmin'' values can be observed from the account of the accusations leveled against \u0100nanda, which appear to be based more on ''brahmin'' values than violations of monastic discipline.<!--174--> Both these ''brahmin'' and ascetic values, as represented by the figure of Mah\u0101ka\u015byapa, would lead to strong opposition to the founding of the ''bhik\u1e63un\u012b'' order in early Buddhism.<!--174-175-->{{sfn |Analayo |2016 |pp=174\u2013175, note 78}} The ascetic values Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa represented, however, were a reaction to less austere tendencies that appeared in early Buddhism at the time.{{sfn |Analayo |2010 |p=14}}\n\nRay concludes that the texts present Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa in different ways.<!--117--> Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa assumes many roles and identities in the texts, that of a renunciant saint, a lawgiver, an anti-establishment figure, but also a \"guarantor of future justice\" in the time of Maitreya.{{sfn |Ray |1994 |p=117}} Indologist [[C.A.F. Rhys Davids]] (1857\u20131942) stated he was \"both the anchorite and the friend of mankind, even of the outcast\".{{sfn |Rhys Davids |1914 |p=160}} His figure unites the opposites of established monasticism and forest renunciation, and \"transcends any particular Buddhist group or set of interests\".<!--117--> Drawing from Przyluski's [[textual criticism]], Ray argues that when Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa replaced Kau\u1e47\u1e0dinya as the head of the ''sa\u1e43gha'' after the Buddha's passing away, his ascetic saint-like role was appropriated into the monastic establishment<!--118--> to serve the need for a charismatic leader.<!--396--> This led him to possess both the character of the anti-establishment ascetic, as well as that of the settled monastic governor.<!--118-->{{sfn |Ray |1994 |pp=114, 117\u2013118, 396}}\n\n=== Eldest son of the Buddha ===\n[[File:Buddha and the gospel of Buddhism (1916) (14779469804).jpg|thumb |Funeral pyre of the Buddha being lit at the arrival of Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa, from ''Buddha and the Gospel of Buddhism'', [[Ananda Coomaraswamy]], 1916 |alt=Illustration in book, 3 monks sitting at fire]]\nIn Abhidharma texts of several Buddhist schools, the fulfilment of Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa's vow in the mountain Kuku\u1e6dapada is connected to a vow Gautama Buddha took to prevent his body from being cremated before Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa's arrival at his teacher's cremation grounds.<!--17--> Buddhist studies scholar [[Gregory Schopen]] analyzes several post-canonical Buddhist texts and concludes that in both instances, a vow is taken based on [[riddhi|psychic powers]], which is then shown to be effective after the death of the person with those psychic powers.<!--18 n 62--> Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa's psychic powers are needed for his role in the texts as the one who preserves the Buddha's dispensation. Indeed, later Buddhist texts depict Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa as the eldest son of the Buddha, who leads both the funerals of his father and, as his heir, presides over the First Council.<!--20-21--> Eventually, he came to be seen as the first teacher after the Buddha and as the beginning of a lineage of teachers. This conceptualization is found within several Buddhist schools, including the Therav\u0101dins and the [[Mahasanghika|Mah\u0101sa\u1e45ghikas]].<!--21-22 n 78-->{{sfn |Tournier |2014 |pp=17\u201318, note 62, 20\u201322, note 78}} Indeed, Therav\u0101da sees him as a sort of \"Father of the Church\".{{sfn |Lagirarde |2006}}\n\n=== Historical lineages ===\nFurthermore, Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa is described in the P\u0101li commentary to the ''D\u012bgha Nik\u0101ya'' as the person responsible for the preservation of collection that was the precursor to the ''Sa\u1e43yutta Nik\u0101ya'' and the ''Sa\u1e43yuktaka \u0100gama''. In both the Nik\u0101ya and \u0100gama version of this same collection, therefore, a great deal of attention is given to him, and Tournier thinks it possible that the lineage of teachers preserving this collection, probably originating from the Sth\u0101viras, also conceived themselves as preservers of Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa's legacy.<!--26--> This is also reflected in the language used in inscriptions from the Sinhalese monk Mah\u0101n\u0101man (5th\u20136th century CE) and in later texts used in the Sinhalese tradition, which both connect Mah\u0101n\u0101man's lineage with that of Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa, and also that of the future Buddha Maitreya.<!--26-29-->{{sfn |Tournier |2014 |pp=26\u201329}} However, some P\u0101li sources indicate that Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa was part of the lineage of the ''A\u1e45guttara Nik\u0101ya'' [[Bh\u0101\u1e47aka|reciters]], which is another collection than the ''Sa\u1e43yutta''.{{sfn |Gethin |2008 |p=18}}\n\nOne of the early Buddhist schools, the [[K\u0101\u015byap\u012bya]]s ({{lang-pi|Kassap\u012bya}}), was founded by Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa, according to scholars [[Paramartha|Param\u0101rtha]] (499\u2013569) and [[Kuiji]] (632\u2013682). Other traditional scholars have argued instead it was another K\u0101\u015byapa, who lived three centuries after the Buddha.{{sfn |Buswell |Lopez |2013 |loc=K\u0101\u015byap\u012bya}} Furthermore, when the differences between the early Buddhist schools grew more prominent, the [[Mahasanghika|Mah\u0101sa\u1e45ghikas]] affiliated themselves with the figure of Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa,<!--207--> and claimed him as their founder and patron-saint.<!--239--> They presented themselves as more orthodox than other schools, such as Therav\u0101da.<!--240-->{{sfn |Dutt |1925 |pp=207, 239\u2013240}}\n\n=== In art and culture ===\n[[File:\u4e5d\u5929\u7985\u9662 \u91ca\u8fe6\u725f\u5c3c\u4f5b.jpg|thumb|alt=Temple with Buddha image, flanked by \u0100nanda and Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa |In Mah\u0101y\u0101na iconography, \u0100nanda is often depicted flanking the Buddha at the right side, together with Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa at the left. {{ill|Temple of Heaven Garden|zh|\u5929\u575b\u82b1\u56ed}} in [[Shantou]], China.]]\nIn Buddhist art, depictions of Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa have \"left an indelible mark\". He was depicted in ''paranirv\u0101\u1e47a'' scenes as a reassurance that Gautama Buddha's dispensation would not be lost; he was depicted next to Maitreya Buddha as an anticipatory vision of the future.{{sfn |Kim |2011 |p=137}} The scene in which he paid his final respects to the Buddha became a well-known depiction in Buddhist art,{{sfn |Lee |2010 |p=57}} and Strong has argued that it may have led to the cult of the [[Buddha footprint|Buddha's footprints]].{{sfn |Strong |2007 |p=113}}\n\nIn Chinese art, Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa is usually depicted with long beard and hair. Buddhist studies scholar Mun-Keat Choong hypothesizes that these depictions found their way back in at least one Chinese Buddhist discourse, the discourse in which Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa is criticized for looking inappropriate. This may have been the work of the translators.{{sfn |Mun-keat |2017 |p=303}} In Mah\u0101y\u0101na iconography, Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa is often depicted flanking the Buddha at the left side, together with \u0100nanda at the right.{{sfn |Buswell |Lopez |2013 |loc=Er xieshi}} The two disciples have been very popular in art depictions since the time of [[Greco-Buddhism]],<!--417--> and Migot argued that the tradition of Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa and \u0100nanda being the Buddha's two main disciples was older than that of the tradition of \u015a\u0101riputra and Maudgaly\u0101yana, because in the ''Mah\u0101parinibb\u0101na Sutta'' only the former pair features, and the traditional explanation for this that \u015a\u0101riputra and Maudgaly\u0101yana did not outlive the Buddha seems unconvincing.<!--536-->{{sfn |Migot |1954 |pp=417, 536}}{{refn |group=note |As for Therav\u0101da iconography, Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa is usually not depicted flanking the Buddha.{{sfn |Edkins |2013 |pages=42\u201343}}}} In Chan temples, the image of Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa is often placed in a central position, being the first patriarch of the tradition.{{sfn |Jorgensen |2000 |pp=158, 271}} In the history of Mah\u0101y\u0101na Buddhism, as the rag-robe asceticism of Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa contributed to his legendary figure and the legitimation of the Mah\u0101y\u0101na creed, rag-robes became an icon in East Asian Buddhism. The Buddha's disciples and founders of East Asian Buddhism were often depicted in them.{{sfn |Riggs |2007 |p=91}} When ''[[fukudenkai]]'' sewing groups were founded in Japan in the early twentieth century, to introduce sewing robes for monastics as a spiritual practice,<!--321--> they often referred to the early Buddhist account of Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa receiving the rag-robes from the Buddha.<!--327--> ''Fukudenkai'' practitioners usually use second-hand clothes to sew the rag-robes, just like in the time of the Buddha.<!--327-328-->{{sfn |Riggs |2004 |pp=321, 327\u2013328}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist |group=note |30em}}\n\n== Citations ==\n{{Reflist|20em}}\n\n== References ==\n{{refbegin |30em}}\n* {{Citation |last1=Adamek |first1=W.L. |title=The Teachings of Master Wuzhu: Zen and Religion of No-Religion |date=2011 |publisher=[[Columbia University Press]] |isbn=978-0-231-52792-7}}\n* {{Citation |last1=Ambros |first1=Barbara R |title=A Rite of Their Own: Japanese Buddhist Nuns and the Anan k\u014dshiki |journal=[[Japanese Journal of Religious Studies]] |date=27 June 2016 |volume=43 |issue=1 |pages=207\u2013250 |doi=10.18874/jjrs.43.1.2016.207-250}}\n* {{Citation |last=Analayo |first=B. |year=2010 |title=Once Again on Bakkula |author-link=Bhikkhu Analayo |journal=The Indian International Journal of Buddhist Studies |volume=11 |pages=1\u201328}}\n* {{Citation |last=Analayo |first=B. |author-link=Bhikkhu Analayo |year=2015 |title=Pratyekabuddhas in the Ekottarika-\u0101gama |journal=Journal of the Oxford Centre for Buddhist Studies |volume=8 |url=http://jocbs.org/index.php/jocbs/article/viewFile/103/122 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191213141452/http://jocbs.org/index.php/