1ka\u015byapa's Precedence to \u0100nanda in the R\u0101jag\u1e5bha Council |journal=Indogaku Bukkyogaku Kenkyu [Journal of Indian and Buddhist Studies] |volume=11 |issue=2 |url=https://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/ibk1952/11/2/11_2_824/_pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180921034502/https://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/ibk1952/11/2/11_2_824/_pdf |pages=824{{en dash}}817 |archive-date=21 September 2018 |url-status=live|doi=10.4259/ibk.11.824 }}<!--some Japanese journals number their pages in reverse order-->\n* {{Citation |last1=Voros |first1=Sebastjan |title=Mahakashyapa's Smile: Language, Silence, and Mysticism |journal=Synthesis Philosophica |date=January 2014 |volume=58 |issue=2 |pages=387\u2013402 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/292087649 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217191449/https://www.researchgate.net/publication/292087649_Mahakashyapa's_Smile_Language_Silence_and_Mysticism |archive-date=17 February 2020 |url-status=live}}\n* {{Citation |last=Welter |first=A. |year=2000 |chapter=Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa\u2019s Smile: Silent Transmission and the Kung-an (K\u014dan) Tradition |title=The K\u014dan: Texts and Contexts in Zen Buddhism |pages=75\u2013109 |editor1-last=Heine |editor1-first=S. |editor2-last=Wright |editor2-first=D.S. |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |isbn=978-0-19-802780-5}}\n* {{Citation |first=A. |last=Welter |editor1-last=Buswell|editor1-first=Robert E.|title=Lineage |encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of Buddhism|date=2004|publisher=Macmillan Reference USA, [[Thomson Gale]]|volume=2 |pages=462\u2013463 <!-- |isbn=0-02-865720-9-->|isbn=978-0-02-865718-9}}\n* {{Citation |last1=Wilson |first1=L. |editor-last1=Holt |editor-first1=J. |editor-last2=Kinnard |editor-first2=J.N. |editor-last3=Walters |editor-first3=J.S. |year=2003 |chapter=Beggars Can Be Choosers: Mah\u0101kassapa as a Selective Eater of Offerings |title=Constituting Communities, Therav\u0101da Buddhism and the Religious Cultures of South and Southeast Asia |pages=57\u201370 |isbn=978-0-7914-8705-1}}\n* {{Citation |last=Wiltshire |first=M.G. |year=1983 |title=The\" Suicide\" Problem in the P\u0101li Canon |journal=Journal of the International Association of Buddhist Studies |pages=124\u2013140 |url=https://journals.ub.uni-heidelberg.de/index.php/jiabs/article/download/8609/2516 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217175753/https://journals.ub.uni-heidelberg.de/index.php/jiabs/article/download/8609/2516 |archive-date=17 February 2020 |url-status=live}}\n* {{Citation |last1=Witanachchi |first1=C.|editor1-last=Malalasekera |editor1-first=G. P. |editor2-last=Weeraratne |editor2-first=W. G. |editor1-link=G. P. Malalasekera |title=\u0100nanda |encyclopedia=Encyclopaedia of Buddhism |date=1965 |publisher=[[Government of Sri Lanka]] |url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/231090852/Enceylopaedia-of-Buddhism-Vol-i |volume=1 |oclc=2863845613}}\n* {{Citation |last1=Zurcher |first1=Erik |editor1-last=Williams |editor1-first=Paul |title=Buddhism: Critical Concepts in Religious Studies, 8: Buddhism in China, East Asia, and Japan |date=2005 |publisher=[[Routledge]] |chapter=Buddhist Influence on Early Taoism |isbn=0-415-33234-6 |page=378}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://www.accesstoinsight.org/lib/authors/hecker/wheel345.html Mah\u0101 Kassapa, Father of the Sangha], by Hellmuth Hecker, biography based on the [[Pali Canon|P\u0101li Canon]], revised and enlarged translation from Wissen und Wandel volume XXI, number 6, 1975, (German) by [[Nyanaponika]] Thera, The Wheel Publication No. 345, {{ISBN|955-24-0026-0}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20190713140808/https://www.accesstoinsight.org/lib/authors/hecker/wheel345.html archived here.]\n* [https://www.learnreligions.com/disciple-mahakasyapa-father-of-sangha-449645 ''Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa''], hosted by Learning Religion, [https://web.archive.org/web/20200217191247/https://www.learnreligions.com/disciple-mahakasyapa-father-of-sangha-449645 archived here.]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-rel|bu}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Lineage (Buddhism)|Lineage of Buddhist patriarchs]]<br /><small>(According to the [[Zen]] schools of China and Japan)</small>|before=[[Gautama Buddha|\u015a\u0101kyamuni]]<br /><small>Beginning of the lineage</small>|after=[[Ananda]]|years=}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Buddhism topics}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mahakasyapa}}\n[[Category:Foremost disciples]]\n[[Category:Arhats]]\n[[Category:Indian Buddhist monks]]\n[[Category:Buddhist patriarchs]]\n[[Category:5th-century Buddhist monks]]\n", "name_user": "Vami IV", "label": "safe", "comment": "CE", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mah%C4%81k%C4%81%C5%9Byapa"}
{"title_page": "Henley Business School", "text_new": "{{otheruses|Henley College (disambiguation)}}\n{{Refimprove|date=April 2009}}\n{{Coord|51|33|47|N|0|52|57|W|region:GB_scale:10000|display=title}}\n\n'''[https://www.henley.ac.uk/ Henley Business School] '''is the [[business school]] of the [[University of Reading]]. It was formed by merging the previously independent '''Henley Management College''', formerly the '''Administrative Staff College''', with the existing business school of the University of Reading. As a result of the merger it now occupies two sites: [[Greenlands|Greenlands Campus]], near the town of [[Henley-on-Thames]], the original site of the Henley Management College, and [[Whiteknights Park|Whiteknights Campus]] in [[Reading, Berkshire|Reading]].\n\nIt is among only 73 institutions worldwide to be granted [[triple accreditation]] by the three largest and most influential business school accreditation associations: [[European Quality Improvement System|EQUIS]], [[Association of MBAs|AMBA]] and the [[Association to Advance Collegiate Schools of Business|AACSB]]. It is ranked among the world's top 50 business schools by the Financial Times<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://rankings.ft.com/businessschoolrankings/european-business-school-rankings-2014|title=Financial Times European Business School Rankings 2015|accessdate=15 December 2017}}</ref> and The Economist.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.economist.com/whichmba/full-time-mba-ranking?page=3|title=The Economist Which MBA? Full time MBA ranking|accessdate=15 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe current dean is [https://www.henley.ac.uk/people/person/professor-john-board Professor John Board.]\n\n==History==\n[[Image:Henley Management College.jpg|thumb|Greenlands campus on the banks of the river Thames]]\n\n===1945-1981===\nThe Administrative Staff College was set up in 1945 at [[Henley-on-Thames]] as the civilian equivalent of the Military Staff Colleges. It offered short courses in problems of advanced management. The College was offered the use of [[Greenlands]] by the [[William Smith, 3rd Viscount Hambleden|3rd Viscount Hambledon]] in 1946, and was bought outright from the family in 1952. In its formative years, the College was influenced by the management consultant and writer [[Lyndall Urwick]], the academic [[Hector Hetherington]], the civil servant [[Donald Banks|Sir Donald Banks]] and the businessman [[Geoffrey Heyworth, 1st Baron Heyworth|Sir Geoffrey Heyworth]] (later Lord Heyworth);<ref>Brech, Edward, Andrew Thomson & John F Wilson, ''Lyndall Urwick, Management Pioneer: A Biography'', Oxford University Press, 2010.</ref> its curriculum was designed by its first Principal, [[Noel Frederick Hall|Noel Hall]]. From the beginning, its intention was to bring together executives from [[Her Majesty's Civil Service]], private business and [[Nationalization#United Kingdom|nationalised industries]] to help develop their skills for promotion to senior management. In the late 1960s, Dr Raymond Meredith Belbin conducted research at the college which lead to the theory of [[Team Role Inventories]]. \n\nThe first Masters (MA in Business) ran in 1974; this was renamed the MBA by the end of the 1970s. In 1980, the college began to offer scholars to Women in Management. This tradition continues today through the [https://www.henley.ac.uk/about-us/women-in-leadership-scholarship Women in Leadership scholarship].\n\n<br />\n\n[[Image:ICMA Thomson Reuters.JPG|thumb|right|The [[ICMA Centre]] Thomson Reuters Trading Rooms]]\n\n===1981-2008===\nIn 1981, the College changed its name from its original title to '''Henley - The Management College'''. This was changed again to the '''Henley Management College''' when it was awarded a [[Royal charter#United Kingdom|Royal charter]] in 1991. By 2002, the College achieved [[triple accreditation]] status from the [[Association to Advance Collegiate Schools of Business]] (AACSB), the [[Association of MBAs]] (AMBA) and the [[European Quality Improvement System]] (EQUIS).<ref>{{cite web|title=Henley Business School rankings and facts|url=http://www.henley.ac.uk/about/hbs-business-school-rankings.aspx|publisher=Henley Business School|accessdate=18 October 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121015003500/http://www.henley.ac.uk/about/hbs-business-school-rankings.aspx|archivedate=15 October 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> \n\nOverseas operations began in 1988, with courses offered in Hong Kong, Finland, Demark and Germany.\n\nIn 2005, MBAid launched, providing a working relationship between MBA students and a range of NGOs in South Africa. This tradition continues today, as students of the [https://www.henley.ac.uk/mba/course/executive-mba-global Executive MBA - Global] take a module in the second stage of the programme, [https://www.henley.ac.uk/mba/course/executive-mba-global#module-info-reputation-and-responsibility-with-global-immersion-study-south-africa-4 Reputation and Responsibility with Global Immersion Study], wherein they undertake consulting projects in the NGO sector in South Africa. \n\n===2008-present===\nIn 2008, the Henley Management College merged with the University of Reading to form the '''[https://www.henley.ac.uk/ Henley Business School]'''. It consists of the [https://www.henley.ac.uk/phd/course/international-business-and-strategy School of International Business and Strategy]; the [https://www.henley.ac.uk/school/leadership-organisations-and-behaviour School of Leadership, Organisations and Behaviour]; the [https://www.henley.ac.uk/school/marketing-and-reputation School of Marketing and Reputation]; the [https://www.henley.ac.uk/school/business-informatics-systems-and-accounting School of Business Informatics, Systems and Accountancy] (which includes the Informatics Research Centre); the [https://www.henley.ac.uk/school/real-estate-and-planning School of Real Estate & Planning]; the [[ICMA Centre]]; and [https://www.henley.ac.uk/executive-education Executive Education Programmes].\n\nIn 2017, Henley Business School announced the [https://www.henley.ac.uk/the-army-higher-education-pathway Army Higher Education Pathway (AHEP)], which allows selected Officer Cadets entering the Commissioning Course at the [[Royal Military Academy Sandhurst]], to pursue either a BSc or MSc in Leadership and Strategic studies over the early years of their career.\n\nWhile the [[Master of Business Administration|MBA]] and corporate learning activities are offered from the Greenlands campus, all [[undergraduate]], [[postgraduate]] and [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] courses are offered from the Whiteknights campus of the University of Reading. A former country estate of the [[Marquis of Blandford]], the 130 hectare Whiteknights campus holds conservation meadows, a rare tree collection and a large lake. In 2009 the School moved into a new building in Whiteknights, with facilities for lectures, conferences and visitors.\n\n==Academics==\nAt its Greenlands campus, the Henley Business School offers an MBA for executive managers, known as [https://www.henley.ac.uk/level/the-henley-mba the Henley MBA], in addition to corporate and executive education programmes, with students from more than 100 countries.<ref>{{cite web|last=Henley Business School|first=Henley Business School|title=Henley Business School Key Facts and Rankings 2015|url=http://www.henley.ac.uk/files/pdf/miscellaneous/Key_facts_Regatta_Expertise__Rankings__Facts__2015.pdf|accessdate=15 December 2017}}</ref> The Henley MBA is designed for experienced, practicing managers, and aims to enhance their leadership skills or prepare for a senior management position; the average age of programme members is 38 years. It is offered in executive (2 years), [[distance learning]] (2.5 years) modes and flexible executive, a programme that allows participants to continue to work full-time and to study The Henley MBA part-time. \n\nThe Henley Business School offers its undergraduate, postgraduate and PhD programmes from its Whiteknights campus. There are 30 different programmes for undergraduates (BA/BSc) and postgraduates (MA/MSc); subject areas offered include finance and investment, management, marketing, and real estate and planning. It also offers PhD and DBA programmes in all these areas.\n\nSpread across both sites are 24 specialist research and knowledge centres.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.henley.ac.uk/research/research-centres|title=Henley Business School, Research Centres|accessdate=15 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nHenley has 150 faculty members that come from 18 countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.henley.ac.uk/about-us/about-henley-business-school/|title=Henley Business School, About us|accessdate=15 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Reputation and Awards==\nHenley Business School is one of the largest providers of business education in the world with over 68,000 alumni members in 154 countries, and the third largest provider of MBA education.<ref>{{cite web|title=Henley Business School - School and Program Profile|url=http://www.topmba.com/node/23|publisher=Top MBA|accessdate=18 October 2012}}</ref> The Henley MBA programme has been ranked at 34 globally,<ref>{{cite web|title=Economist 2014 Full-Time MBA Global Ranking|url=http://www.economist.com/whichmba/full-time-mba-ranking?page=3|accessdate=15 December 2017}}</ref> number one regionally<ref>{{cite web|title=Henley Business School MBA Rankings 2014|url=http://www.henley.ac.uk/about-us/mba-rankings/|accessdate=15 December 2017}}</ref> and first worldwide for potential to network and breadth of alumni.<ref>{{cite web|title=Economist 2014 Henley Business School Rankings|url=http://www.economist.com/whichmba/henley-business-school/2014|accessdate=15 December 2017}}</ref> The executive MBA (EMBA) programme has been ranked at 36 worldwide by The Economist, Which MBA? 2014 rankings<ref>{{cite web|title=The Economic, Which MBA? EMBA Rankings 2014|url=http://www.economist.com/whichmba/executive-mba-ranking/2015/henley-business-school|accessdate=15 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe School's Centre for Coaching won a 2019 Global Coaching Award from the [[European Mentoring & Coaching Council]] in January 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pressat.co.uk/releases/2019-emcc-global-coaching-award-winners-d7fc964b042df029d4996bfcf8317c7d/}}</ref>\n\nThe Research Excellence Framework 2014 ranked Henley in the top 10% for internationally excellent and world-leading research.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://results.ref.ac.uk/Results/ByHei/167|title=REF 2014, University of Reading|accessdate=15 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Henley Business School was awarded the National Undergraduate Employability (NUE) Award for [https://www.henley.ac.uk/news/2018/nue-awards \u2018Best University Careers/Employability Service\u2019.]\n\n==Alumni and affiliates==\n{{unreferenced section|date=May 2013}}\nAt any given time, Henley has around 7,000 students and programme members from more than 140 countries (directly or through its affiliates), ranging from the UK and Europe to Asia and Africa, from North and South America to Australasia. As one of the oldest business school in the UK, it has over 68,000 alumni members in 154 countries. Henley Business School has an active alumni network which is delivered through events, resources, a careers service and an online forum, [https://www.henley.ac.uk/news/2018/henley-live-our-new-online-platform Henley Live].\n\nNotable alumni include Cdr. Dr Mike Young, Head of Leadership & Management\u00a0at the Royal Navy; [https://www.linkedin.com/in/jonathan-firth-013a4830/ Jonathan Firth], former Vice President at Virgin Galactic (2004-2018); [https://www.linkedin.com/in/gordon-seabright-1175381b/ Gordon Seabright], Executive Director\u00a0of the  Eden Project; and [https://www.linkedin.com/in/janeholbrook/?originalSubdomain=uk Jane Holbrook], former Chief Executive Officer\u00a0at Wagamama (2017-2019).\n\nHenley has several affiliate campuses abroad and The Henley Flexible Executive is delivered in 9 of these locations worldwide: [https://henley.dk/ Denmark] and Sweden, [https://www.henley.fi/en/ Finland & Estonia], [https://henleybusinessschool.de/ Germany], Hong Kong, Malaysia, [http://www.henleymalta.com.mt/ Malta,] [https://www.henleysa.ac.za/ South Africa], India, Ireland, Dubai, Singapore.\n\nEach local campus and subsidiary could vary in what is offered, with each having some local customisation.  A number of countries have a full local campus, with local teaching staff and local accreditation (the [[Henley Business School South Africa]], for example). A number of others, which Henley lists as countries they serve, have an office without local instructors. Students in those countries must either travel abroad or use the distance learning mode to complete their degrees.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.henley.ac.uk/ Official Website]\n\n{{University of Reading}}\n{{Business schools in the United Kingdom}}\n\n[[Category:Business schools in England]]\n[[Category:Education in Buckinghamshire]]\n[[Category:Henley-on-Thames]]\n[[Category:Higher education colleges in England]]\n[[Category:University of Reading]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2008]]\n[[Category:2008 establishments in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{otheruses|Henley College (disambiguation)}}\n{{Refimprove|date=April 2009}}\n{{Coord|51|33|47|N|0|52|57|W|region:GB_scale:10000|display=title}}\n\n'''[https://www.henley.ac.uk/ Henley Business School] '''is the [[business school]] of the [[University of Reading]]. It was formed by merging the previously independent '''Henley Management College''', formerly the '''Administrative Staff College''', with the existing business school of the University of Reading. As a result of the merger it now occupies two sites: [[Greenlands|Greenlands Campus]], near the town of [[Henley-on-Thames]], the original site of the Henley Management College, and [[Whiteknights Park|Whiteknights Campus]] in [[Reading, Berkshire|Reading]].\n\nIt is among only 73 institutions worldwide to be granted [[triple accreditation]] by the three largest and most influential business school accreditation associations: [[European Quality Improvement System|EQUIS]], [[Association of MBAs|AMBA]] and the [[Association to Advance Collegiate Schools of Business|AACSB]]. It is ranked among the world's top 50 business schools by the Financial Times<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://rankings.ft.com/businessschoolrankings/european-business-school-rankings-2014|title=Financial Times European Business School Rankings 2015|accessdate=15 December 2017}}</ref> and The Economist.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.economist.com/whichmba/full-time-mba-ranking?page=3|title=The Economist Which MBA? Full time MBA ranking|accessdate=15 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe current dean is [https://www.henley.ac.uk/people/person/professor-john-board Professor John Board.]\n\n==History==\n[[Image:Henley Management College.jpg|thumb|Greenlands campus on the banks of the river Thames]]\n\n===1945-1981===\nThe Administrative Staff College was set up in 1945 at [[Henley-on-Thames]] as the civilian equivalent of the Military Staff Colleges. It offered short courses in problems of advanced management. The College was offered the use of [[Greenlands]] by the [[William Smith, 3rd Viscount Hambleden|3rd Viscount Hambledon]] in 1946, and was bought outright from the family in 1952. In its formative years, the College was influenced by the management consultant and writer [[Lyndall Urwick]], the academic [[Hector Hetherington]], the civil servant [[Donald Banks|Sir Donald Banks]] and the businessman [[Geoffrey Heyworth, 1st Baron Heyworth|Sir Geoffrey Heyworth]] (later Lord Heyworth);<ref>Brech, Edward, Andrew Thomson & John F Wilson, ''Lyndall Urwick, Management Pioneer: A Biography'', Oxford University Press, 2010.</ref> its curriculum was designed by its first Principal, [[Noel Frederick Hall|Noel Hall]]. From the beginning, its intention was to bring together executives from [[Her Majesty's Civil Service]], private business and [[Nationalization#United Kingdom|nationalised industries]] to help develop their skills for promotion to senior management.\n\n[[Image:ICMA Thomson Reuters.JPG|thumb|right|The [[ICMA Centre]] Thomson Reuters Trading Rooms]]\n\n===1981-2008===\nIn 1981, the College changed its name from its original title to '''Henley - The Management College'''. This was changed again to the '''Henley Management College''' when it was awarded a [[Royal charter#United Kingdom|Royal charter]] in 1991. By 2002, the College achieved [[triple accreditation]] status from the [[Association to Advance Collegiate Schools of Business]] (AACSB), the [[Association of MBAs]] (AMBA) and the [[European Quality Improvement System]] (EQUIS).<ref>{{cite web|title=Henley Business School rankings and facts|url=http://www.henley.ac.uk/about/hbs-business-school-rankings.aspx|publisher=Henley Business School|accessdate=18 October 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121015003500/http://www.henley.ac.uk/about/hbs-business-school-rankings.aspx|archivedate=15 October 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> The Greenlands campus of the College is located on the banks of the river [[Thames]] near Henley-on-Thames, on a [[country estate]] and former home of the [[WH Smith]] family.\n\n===2008-present===\nIn 2008, the Henley Management College merged with the University of Reading to form the '''[https://www.henley.ac.uk/ Henley Business School]'''. It consists of the [https://www.henley.ac.uk/phd/course/international-business-and-strategy School of International Business and Strategy]; the [https://www.henley.ac.uk/school/leadership-organisations-and-behaviour School of Leadership, Organisations and Behaviour]; the [https://www.henley.ac.uk/school/marketing-and-reputation School of Marketing and Reputation]; the [https://www.henley.ac.uk/school/business-informatics-systems-and-accounting School of Business Informatics, Systems and Accountancy] (which includes the Informatics Research Centre); the [https://www.henley.ac.uk/school/real-estate-and-planning School of Real Estate & Planning]; the [[ICMA Centre]]; and [https://www.henley.ac.uk/executive-education Executive Education Programmes].\n\nWhile the [[Master of Business Administration|MBA]] and corporate learning activities are offered from the Greenlands campus, all [[undergraduate]], [[postgraduate]] and [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] courses are offered from the Whiteknights campus of the University of Reading.\n\nA former country estate of the [[Marquis of Blandford]], the 130 hectare Whiteknights campus holds conservation meadows, a rare tree collection and a large lake. In 2009 the School moved into a new building in Whiteknights, with facilities for lectures, conferences and visitors.\n\n==Academics==\nAt its Greenlands campus, the Henley Business School offers an MBA for executive managers, in addition to corporate and executive education programmes with students from more than 100 countries.<ref>{{cite web|last=Henley Business School|first=Henley Business School|title=Henley Business School Key Facts and Rankings 2015|url=http://www.henley.ac.uk/files/pdf/miscellaneous/Key_facts_Regatta_Expertise__Rankings__Facts__2015.pdf|accessdate=15 December 2017}}</ref> The Henley MBA is designed for experienced, practicing managers, and aims to enhance their leadership skills or prepare for a senior management position; the average age of programme members is 38 years. It is offered in executive (2 years), [[distance learning]] (2,5 years) modes and flexible executive, a programme that allows participants to continue to work full-time and to study The Henley MBA part-time.\n\nThe Henley Business School offers its undergraduate, postgraduate and PhD programmes from its Whiteknights campus. 30 different programmes for undergraduates (BA/BSc) and postgraduates (MA/MSc) are offered in finance and investment, management, marketing, and real estate and planning. It also offers PhD and DBA programmes in all these areas.\n\nSpread across both sites are 24 specialist research and knowledge centres.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.henley.ac.uk/research/research-centres|title=Henley Business School, Research Centres|accessdate=15 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nHenley has 150 faculty members that come from 18 countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.henley.ac.uk/about-us/about-henley-business-school/|title=Henley Business School, About us|accessdate=15 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Reputation and Awards==\nHenley Business School is one of the largest providers of business education in the world with over 68,000 alumni members in 154 countries, and the third largest provider of MBA education.<ref>{{cite web|title=Henley Business School - School and Program Profile|url=http://www.topmba.com/node/23|publisher=Top MBA|accessdate=18 October 2012}}</ref> The Henley MBA programme has been ranked at 34 globally,<ref>{{cite web|title=Economist 2014 Full-Time MBA Global Ranking|url=http://www.economist.com/whichmba/full-time-mba-ranking?page=3|accessdate=15 December 2017}}</ref> number one regionally<ref>{{cite web|title=Henley Business School MBA Rankings 2014|url=http://www.henley.ac.uk/about-us/mba-rankings/|accessdate=15 December 2017}}</ref> and first worldwide for potential to network and breadth of alumni.<ref>{{cite web|title=Economist 2014 Henley Business School Rankings|url=http://www.economist.com/whichmba/henley-business-school/2014|accessdate=15 December 2017}}</ref> The executive MBA (EMBA) programme has been ranked at 36 worldwide by The Economist, Which MBA? 2014 rankings<ref>{{cite web|title=The Economic, Which MBA? EMBA Rankings 2014|url=http://www.economist.com/whichmba/executive-mba-ranking/2015/henley-business-school|accessdate=15 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe School's Centre for Coaching won a 2019 Global Coaching Award from the [[European Mentoring & Coaching Council]] in January 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pressat.co.uk/releases/2019-emcc-global-coaching-award-winners-d7fc964b042df029d4996bfcf8317c7d/}}</ref>\n\nThe Research Excellence Framework 2014 ranked Henley in the top 10% for internationally excellent and world-leading research.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://results.ref.ac.uk/Results/ByHei/167|title=REF 2014, University of Reading|accessdate=15 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Alumni and affiliates==\n{{unreferenced section|date=May 2013}}\nAt any given time, Henley has around 7,000 students and programme members from more than 140 countries (directly or through its affiliates), ranging from the UK and Europe to Asia and Africa, from North and South America to Australasia. As one of the oldest business school in the UK, it has over 68,000 alumni members in 154 countries.\n\nNotable alumni include Cdr. Dr Mike Young, Head of Leadership & Management\u00a0at the Royal Navy; [https://www.linkedin.com/in/jonathan-firth-013a4830/ Jonathan Firth], former Vice President at Virgin Galactic (2004-2018); [https://www.linkedin.com/in/gordon-seabright-1175381b/ Gordon Seabright], Executive Director\u00a0of the  Eden Project; and [https://www.linkedin.com/in/janeholbrook/?originalSubdomain=uk Jane Holbrook], former Chief Executive Officer\u00a0at Wagamama (2017-2019).\n\nHenley has several affiliate campuses abroad and The Henley Flexible Executive is delivered in 9 of these locations worldwide: [https://henley.dk/ Denmark] and Sweden, [https://www.henley.fi/en/ Finland & Estonia], [https://henleybusinessschool.de/ Germany], Hong Kong, Malaysia, [http://www.henleymalta.com.mt/ Malta,] [https://www.henleysa.ac.za/ South Africa], India, Ireland, Dubai, Singapore.\n\nEach local campus and subsidiary could vary in what is offered, with each having some local customisation.  A number of countries have a full local campus, with local teaching staff and local accreditation (the [[Henley Business School South Africa]], for example). A number of others, which Henley lists as countries they serve, have an office without local instructors. Students in those countries must either travel abroad or use the distance learning mode to complete their degrees.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.henley.ac.uk/ Official Website]\n\n{{University of Reading}}\n{{Business schools in the United Kingdom}}\n\n[[Category:Business schools in England]]\n[[Category:Education in Buckinghamshire]]\n[[Category:Henley-on-Thames]]\n[[Category:Higher education colleges in England]]\n[[Category:University of Reading]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2008]]\n[[Category:2008 establishments in England]]\n", "name_user": "SarahJGosling", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added links to alumni services", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henley_Business_School"}
{"title_page": "Solly Msimanga", "text_new": "{{short description|Leader of the Opposition in the Gauteng Provincial Legislature}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name               = Solly Msimanga\n|order              = \n|honorific-prefix   = [[The Honourable]]\n|honorific-suffix   = [[Gauteng Provincial Legislature|MPL]]\n|native_name        = \n|native_name_lang   = \n|image              = Mayor Solly Msimanga with former US Mayor Anthony Williams (2).jpg\n|image_size         = 250px\n|alt                = \n|smallimage         = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n|caption            = Msimanga in 2017\n|office             = [[Gauteng Provincial Legislature|Leader of the Opposition in the Gauteng Provincial Legislature]]\n|premier            = [[David Makhura]]\n|status             = \n|term_start         = 22 May 2019\n|term_end           = \n|predecessor        = [[John Moodey]]\n|successor          = \n|succeeding         = \n|office1            = [[Mayor of Tshwane]]\n|term_start1        = 19 August 2016\n|term_end1          = 11 February 2019\n|predecessor1       = Kgosientso Ramokgopa\n|successor1         = [[Stevens Mokgalapa]]\n|office2            = [[Gauteng Provincial Legislature|Member of the Gauteng Provincial Legislature]]\n|term_start2        = 12 February 2019\n|term_end2          = \n|predecessor2       = \n|successor2         = \n|term_start3        = 21 May 2014\n|term_end3          = 19 August 2016\n|office4            = [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Provincial Chairperson of the Gauteng Democratic Alliance]]\n|term_start4        = 22 November 2014\n|term_end4          = 18 November 2017\n|predecessor4       = [[Michael Moriarty (politician)|Michael Moriarty]]\n|successor4         = [[Michael Moriarty (politician)|Michael Moriarty]]\n|party              = [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]] (2006\u2013present)\n|birthname          = Solly Tshepiso Msimanga\n|birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1980|07|16}}\n|birth_place        = [[Atteridgeville]], [[Pretoria]], [[South Africa]]\n|death_date         = <!-- {{Death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n|death_place        = \n|otherparty         =  <!--For additional political affiliations-->\n|spouse             = Monde Msimanga (m. 2006)\n|partner            =  <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n|relations          = \n|children           = Amogelong Msimanga <br/> Aobokwe Msimanga\n|residence          = \n|alma_mater         = [[University of Pretoria]] (BCompt)\n|imagesize          = \n|restingplace       = \n|restingplacecoordinates = \n }}\n\n'''Solly Tshepiso Msimanga''' (born 16 July 1980) is a [[South Africa]]n politician who has been serving as the Leader of the Opposition in the [[Gauteng Provincial Legislature]] since May 2019. He took office as a [[Gauteng Provincial Legislature|Member of the Gauteng Provincial Legislature]] in February 2019. He previously held the position from 2014 to 2016. Msimanga served as the Executive Mayor of the [[City of Tshwane Metropolitan Municipality]] from 2016 to 2019 and was DA Provincial Chairperson from 2014 to 2017. He was the Democratic Alliance's Gauteng Premier candidate for the 2019 elections.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sabcnews.com/sabcnews/maimane-announces-msimanga-as-gauteng-premier-candidate/|title= Maimane announces Msimanga as Gauteng Premier candidate|newspaper= SABC News|access-date= 24 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Solly Tshepiso Msimanga|url=http://da-gpl.co.za/team-page/solly-tshepiso-msimanga/|website=Democratic Alliance|accessdate=20 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Poplak|first1=Richard|title=How the DA\u2019s Solly Msimanga hopes to turn Battleground Tshwane into a better version of Sweden|url=http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2016-07-19-trainspotter-how-the-das-solly-msimanga-hopes-to-turn-battleground-tshwane-into-a-better-version-of-sweden/|accessdate=20 August 2016|publisher=Daily Maverick|date=19 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Early life, education and family==\n\nSolly Tshepiso Msimanga was born in [[Atteridgeville]], a township in the west of Pretoria. He attended Isaac Mor\u00e9 Primary School, Patogeng Higher Primary and Saulridge High School. He obtained a national diploma in marketing management and a BCompt from the [[University of Pretoria]]. He married Monde Msimanga in 2006. They have two children named Amogelong and Aobokwe. Solly and his wife work together on the charity organisation named \u201cMake Somebody\u2019s Christmas a Merry One\u201d. The project donates groceries to disadvantaged families.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thesouthafrican.com/who-is-solly-msimanga-five-facts-about-the-das-tshwane-mayor/ |title=Who is Solly Msimanga? Five facts about the DA\u2019s Tshwane mayor|newspaper= The South African|access-date= 24 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nHe worked with Project Literacy and was enlisted at the Liberian embassy at one stage. Later on, he was employed by the United States embassy. He has been a national director for Legal Education And Development and has held multiple senior management positions in the private sector.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://citizen.co.za/news/features-news/1329744/things-you-did-not-know-about-solly-msimanga/|title= Things you did not know about Solly Msimanga|newspaper=TheCitizen|access-date= 24 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/here-are-tshwanes-mayoral-hopefuls-2049664|title= Here are Tshwane\u2019s mayoral hopefuls|newspaper= IOL|access-date=24 March 2019}}</ref>\n===Entry into politics===\n[[File:Solly Msimanga and Mmusi Maimane, 2012.jpg|x200px|left|thumb|Msimanga delivering a speech, while Mmusi Maimane watches in the background]]\nMsimanga first joined the DA in 2006. After having attended a DA event, he wrote to the party criticising its campaign approach and was soon offered a staff position by the party's CEO [[Ryan Coetzee]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bdlive.co.za/national/politics/2016/08/15/das-solly-msimanga-eager-to-clean-up-tainted-tshwane|title=DA\u2019s Solly Msimanga eager to clean up tainted Tshwane|newspaper=BDlive|date=15 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://mg.co.za/article/2016-08-26-00-i-lived-in-a-shack-says-optimistic-newly-elected-tshwane-mayor-solly-msimanga|title=\"I lived in a shack\" says optimistic newly-elected Tshwane mayor Solly Msimanga|newspaper=M&G|date=26 August 2016}}</ref> \n\nHe eventually began rising through the ranks of the party. In May 2011, he was elected to the Tshwane City Council, and in the same year, he became the leader of the DA's Gauteng North region.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.enca.com/south-africa/who-is-solly-msimanga|title= Who is Solly Msimanga?|newspaper= eNCA|access-date= 24 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=New DA leaders named in Gauteng |url=https://www.iol.co.za/the-star/new-da-leaders-named-in-gauteng-1198118 |accessdate=2 January 2020 |newspaper=The Star |date=14 December 2011}}</ref> \n\nIn May 2014, Msimanga was elected a Member of the [[Gauteng Provincial Legislature]]. He was appointed the party's provincial spokesperson for sports and served on the Education and Economic Development Portfolio Committees in the legislature.\n\n===DA leadership elections===\nIn November 2014, he succeeded [[Michael Moriarty (politician)|Michael Moriarty]] as DA Provincial Chairperson, after Moriarty had stood down.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.enca.com/south-africa/moodey-re-elected-lead-da-gauteng|title= Moodey re-elected to lead DA Gauteng|newspaper=eNCA|date=22 November 2014|access-date= 25 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2017, [[Michael Moriarty (politician)|Michael Moriarty]] succeeded Msimanga as DA Provincial Chairperson at the party's Provincial Congress, after Msimanga took the decision to not run for re-election.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sabcnews.com/sabcnews/da-re-elect-moodey-as-gauteng-leader/|title= DA re-elects Moodey as Gauteng leader|newspaper= SABC News|date=18 November 2017|access-date= 25 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/john-moodey-re-elected-da-gauteng-leader-12068326|title= John Moodey re-elected DA Gauteng leader|newspaper=IOL|date= 19 November 2017|access-date= 25 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2014-11-21-da-gauteng-leader-post-to-be-contested-at-provincial-conference/ |title=DA Gauteng leader post to be contested at provincial conference|newspaper=TimesLIVE|date= 21 November 2014|access-date=25 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, Msimanga declared himself a candidate for the position of Federal Chairperson of the Democratic Alliance ahead of the party's Federal Congress. On 8 April 2018, he lost to incumbent [[Athol Trollip]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.politicsweb.co.za/news-and-analysis/solly-msimanga-to-challenge-athol-trollip-for-da-f| title=Solly Msimanga to challenge Athol Trollip for DA federal chairperson position|newspaper=Politicsweb|access-date=24 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/athol-trollip-re-elected-as-da-federal-chairperson-20180408 |title=Athol Trollip re-elected as DA federal chairperson|newspaper=News24|access-date= 24 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Mayoral career===\n[[File:Mayor Solly Msimanga with former US Mayor Anthony Williams.jpg|thumb|right|x170px|Msimanga met with former U.S. Mayor [[Anthony A. Williams]] on 13 February 2019. Msimanga handed Williams a gift to celebrate their meeting which focused on urban renewal]]\nIn September 2015, Msimanga was announced as the DA's mayoral candidate for the [[City of Tshwane]] in the [[2016 South African municipal elections|2016 municipal elections]]. He defeated [[Brandon Topham]] and Bronwyn Engelbrecht for the nomination.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ewn.co.za/2015/09/05/DA-chooses-Tshwanes-Solly-Msimanga-as-2016-mayoral-candidate|title=DA chooses Tshwane\u2019s Solly Msimanga as 2016 mayoral candidate|publisher=Eyewitness News|date=5 September 2015}}</ref> The DA emerged as the largest party after the election, but without a majority. By forming a coalition with several smaller parties, and with the support of the [[Economic Freedom Fighters]], Msimanga was elected unopposed as the Executive Mayor of Tshwane. He was the first DA member to hold the post.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/elections/news/msimanga-elected-tshwane-mayor-20160819|title= Msimanga elected Tshwane mayor|newspaper=News24|date=19 August 2016|access-date =24 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Moatshe|first= Rapula|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/msimanga-elected-tshwane-mayor-2059057|title= Msimanga elected Tshwane mayor|newspaper=IOL|date= 19 August 2016|access-date=24 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nWhen he was elected Mayor, he stated his intention to outlaw blue-lights brigades in the City \u2014 for everyone except the President. \u201cThe only VIPs in the City will be the residents of the City,\u201d he said.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://businesstech.co.za/news/government/133910/no-more-blue-lights-for-vips-in-tshwane-da/ |title=No more blue lights for VIPs in Tshwane: DA|newspaper= BusinessTech|access-date= 24 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, it was revealed that Msimanga's chief of staff Marietha Aucamp had been dishonest about her qualifications.<ref>{{cite news|last=Dlamini|first=Penwell|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2018-05-16-tshwane-places-chief-of-staff-on-special-leave-amid-qualification-allegations/|title= Tshwane places chief of staff on special leave amid qualification allegations|newspaper=TimesLIVE|date= 16 May 2018|access-date= 25 March 2019}}</ref> She was placed on special leave on 16 May 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/gauteng/tshwane-places-chief-of-staff-on-special-leave-amid-qualifications-scandal-15008517|title= Tshwane places chief of staff on special leave amid qualifications scandal|newspaper=IOL|date= 16 May 2018|access-date= 25 March 2019}}</ref> She subsequently resigned on 17 May 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://ewn.co.za/2018/05/17/msimanga-s-chief-of-staff-marietha-aucamp-resigns|title= Msimanga's chief of staff Marietha Aucamp resigns|newspaper= EWN|date= 17 May 2018|access-date= 25 March 2019}}</ref> In June 2018, an inquiry found that she had misrepresented her qualifications. It also found that her appointment was unlawful.<ref>{{cite news|last=Khoza|first= Amanda|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/aucamps-appointment-as-chief-of-staff-was-irregular-city-of-tshwane-20180628|title= Aucamp's appointment as chief of staff was irregular - City of Tshwane|newspaper= News24|date= 28 June 2018|access-date=25 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.iol.co.za/pretoria-news/watch-report-reveals-marietha-aucamp-misrepresented-her-qualifications-15729592|title= WATCH: Report reveals Marietha Aucamp misrepresented her qualifications|newspaper= IOL|date=28 June 2018|access-date= 25 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2018, both the [[Economic Freedom Fighters]] (EFF) and [[African National Congress]] (ANC) had tabled motions of no confidence to remove Msimanga as Mayor.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/eff-tables-motion-of-no-confidence-in-tshwane-mayor-solly-msimanga-20180823|title= EFF tables motion of no confidence in Tshwane Mayor Solly Msimanga|newspaper=News24|access-date= 23 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.iol.co.za/pretoria-news/anc-want-motion-of-no-confidence-secret-ballot-against-solly-msimanga-16704176|title= ANC want motion of no confidence secret ballot against Solly Msimanga|newspaper=IOL|access-date= 23 February 2019}}</ref> The ANC Tshwane Regional Chairperson Kgosi Maepa had said in an interview that his party's caucus would support the EFF's motion, if needed. He also said that the party had lobbied other political parties to support their motion. On 30 August 2018, Tshwane Council Speaker [[Katlego Mathebe]] declined to proceed with the EFF's motion of no confidence because it did not comply with the council's rules. The EFF subsequently staged a walkout out of the council chamber.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2018-08-30-eff-goes-to-court-after-no-confidence-motion-in-solly-msimanga-is-rejected/ |title=EFF goes to court after no-confidence motion in Solly Msimanga is rejected|newspaper=TimesLive| access-date= 23 February 2019}}</ref> The party's caucus leader said that it would not support the ANC's motion and that it would challenge the Speaker's decision in court. Due to the lack of support, the ANC withdrew its motion.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://ewn.co.za/2018/08/30/anc-withdraws-motion-of-no-confidence-in-msimanga|title= ANC withdraws motion of no confidence in Msimanga|newspaper=EWN|access-date= 23 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 September 2018, he survived another motion of no confidence tabled by the ANC. The EFF abstained from voting. Ninety-five councillors voted against the motion, while seventy-seven voted for it. Twenty-one councillors abstained.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/tshwane-mayor-solly-msimanga-survives-motion-of-no-confidence-17248280|title= Tshwane Mayor Solly Msimanga survives motion of no confidence|newspaper=IOL|access-date= 23 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nMsimanga's last months as Mayor were overshadowed by the irregular awarding of a multi-billion-rand tender contract to GladAfrica by embattled City Manager Moeketsi Mosola.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.iol.co.za/pretoria-news/gladafrica-solly-msimanga-in-tight-spot-18188960|title= GladAfrica: Solly Msimanga in tight spot|newspaper= IOL|access-date= 26 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/exclusive-gladafrica-scandal-mosola-quietly-concedes-tender-was-irregular-says-official-20190125|title= EXCLUSIVE: GladAfrica scandal - Mosola quietly concedes tender was irregular, says official|newspaper= News24|access-date= 26 March 2019}}</ref> Msimanga tried to suspend Mosola<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/politics/2018-08-22-tshwanes-city-manager-given-notice-to-suspend-over-gladafrica-tender/ |title=Tshwane\u2019s city manager given notice to suspend over GladAfrica tender|newspaper= BusinessLIVE|access-date= 26 March 2019}}</ref>, and the DA caucus of the Tshwane City Council attempted multiple times to remove Mosola from the position.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/tshwane-council-issues-notice-of-intention-to-suspend-city-manager-20180822|title= Tshwane Council issues notice of intention to suspend city manager|newspaper= News24|access-date= 26 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.enca.com/news/da-motion-suspend-mosola-fails|title= DA motion to suspend Mosola fails|newspaper=eNCA|access-date= 26 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.sowetanlive.co.za/news/south-africa/2018-11-30-second-bid-to-remove-tshwane-city-manager-moeketsi-mosola-fails/|title= Second bid to remove Tshwane City manager Moeketsi Mosola fails|newspaper= SowetanLIVE}}</ref> Mosola announced in July 2019 that he would step down as the City Manager of Tshwane.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/national/2019-07-26-moeketsi-mosola-reaches-separation-agreement-with-city-of-tshwane/|title= Moeketsi Mosola reaches separation agreement with City of Tshwane|access-date=26 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 January 2019, Msimanga announced that he was stepping down as Mayor of Tshwane to focus on his Gauteng premiership campaign. He also said that his resignation would be finalised in the first two weeks of February.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/solly-msimanga-to-step-down-as-tshwane-mayor-20190118|title= Solly Msimanga to step down as Tshwane mayor|newspaper= News24|date=18 January 2019|access-date= 24 March 2019}}</ref> He later announced on 31 January 2019 that he would effectively resign on 11 February 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/politics/2074552/msimanga-resigns-as-mayor-but-tshwane-anc-wants-him-out-now/|title= Msimanga resigns as mayor but Tshwane ANC wants him out now|newspaper= TheCitizen|access-date= 24 March 2019}}</ref> He was succeeded by [[Stevens Mokgalapa]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/politics/2081597/das-stevens-mokgalapa-is-tshwanes-new-mayor/ |title=DA\u2019s Stevens Mokgalapa is Tshwane\u2019s new mayor|newspaper=TheCitizen|access-date=24 March 2019}}</ref> Msimanga was subsequently sworn in as a Member of the Gauteng Provincial Legislature.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://mg.co.za/article/2019-02-12-city-of-tshwane-lands-itself-a-new-da-mayor|title= City of Tshwane lands itself a new DA mayor|access-date= 24 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Gauteng premiership campaign===\nOn 19 August 2018, Msimanga was announced as the party's Gauteng Premier candidate for the upcoming 2019 general elections.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2018-08-19-solly-msimanga-named-as-das-candidate-for-gauteng-premier/|title= Solly Msimanga named as DA\u2019s candidate for Gauteng premier|newspaper= TimesLIVE|date= 19 August 2018|access-date=25 March 2019}}</ref> He defeated many prominent candidates for the nomination, such as Member of the Gauteng Provincial Legislature [[Makashule Gana]], Member of Parliament [[Ghaleb Cachalia]], and DA Party Spokesperson Refiloe Nt\u2019sheke.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.enca.com/news/da-picks-solly-msimanga-gauteng-premier|title= DA picks Solly Msimanga for Gauteng premier|newspaper= eNCA|date= 19 August 2018|access-date= 25 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 May 2019, the African National Congress narrowly retained their majority in the [[Gauteng Provincial Legislature]] with a total of 50.19% of the vote. The Democratic Alliance remained the official opposition, but lost three seats, giving them a total of twenty seats in the provincial legislature.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://mg.co.za/article/2019-05-11-analysis-anc-hangs-onto-gauteng-but-its-a-whole-new-political-world|title= ANC hangs onto Gauteng, but it\u2019s a whole new political world|access-date= 17 May 2019}}</ref> Msimanga was elected DA caucus leader on 17 May 2019 and officially assumed the post of Leader of the Opposition on 22 May 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.enca.com/news/livestream-da-announced-gauteng-provincial-leadership|title= LIVESTREAM: DA announces Gauteng legislature leadership|access-date= 17 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [https://www.pa.org.za/person/solly-tshepiso-msimanga/ People's Assembly profile]\n* [https://twitter.com/SollyMsimanga Profile] on [[Twitter]]\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Moodey]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Leader of the Opposition in the [[Gauteng Provincial Legislature]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-bef|before=Kgosientso Ramokgopa}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Mayor of Tshwane]]|years=2016\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Stevens Mokgalapa]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Michael Moriarty (politician)|Michael Moriarty]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Provincial Chairperson of the Gauteng Democratic Alliance]]|years=2014\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Michael Moriarty (politician)|Michael Moriarty]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Mayors of Pretoria and Tshwane}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Msimanga, Solly}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Democratic Alliance (South Africa) politicians]]\n[[Category:University of Pretoria alumni]]\n[[Category:Members of the Gauteng Provincial Legislature]]\n[[Category: Mayors of Pretoria]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Leader of the Opposition in the Gauteng Provincial Legislature}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name               = Solly Msimanga\n|order              = \n|honorific-prefix   = [[The Honourable]]\n|honorific-suffix   = [[Gauteng Provincial Legislature|MPL]]\n|native_name        = \n|native_name_lang   = \n|image              = Mayor Solly Msimanga with former US Mayor Anthony Williams (2).jpg\n|image_size         = 250px\n|alt                = \n|smallimage         = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n|caption            = Msimanga in 2017\n|office             = [[Gauteng Provincial Legislature|Leader of the Opposition in the Gauteng Provincial Legislature]]\n|premier            = [[David Makhura]]\n|status             = \n|term_start         = 22 May 2019\n|term_end           = \n|predecessor        = [[John Moodey]]\n|successor          = \n|succeeding         = \n|office1            = [[Mayor of Tshwane]]\n|term_start1        = 19 August 2016\n|term_end1          = 11 February 2019\n|predecessor1       = Kgosientso Ramokgopa\n|successor1         = [[Stevens Mokgalapa]]\n|office2            = [[Gauteng Provincial Legislature|Member of the Gauteng Provincial Legislature]]\n|term_start2        = 12 February 2019\n|term_end2          = \n|predecessor2       = \n|successor2         = \n|term_start3        = 21 May 2014\n|term_end3          = 19 August 2016\n|office4            = [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Provincial Chairperson of the Gauteng Democratic Alliance]]\n|term_start4        = 22 November 2014\n|term_end4          = 18 November 2017\n|predecessor4       = [[Michael Moriarty (politician)|Michael Moriarty]]\n|successor4         = [[Michael Moriarty (politician)|Michael Moriarty]]\n|party              = [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]] (2006\u2013present)\n|birthname          = Solly Tshepiso Msimanga\n|birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1980|07|16}}\n|birth_place        = [[Atteridgeville]], [[Pretoria]], [[South Africa]]\n|death_date         = <!-- {{Death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n|death_place        = \n|otherparty         =  <!--For additional political affiliations-->\n|spouse             = Monde Msimanga (m. 2006)\n|partner            =  <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n|relations          = \n|children           = Amogelong Msimanga <br/> Aobokwe Msimanga\n|residence          = \n|alma_mater         = [[University of Pretoria]] (BCompt)\n|imagesize          = \n|restingplace       = \n|restingplacecoordinates = \n }}\n\n'''Solly Tshepiso Msimanga''' (born 16 July 1980) is a [[South Africa]]n politician who has been serving as the Leader of the Opposition in the [[Gauteng Provincial Legislature]] since May 2019. He took office as a [[Gauteng Provincial Legislature|Member of the Gauteng Provincial Legislature]] in February 2019. He previously held the position from 2014 to 2016. Msimanga served as the Executive Mayor of the [[City of Tshwane Metropolitan Municipality]] from 2016 to 2019 and was DA Provincial Chairperson from 2014 to 2017. He was the Democratic Alliance's Gauteng Premier candidate for the 2019 elections.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sabcnews.com/sabcnews/maimane-announces-msimanga-as-gauteng-premier-candidate/|title= Maimane announces Msimanga as Gauteng Premier candidate|newspaper= SABC News|access-date= 24 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Solly Tshepiso Msimanga|url=http://da-gpl.co.za/team-page/solly-tshepiso-msimanga/|website=Democratic Alliance|accessdate=20 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Poplak|first1=Richard|title=How the DA\u2019s Solly Msimanga hopes to turn Battleground Tshwane into a better version of Sweden|url=http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2016-07-19-trainspotter-how-the-das-solly-msimanga-hopes-to-turn-battleground-tshwane-into-a-better-version-of-sweden/|accessdate=20 August 2016|publisher=Daily Maverick|date=19 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Early life, education and family==\n\nSolly Tshepiso Msimanga was born in [[Atteridgeville]], a township in the west of Pretoria. He attended Isaac Mor\u00e9 Primary School, Patogeng Higher Primary and Saulridge High School. He obtained a national diploma in marketing management and a BCompt from the [[University of Pretoria]]. He married Monde Msimanga in 2006. They have two children named Amogelong and Aobokwe. Solly and his wife work together on the charity organisation named \u201cMake Somebody\u2019s Christmas a Merry One\u201d. The project donates groceries to disadvantaged families.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thesouthafrican.com/who-is-solly-msimanga-five-facts-about-the-das-tshwane-mayor/ |title=Who is Solly Msimanga? Five facts about the DA\u2019s Tshwane mayor|newspaper= The South African|access-date= 24 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nHe worked with Project Literacy and was enlisted at the Liberian embassy at one stage. Later on, he was employed by the United States embassy. He has been a national director for Legal Education And Development and has held multiple senior management positions in the private sector.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://citizen.co.za/news/features-news/1329744/things-you-did-not-know-about-solly-msimanga/|title= Things you did not know about Solly Msimanga|newspaper=TheCitizen|access-date= 24 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/here-are-tshwanes-mayoral-hopefuls-2049664|title= Here are Tshwane\u2019s mayoral hopefuls|newspaper= IOL|access-date=24 March 2019}}</ref>\n===Entry into politics===\n[[File:Solly Msimanga and Mmusi Maimane, 2012.jpg|x200px|left|thumb|Msimanga delivers a speech, while Mmusi Maimane watches in the background]]\nMsimanga first joined the DA in 2006. After having attended a DA event, he wrote to the party criticising its campaign approach and was soon offered a staff position by the party's CEO [[Ryan Coetzee]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bdlive.co.za/national/politics/2016/08/15/das-solly-msimanga-eager-to-clean-up-tainted-tshwane|title=DA\u2019s Solly Msimanga eager to clean up tainted Tshwane|newspaper=BDlive|date=15 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://mg.co.za/article/2016-08-26-00-i-lived-in-a-shack-says-optimistic-newly-elected-tshwane-mayor-solly-msimanga|title=\"I lived in a shack\" says optimistic newly-elected Tshwane mayor Solly Msimanga|newspaper=M&G|date=26 August 2016}}</ref> \n\nHe eventually began rising through the ranks of the party. In May 2011, he was elected to the Tshwane City Council, and in the same year, he became the leader of the DA's Gauteng North region.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.enca.com/south-africa/who-is-solly-msimanga|title= Who is Solly Msimanga?|newspaper= eNCA|access-date= 24 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=New DA leaders named in Gauteng |url=https://www.iol.co.za/the-star/new-da-leaders-named-in-gauteng-1198118 |accessdate=2 January 2020 |newspaper=The Star |date=14 December 2011}}</ref> \n\nIn May 2014, Msimanga was elected a Member of the [[Gauteng Provincial Legislature]]. He was appointed the party's provincial spokesperson for sports and served on the Education and Economic Development Portfolio Committees in the legislature.\n\n===DA leadership elections===\nIn November 2014, he succeeded [[Michael Moriarty (politician)|Michael Moriarty]] as DA Provincial Chairperson, after Moriarty had stood down.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.enca.com/south-africa/moodey-re-elected-lead-da-gauteng|title= Moodey re-elected to lead DA Gauteng|newspaper=eNCA|date=22 November 2014|access-date= 25 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2017, [[Michael Moriarty (politician)|Michael Moriarty]] succeeded Msimanga as DA Provincial Chairperson at the party's Provincial Congress, after Msimanga took the decision to not run for re-election.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sabcnews.com/sabcnews/da-re-elect-moodey-as-gauteng-leader/|title= DA re-elects Moodey as Gauteng leader|newspaper= SABC News|date=18 November 2017|access-date= 25 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/john-moodey-re-elected-da-gauteng-leader-12068326|title= John Moodey re-elected DA Gauteng leader|newspaper=IOL|date= 19 November 2017|access-date= 25 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2014-11-21-da-gauteng-leader-post-to-be-contested-at-provincial-conference/ |title=DA Gauteng leader post to be contested at provincial conference|newspaper=TimesLIVE|date= 21 November 2014|access-date=25 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, Msimanga declared himself a candidate for the position of Federal Chairperson of the Democratic Alliance ahead of the party's Federal Congress. On 8 April 2018, he lost to incumbent [[Athol Trollip]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.politicsweb.co.za/news-and-analysis/solly-msimanga-to-challenge-athol-trollip-for-da-f| title=Solly Msimanga to challenge Athol Trollip for DA federal chairperson position|newspaper=Politicsweb|access-date=24 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/athol-trollip-re-elected-as-da-federal-chairperson-20180408 |title=Athol Trollip re-elected as DA federal chairperson|newspaper=News24|access-date= 24 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Mayoral career===\n[[File:Mayor Solly Msimanga with former US Mayor Anthony Williams.jpg|thumb|right|x170px|Msimanga met with former U.S. Mayor [[Anthony A. Williams]] on 13 February 2019. Msimanga handed Williams a gift to celebrate their meeting which focused on urban renewal]]\nIn September 2015, Msimanga was announced as the DA's mayoral candidate for the [[City of Tshwane]] in the [[2016 South African municipal elections|2016 municipal elections]]. He defeated [[Brandon Topham]] and Bronwyn Engelbrecht for the nomination.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ewn.co.za/2015/09/05/DA-chooses-Tshwanes-Solly-Msimanga-as-2016-mayoral-candidate|title=DA chooses Tshwane\u2019s Solly Msimanga as 2016 mayoral candidate|publisher=Eyewitness News|date=5 September 2015}}</ref> The DA emerged as the largest party after the election, but without a majority. By forming a coalition with several smaller parties, and with the support of the [[Economic Freedom Fighters]], Msimanga was elected unopposed as the Executive Mayor of Tshwane. He was the first DA member to hold the post.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/elections/news/msimanga-elected-tshwane-mayor-20160819|title= Msimanga elected Tshwane mayor|newspaper=News24|date=19 August 2016|access-date =24 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Moatshe|first= Rapula|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/msimanga-elected-tshwane-mayor-2059057|title= Msimanga elected Tshwane mayor|newspaper=IOL|date= 19 August 2016|access-date=24 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nWhen he was elected Mayor, he stated his intention to outlaw blue-lights brigades in the City \u2014 for everyone except the President. \u201cThe only VIPs in the City will be the residents of the City,\u201d he said.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://businesstech.co.za/news/government/133910/no-more-blue-lights-for-vips-in-tshwane-da/ |title=No more blue lights for VIPs in Tshwane: DA|newspaper= BusinessTech|access-date= 24 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, it was revealed that Msimanga's chief of staff Marietha Aucamp had been dishonest about her qualifications.<ref>{{cite news|last=Dlamini|first=Penwell|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2018-05-16-tshwane-places-chief-of-staff-on-special-leave-amid-qualification-allegations/|title= Tshwane places chief of staff on special leave amid qualification allegations|newspaper=TimesLIVE|date= 16 May 2018|access-date= 25 March 2019}}</ref> She was placed on special leave on 16 May 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/gauteng/tshwane-places-chief-of-staff-on-special-leave-amid-qualifications-scandal-15008517|title= Tshwane places chief of staff on special leave amid qualifications scandal|newspaper=IOL|date= 16 May 2018|access-date= 25 March 2019}}</ref> She subsequently resigned on 17 May 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://ewn.co.za/2018/05/17/msimanga-s-chief-of-staff-marietha-aucamp-resigns|title= Msimanga's chief of staff Marietha Aucamp resigns|newspaper= EWN|date= 17 May 2018|access-date= 25 March 2019}}</ref> In June 2018, an inquiry found that she had misrepresented her qualifications. It also found that her appointment was unlawful.<ref>{{cite news|last=Khoza|first= Amanda|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/aucamps-appointment-as-chief-of-staff-was-irregular-city-of-tshwane-20180628|title= Aucamp's appointment as chief of staff was irregular - City of Tshwane|newspaper= News24|date= 28 June 2018|access-date=25 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.iol.co.za/pretoria-news/watch-report-reveals-marietha-aucamp-misrepresented-her-qualifications-15729592|title= WATCH: Report reveals Marietha Aucamp misrepresented her qualifications|newspaper= IOL|date=28 June 2018|access-date= 25 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2018, both the [[Economic Freedom Fighters]] (EFF) and [[African National Congress]] (ANC) had tabled motions of no confidence to remove Msimanga as Mayor.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/eff-tables-motion-of-no-confidence-in-tshwane-mayor-solly-msimanga-20180823|title= EFF tables motion of no confidence in Tshwane Mayor Solly Msimanga|newspaper=News24|access-date= 23 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.iol.co.za/pretoria-news/anc-want-motion-of-no-confidence-secret-ballot-against-solly-msimanga-16704176|title= ANC want motion of no confidence secret ballot against Solly Msimanga|newspaper=IOL|access-date= 23 February 2019}}</ref> The ANC Tshwane Regional Chairperson Kgosi Maepa had said in an interview that his party's caucus would support the EFF's motion, if needed. He also said that the party had lobbied other political parties to support their motion. On 30 August 2018, Tshwane Council Speaker [[Katlego Mathebe]] declined to proceed with the EFF's motion of no confidence because it did not comply with the council's rules. The EFF subsequently staged a walkout out of the council chamber.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2018-08-30-eff-goes-to-court-after-no-confidence-motion-in-solly-msimanga-is-rejected/ |title=EFF goes to court after no-confidence motion in Solly Msimanga is rejected|newspaper=TimesLive| access-date= 23 February 2019}}</ref> The party's caucus leader said that it would not support the ANC's motion and that it would challenge the Speaker's decision in court. Due to the lack of support, the ANC withdrew its motion.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://ewn.co.za/2018/08/30/anc-withdraws-motion-of-no-confidence-in-msimanga|title= ANC withdraws motion of no confidence in Msimanga|newspaper=EWN|access-date= 23 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 September 2018, he survived another motion of no confidence tabled by the ANC. The EFF abstained from voting. Ninety-five councillors voted against the motion, while seventy-seven voted for it. Twenty-one councillors abstained.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/tshwane-mayor-solly-msimanga-survives-motion-of-no-confidence-17248280|title= Tshwane Mayor Solly Msimanga survives motion of no confidence|newspaper=IOL|access-date= 23 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nMsimanga's last months as Mayor were overshadowed by the irregular awarding of a multi-billion-rand tender contract to GladAfrica by embattled City Manager Moeketsi Mosola.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.iol.co.za/pretoria-news/gladafrica-solly-msimanga-in-tight-spot-18188960|title= GladAfrica: Solly Msimanga in tight spot|newspaper= IOL|access-date= 26 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/exclusive-gladafrica-scandal-mosola-quietly-concedes-tender-was-irregular-says-official-20190125|title= EXCLUSIVE: GladAfrica scandal - Mosola quietly concedes tender was irregular, says official|newspaper= News24|access-date= 26 March 2019}}</ref> Msimanga tried to suspend Mosola<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/politics/2018-08-22-tshwanes-city-manager-given-notice-to-suspend-over-gladafrica-tender/ |title=Tshwane\u2019s city manager given notice to suspend over GladAfrica tender|newspaper= BusinessLIVE|access-date= 26 March 2019}}</ref>, and the DA caucus of the Tshwane City Council attempted multiple times to remove Mosola from the position.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/tshwane-council-issues-notice-of-intention-to-suspend-city-manager-20180822|title= Tshwane Council issues notice of intention to suspend city manager|newspaper= News24|access-date= 26 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.enca.com/news/da-motion-suspend-mosola-fails|title= DA motion to suspend Mosola fails|newspaper=eNCA|access-date= 26 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.sowetanlive.co.za/news/south-africa/2018-11-30-second-bid-to-remove-tshwane-city-manager-moeketsi-mosola-fails/|title= Second bid to remove Tshwane City manager Moeketsi Mosola fails|newspaper= SowetanLIVE}}</ref> Mosola announced in July 2019 that he would step down as the City Manager of Tshwane.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/national/2019-07-26-moeketsi-mosola-reaches-separation-agreement-with-city-of-tshwane/|title= Moeketsi Mosola reaches separation agreement with City of Tshwane|access-date=26 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 January 2019, Msimanga announced that he was stepping down as Mayor of Tshwane to focus on his Gauteng premiership campaign. He also said that his resignation would be finalised in the first two weeks of February.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/solly-msimanga-to-step-down-as-tshwane-mayor-20190118|title= Solly Msimanga to step down as Tshwane mayor|newspaper= News24|date=18 January 2019|access-date= 24 March 2019}}</ref> He later announced on 31 January 2019 that he would effectively resign on 11 February 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/politics/2074552/msimanga-resigns-as-mayor-but-tshwane-anc-wants-him-out-now/|title= Msimanga resigns as mayor but Tshwane ANC wants him out now|newspaper= TheCitizen|access-date= 24 March 2019}}</ref> He was succeeded by [[Stevens Mokgalapa]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/politics/2081597/das-stevens-mokgalapa-is-tshwanes-new-mayor/ |title=DA\u2019s Stevens Mokgalapa is Tshwane\u2019s new mayor|newspaper=TheCitizen|access-date=24 March 2019}}</ref> Msimanga was subsequently sworn in as a Member of the Gauteng Provincial Legislature.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://mg.co.za/article/2019-02-12-city-of-tshwane-lands-itself-a-new-da-mayor|title= City of Tshwane lands itself a new DA mayor|access-date= 24 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Gauteng premiership campaign===\nOn 19 August 2018, Msimanga was announced as the party's Gauteng Premier candidate for the upcoming 2019 general elections.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2018-08-19-solly-msimanga-named-as-das-candidate-for-gauteng-premier/|title= Solly Msimanga named as DA\u2019s candidate for Gauteng premier|newspaper= TimesLIVE|date= 19 August 2018|access-date=25 March 2019}}</ref> He defeated many prominent candidates for the nomination, such as Member of the Gauteng Provincial Legislature [[Makashule Gana]], Member of Parliament [[Ghaleb Cachalia]], and DA Party Spokesperson Refiloe Nt\u2019sheke.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.enca.com/news/da-picks-solly-msimanga-gauteng-premier|title= DA picks Solly Msimanga for Gauteng premier|newspaper= eNCA|date= 19 August 2018|access-date= 25 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 May 2019, the African National Congress narrowly retained their majority in the [[Gauteng Provincial Legislature]] with a total of 50.19% of the vote. The Democratic Alliance remained the official opposition, but lost three seats, giving them a total of twenty seats in the provincial legislature.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://mg.co.za/article/2019-05-11-analysis-anc-hangs-onto-gauteng-but-its-a-whole-new-political-world|title= ANC hangs onto Gauteng, but it\u2019s a whole new political world|access-date= 17 May 2019}}</ref> Msimanga was elected DA caucus leader on 17 May 2019 and officially assumed the post of Leader of the Opposition on 22 May 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.enca.com/news/livestream-da-announced-gauteng-provincial-leadership|title= LIVESTREAM: DA announces Gauteng legislature leadership|access-date= 17 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [https://www.pa.org.za/person/solly-tshepiso-msimanga/ People's Assembly profile]\n* [https://twitter.com/SollyMsimanga Profile] on [[Twitter]]\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Moodey]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Leader of the Opposition in the [[Gauteng Provincial Legislature]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-bef|before=Kgosientso Ramokgopa}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Mayor of Tshwane]]|years=2016\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Stevens Mokgalapa]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Michael Moriarty (politician)|Michael Moriarty]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Provincial Chairperson of the Gauteng Democratic Alliance]]|years=2014\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Michael Moriarty (politician)|Michael Moriarty]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Mayors of Pretoria and Tshwane}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Msimanga, Solly}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Democratic Alliance (South Africa) politicians]]\n[[Category:University of Pretoria alumni]]\n[[Category:Members of the Gauteng Provincial Legislature]]\n[[Category: Mayors of Pretoria]]\n", "name_user": "Lefcentreright", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEntry into politics:Delivering", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solly_Msimanga"}
{"title_page": "Ray Santos", "text_new": "{{For|the soap opera character|Ray Santos (Guiding Light)}}\n{{short description|American musician}}\n\n'''Raymond Santos''' (December 28, 1928 \u2013 October 17, 2019) was an American [[Grammy Award]]-winning Latin musician, composer, and educator. Santos has played and arranged for such artists as [[Noro Morales]], [[Machito]], [[Tito Rodriguez]], [[Eddie Palmieri]], and [[Tito Puente]] among many others. He was nicknamed '''El Maestro'''.<ref name=\"BilboardObit\"/>\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nRay Santos was born in [[East Harlem]] in [[New York City|New York]] on December 28, 1928. His mother was a doll maker and his father was a doorman. They were born in Puerto Rico. When Santos was thirteen, the family moved to [[The Bronx]]. As a child, Santos heard [[Machito and his Afro-Cuban boys]] and [[Charlie Parker]]'s music, which inspired him to pursue a career in music. He played [[tenor sax]] while in high school at [[Haaren High School]].<ref>Slotnik, Daniel E. [https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/23/arts/music/ray-santos-dead.html \"Ray Santos, a Pillar of Latin Jazz, Is Dead at 90\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', October 23, 2019. Accessed October 23, 2019. </ref> Santos attended [[Juilliard School]] and graduated in 1952.<ref name=\"BilboardObit\">{{cite web |last1=Cobo |first1=Leila |title=Latin Music Maestro Ray Santos Dies at 90 |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8533458/ray-santos-dead-latin-music-maestro-dies |website=Billboard |publisher=Prometheus Global Media |accessdate=October 21, 2019 |date=October 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career== \n\nSantos started his career in music playing Latin-inspired big band music in the 1950s. He played with bands in the [[Catskills]] and at the [[Palladium (New York City)|Palladium]] in New York City.\n \nSantos served as music consultant and arranger for the soundtrack of the motion picture ''[[The Mambo Kings]]''. He arranged the Oscar-nominated song ''Beautiful Maria of My Soul''. He arranged and directed the orchestra for [[Linda Ronstadt]]'s ''[[Frenes\u00ed (album)|Frenes\u00ed]]'' album, for which he won a Grammy.<ref name=\"BilboardObit\"/>\n\nHe was inducted into the [[International Latin Music Hall of Fame]] in 2003 and received the [[Latin Grammy Trustees Award]] in 2011.<ref>{{cite news|title=International Latin Music Hall of Fame announces inductees for 2003|url=http://top40-charts.com/news.php?nid=4656|accessdate=31 October 2015|date=3 March 2003}}</ref><ref name=\"2011recipients\">{{cite web|last=Salomon|first=Gisela|title=Arroyo, Costa, Lora y Les Luthiers honrados por Academia Latina|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160225022114/http://entretenimiento.terra.com/awards-central/arroyo-costa-lora-y-les-luthiers-honrados-por-academia-latina,cafadee78d883310VgnVCM4000009bf154d0RCRD.html|archivedate=February 25, 2016|url=http://entretenimiento.terra.com/awards-central/arroyo-costa-lora-y-les-luthiers-honrados-por-academia-latina,cafadee78d883310VgnVCM4000009bf154d0RCRD.html|website=Terra Networks|accessdate=February 19, 2016|date=November 9, 2011|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nSantos taught at the [[City College of New York]] for over 20 years, directing the Latin Band. He retired from City College in December 2013 at the age of 84.<ref name=\"BilboardObit\"/>\n\nIn 2016, Santos received an honorary doctorate of music from Berklee College of Music.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jazztimes.com/features/tributes-and-obituaries/ray-santos-1928-2019/|title=Ray Santos 1928-2019|last=West|first=Michael J.|website=JazzTimes|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> \n\nSantos arranged [[Jon Secada]]'s album ''To Beny Mor\u00e9 With Love''.<ref name=\"BilboardObit\"/> In 2018, Santos contributed arrangements to [[Eddie Palmieri]]'s ''Mi Luz Mayor'' album. \n\nHe died on October 17, 2019 at age 90.<ref name=\"BilboardObit\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{findagrave|204414801}}\n* {{Discogs artist|Ray Santos}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Santos, Ray}}\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male musicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century saxophonists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century saxophonists]]\n[[Category:American jazz music arrangers]]\n[[Category:American musicians of Puerto Rican descent]]\n[[Category:American saxophonists]]\n[[Category:American male saxophonists]]\n[[Category:City College of New York faculty]]\n[[Category:Haaren High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Juilliard School alumni]]\n[[Category:Latin jazz saxophonists]]\n[[Category:Latin music composers]]\n[[Category:Musicians from New York City]]\n[[Category:People from East Harlem]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the soap opera character|Ray Santos (Guiding Light)}}\n{{short description|American musician}}\n\n'''Raymond Santos''' (December 28, 1928 \u2013 October 17, 2019) was an American [[Grammy Award]]-winning Latin musician, composer, and educator. Santos has played and arranged for such artists as [[Noro Morales]], [[Machito]], [[Tito Rodriguez]], [[Eddie Palmieri]], and [[Tito Puente]] among many others. He was nicknamed '''El Maestro'''.<ref name=\"BilboardObit\"/>\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nRay Santos was born in [[East Harlem]] in [[New York City|New York]] on December 28, 1928. His mother was a doll maker and his father was a doorman. They were born in Puerto Rico. When Santos was thirteen, the family moved to [[The Bronx]]. As a child, Santos heard [[Machito and his Afro-Cuban boys]] and [[Charlie Parker]]'s music, which inspired him to pursue a career in music. He played [[tenor sax]] while in high school at [[Haaren High School]].<ref>Slotnik, Daniel E. [https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/23/arts/music/ray-santos-dead.html \"Ray Santos, a Pillar of Latin Jazz, Is Dead at 90\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', October 23, 2019. Accessed October 23, 2019. </ref> Santos attended [[Juilliard School]] and graduated in 1952.<ref name=\"BilboardObit\">{{cite web |last1=Cobo |first1=Leila |title=Latin Music Maestro Ray Santos Dies at 90 |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8533458/ray-santos-dead-latin-music-maestro-dies |website=Billboard |publisher=Prometheus Global Media |accessdate=October 21, 2019 |date=October 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career== \n\nSantos started his career in music playing Latin-inspired big band music in the 1950s. He played with bands in the [[Catskills]] and at the [[Palladium (New York City)|Palladium]] in New York City.\n \nSantos served as music consultant and arranger for the soundtrack of the motion picture ''[[The Mambo Kings]]''. He arranged the Oscar-nominated song ''Beautiful Maria of My Soul''. He arranged and directed the orchestra for [[Linda Ronstadt]]'s ''[[Frenes\u00ed (album)|Frenes\u00ed]]'' album, for which he won a Grammy.<ref name=\"BilboardObit\"/>\n\nHe was inducted into the [[International Latin Music Hall of Fame]] in 2003 and received the [[Latin Grammy Trustees Award]] in 2011.<ref>{{cite news|title=International Latin Music Hall of Fame announces inductees for 2003|url=http://top40-charts.com/news.php?nid=4656|accessdate=31 October 2015|date=3 March 2003}}</ref><ref name=\"2011recipients\">{{cite web|last=Salomon|first=Gisela|title=Arroyo, Costa, Lora y Les Luthiers honrados por Academia Latina|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160225022114/http://entretenimiento.terra.com/awards-central/arroyo-costa-lora-y-les-luthiers-honrados-por-academia-latina,cafadee78d883310VgnVCM4000009bf154d0RCRD.html|archivedate=February 25, 2016|url=http://entretenimiento.terra.com/awards-central/arroyo-costa-lora-y-les-luthiers-honrados-por-academia-latina,cafadee78d883310VgnVCM4000009bf154d0RCRD.html|website=Terra Networks|accessdate=February 19, 2016|date=November 9, 2011|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nSantos taught at the [[City College of New York]] for over 20 years, directing the Latin Band. He retired from City College in December 2013 at the age of 84.<ref name=\"BilboardObit\"/> \n\nSantos arranged [[Jon Secada]]'s album ''To Beny Mor\u00e9 With Love''.<ref name=\"BilboardObit\"/> In 2018, Santos contributed arrangements to [[Eddie Palmieri]]'s ''Mi Luz Mayor'' album. \n\nHe died on October 17, 2019 at age 90.<ref name=\"BilboardObit\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{findagrave|204414801}}\n* {{Discogs artist|Ray Santos}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Santos, Ray}}\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male musicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century saxophonists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century saxophonists]]\n[[Category:American jazz music arrangers]]\n[[Category:American musicians of Puerto Rican descent]]\n[[Category:American saxophonists]]\n[[Category:American male saxophonists]]\n[[Category:City College of New York faculty]]\n[[Category:Haaren High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Juilliard School alumni]]\n[[Category:Latin jazz saxophonists]]\n[[Category:Latin music composers]]\n[[Category:Musicians from New York City]]\n[[Category:People from East Harlem]]\n", "name_user": "BCMBCBOP", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added honorary degree from Berklee College of Music", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ray_Santos"}
{"title_page": "2019\u201320 UC Irvine Anteaters men's basketball team", "text_new": "{{short description|American college basketball season}}\n{{Infobox NCAA team season\n| sport = basketball\n| year = 2019\u201320\n| prev_year = 2018\u201319\n| next_year = 2020\u201321\n| team = UC Irvine Anteaters\n| logo = UC Irvine Anteaters logo.svg\n| logo_size = 100\n| conference = Big West Conference\n| short_conf = Big West\n| CoachRank = \n| APRank = \n| record = 21\u201311\n| conf_record = 13\u20133\n| wins_vacated = \n| ties_forfeited =\n| wins_forfeited = \n| conf_wins_vacated = \n| conf_wins_forfeited = \n| head_coach = [[Russell Turner (basketball)|Russell Turner]]\n| hc_year = 10th\n| asst_coach1 = [[Blaine Taylor]]\n| ac1_year = \n| asst_coach2 = Ryan Badrtalei\n| ac2_year = \n| asst_coach3 = Michael Wilder\n| ac3_year = \n| mvp = \n| mvp_year = \n| mvp2 = \n| mvp2_year = \n| captain = \n| captain_year = \n| captain2 = \n| captain2_year = \n| captain3 = \n| captain3_year = \n| captain4 = \n| captain4_year = \n| arena = [[Bren Events Center]]<br>(Capacity: 5,000)\n| champion = Big West regular season champions\n| tourney = \n| tourney_result = \n}}\n{{2019\u201320 Big West men's basketball standings}}\nThe '''2019\u201320 UC Irvine Anteaters men's basketball team''' represented the [[University of California, Irvine]] in the [[2019\u201320 NCAA Division I men's basketball season]]. The Anteaters were led by tenth-year head coach [[Russell Turner (basketball)|Russell Turner]] competing in the [[Bren Events Center]]. UC Irvine is a member of the [[Big West Conference]]. The team won their 2nd straight Big West Regular Season title before the [[2020 Big West Conference Men's Basketball Tournament]] and subsequently, the remainder of the [[2019\u201320 NCAA Division I men's basketball season]] and postseason tournaments were canceled as a result of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|COVID-19 Pandemic]]. The team finished 21-11, and has won at least a share of 3 of the last 4 Big West Regular season titles. The program has won at least 20 games in 7 of the last 8 seasons. Turner became the winningest coach in program history on Jan 15 surpassing [[Pat Douglass]] total of 197 wins and won his 4th Big West Coach of the Year Award. Evan Leonard, Eyassu Worku, and Tommy Rutherford all recorded their 1000th point during the season, the first time the program has had 3 players score 1,000 career points in the same season. The team was 12th in the nation in FG % defense holding opponents to (38.8%) shooting, 11th in total rebounds (1,269), 3rd in rebounding margin (+9.4). Brad Greene pulled a Bren Events Center record 21 rebounds on Jan. 11 vs Hawai'i. <ref>{{cite web |title=2019-20 MEN'S BASKETBALL SEASON REVIEW  |url=https://ucirvinesports.com/news/2020/3/30/2019-20-mens-basketball-season-review.aspx |publisher=[[University of California, Irvine]] |accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Previous season==\n{{See also|2018\u201319 UC Irvine Anteaters men's basketball team}}\n\nThe Anteaters finished the season a program best 31\u20136 overall, and 15\u20131 in the conference and recorded their first ever NCAA Tournament win over [[2018\u201319 Kansas State Wildcats men's basketball team|Kansas State]] in the South Region 1st Round before falling to [[2018\u201319 Oregon Ducks men's basketball team|Oregon]] in the 2nd Round.<ref>{{cite web |title=Historic Season Comes to an End in NCAA Round of 32  |url=https://ucirvinesports.com/news/2019/3/24/mens-basketball-eaters-historic-season-comes-to-an-end-in-ncaa-round-of-32.aspx |publisher=[[University of California, Irvine]] |accessdate=25 March 2019}}</ref> During the season, the Anteaters participated in the 2019 [[Gulf Coast Showcase]], which was held in [[Estero, Florida]], where they were runner-ups defeating [[2018\u201319 UTSA Roadrunners men's basketball team|UTSA]] and [[2018\u201319 Tulane Green Wave men's basketball team|Tulane]] before losing to [[2018\u201319 Toledo Rockets men's basketball team|Toledo]]. Prior to the season, the Anteaters competed in the 2018 [[Asia-Pacific University Basketball Challenge]], hosted by the [[Korea Basketball Association|KBA]] and [[Yonsei University]] where they were also runner-ups. <ref>{{cite web |title=UCI FALLS TO RUSSIA, 92-91, AT THE ASIA PACIFIC UNIVERSITY CHALLENGE  |url=https://ucirvinesports.com/news/2018/8/12/mens-basketball-uci-falls-to-russia-92-91-at-the-asia-pacific-university-challenge.aspx?path=mbball |publisher=[[University of California, Irvine]] |accessdate=25 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Roster==\n\n{{CBB roster/Header|year=2019|team=UC Irvine Anteaters|teamcolors=y|sex=M|high_school=y}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=JC|last=Butler|dab=|num=0|pos=F|ft=6|in=5|lbs=200|class=So|rs=|cur_rs=|home=[[Racine, Wisconsin]]|high_school=[[Prairie School]]|note=W}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=Devin|last=Cole|dab=|num=1|pos=G|ft=5|in=11|lbs=175|class=FR|rs=y|cur_rs=|home=[[Ventura, California]]|high_school=[[Buena High School (California)|Buena High School]]|note=W}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=Justin|last=Hohn|dab=|num=2|pos=G|ft=6|in=1|lbs=175|class=FR|rs=|cur_rs=|home=[[Sioux Falls, South Dakota]]|high_school=[[Tea Area High School|Tea High]]}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=Aiden|last=Krause|dab=|num=4|pos=G|ft=6|in=4|lbs=198|class=FR|rs=y|cur_rs=|home=[[Mackay, Queensland|Mackay, QLD, Australia]]|high_school=[[Australian Institute of Sport]]}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=Isaiah|last=Lee|dab=|num=5|pos=G|ft=6|in=2|lbs=190|class=FR|rs=|cur_rs=|home=[[Sydney|Sydney, NSW, Australia]]|high_school=[[Australian Institute of Sport]]}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=Ofure|last=Ujadughele|dab=|num=10|pos=G|ft=6|in=3|lbs=210|class=FR|rs=|cur_rs=|home=[[Chino Hills, California]]|high_school=[[Chino Hills High School]]}}\n{{CBB roster/Player|first=John|last=Edgar Jr.|dab=|num=11|pos=F|ft=6|in=5|lbs=215|class=SR|rs=|cur_rs=|home=[[Chino Hills, California]]|high_school=[[Ruben S. Ayala High School|Ayala High School]]}}\n{{CBB 